<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--ApplesandOranges     11-17 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Apples and Oranges,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>OJ Sales Up While Apple Juice Plunges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who stopped buying apple juice
because of the Alar chemical scare apparently are buying more
orange juice, according to a national survey.
   Apple juice sales were down 14 percent to 146 million gallons in
American supermarkets in the first nine months of 1989, a spokesman
for A.C. Nielsen Co. told the Florida Citrus Commission on
Wednesday. The drop in revenue was 9 percent to $430 million over
the same period a year ago.
   By contrast, supermarket orange juice sales in the same period
were up 5 percent to 512 million gallons and up 7 percent in value
to $1.9 billion, said Mike Miller, a Nielsen vice president.
   Alar is the trade name for a spray that keeps apples red and
fresh longer. A widely publicized consumer report in February
linked Alar to a long-term health threat. The spray is not used on
citrus.
   Apple growers have dropped use of the chemical, and federal
health officials have tried to reassure consumers about the safety
of apples.
</TEXT>
