<FIRST>r w PM-D'Amato-HUD     11-17 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-D'Amato-HUD,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Ethics Committee Looking Into HUD Allegation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Ethics Committee is reviewing
allegations that Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato, R-N.Y., violated rules in
the Department of Housing and Urban development scandal, a source
says, but there is no indication of a formal investigation.
   The ethics panel can check into allegations at an early stage
before even starting a preliminary inquiry, said the source,
speaking Thursday on condition of anonymity.
   When a complaint is filed _ one was submitted by the senator's
former opponent _ the staff begins to look into the allegations.
The Ethics Committee then must decide whether to proceed to the
first formal stage, a preliminary inquiry.
   D'Amato's spokeswoman, Zenia Mucha, said in New York, ``We
haven't been told anything'' about the inquiry, which was first
reported on the CBS Evening News.
   Referring to the CBS report, she said: ``That doesn't mean
squat. They're obligated under the law to investigate anything
that's filed with the ethics committee.''
   The New York Times said in today's editions the committee had
decided to hire prominent Washington attorney Robert S. Bennett for
the D'Amato case and for another investigation of the involvement
of five senators with a failing savings and loan.
   Bennett earlier this year was selected by the committee to
investigate accusations that Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn.,
laundered $100,000 in campaign contributions through a book
contract.
   Last summer Mark Green, who ran against D'Amato in 1986, filed a
complaint against him with the Senate Ethics Committee, saying
there was ``substantial evidence'' that D'Amato broke Senate rules
and federal law. Green cited news reports of D'Amato's involvement
in the Wedtech scandal and influence-peddling at the Department of
Housing and Urban Development.
   D'Amato reportedly has been involved in lobbying HUD on behalf
of projects in New York and Puerto Rico, including winning a $1
million government grant to build a swimming pool in Island Park,
N.Y., a middle-class beachfront community. The village since has
decided to kill that project and give back the money.
   Green's complaint also cited other alleged improprieties going
back to the early 1970s, but D'Amato denounced Green's complaint as
politically motivated.
   A figure in the Wedtech case testified in court that he made an
illegal $30,000 contribution to D'Amato's re-election campaign, but
the senator denied it.
   Green, who has said in the past that the committee confirmed to
him receipt of his complaint, said Thursday night, ``I have gotten
no official notice from the committee whatsoever.''
</TEXT>
