<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WeaponsPlants     11-17 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weapons Plants,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auditors Question Practice of Reimbursing Contractors for Fines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department's practice of paying all
fines incurred by private companies that run its nuclear weapons
plants is undermining efforts to improve environmental conditions
at the sites, federal auditors said today.
   In a report to Congress, the General Accounting Office said the
department shields the contractors from all financial liability for
violations of state and federal environmental laws. Even the
companies' related legal bills are paid.
   By contrast, the Defense Department makes its contractors pay
such fines, the auditors said.
   ``If DOE continues its current policy and practice ... we
believe DOE will reduce contractors' incentives to comply'' with
hazardous waste regulations ``and may negate the benefits'' of the
Environmental Protection Agency's efforts to enforce its rules at
these federal facilities, the audit report concluded.
   Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, said the report highlighted a serious
flaw in Energy Department policy.
   ``DOE has disavowed a vital tool for ensuring that its weapons
plants comply with the environmental laws _ the basic premise that
the polluter pays,'' Luken said.
   Luken is chairman of the House Energy subcommittee on
transportation and hazardous materials, which was holding a hearing
today on the GAO report and a bill sponsored by Rep. Ron Wyden,
D-Ore., that would prohibit the government from reimbursing
contractors if they are at fault for drawing environmental fines or
penalties.
   The department's inspector general earlier this year reported on
the practice of reimbursing contractors for their fines, and the
department has told Congress it is considering changing the
contracts to limit such reimbursements.
   The GAO report said the Energy Department's policy is legally
permissible and is rooted in the unusual circumstances surrounding
the origin of the nuclear weapons program. The government felt it
had to offer such financial protection to attract the expertise it
needed to develop the atomic bomb during World War II.
   Today's weapons are made at plants built during and shortly
after the war. The facilities' age, combined with the government's
failure to modernize their waste management, has led to widespread
violation of environmental protection regulations.
   The report said that since 1983, the EPA and various states have
assessed penalties in six cases against Energy Department
contractors for violations of laws governing the handling of
hazardous wastes. Four of those cases are unresolved.
   In the two other cases, settlement agreements were reached in
which payments totaling $295,000 were assessed against the
contractors. The Energy Department paid the fines in full, plus
$528,639 in related legal costs of the contractors.
   The contractors in these cases were not identified.
   In a related development, a special team of inspectors said in a
report released Thursday that workers at the Y-12 nuclear weapons
plant in Oak Ridge, Tenn., are not adequately protected from
exposure to radiation.
   Among the major flaws in the radiation protection system are a
failure of the plant's health physics specialists to routinely
check radiation levels in all areas where significant amounts of
radiation are generated, the report said.
   In response to the report, which was sent to Energy Secretary
James D. Watkins late last month, Watkins ordered Undersecretary
John Tuck to develop a plan to correct the radiation protection
problems and other safety and environmental flaws identified by the
team of private and government inspectors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
