<FIRST>r w PM-VaughnWalker     11-17 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vaughn Walker,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Breaks Deadlock on California Judicial Nomination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   San Francisco attorney Vaughn R. Walker, whose
nomination as a federal judge languished for almost two years,
appears headed for confirmation after approval by the Senate
Judiciary Committee.
   ``After sweeping aside all the mudslinging, the committee
latched onto the truth and overwhelmingly indicated its belief that
Vaughn Walker is qualified to serve on the federal bench,'' Sen.
Pete Wilson, R-Calif., said Thursday after the panel approved the
nomination, 11-2.
   The nomination goes to the full Senate for final action, with
lawmakers scrambling to clear away they last of the nominations
before a planned pre-Thanksgiving adjournment for the year.
   As the committee pushed to wrap up its work, it also approved
and sent to the full Senate seven other judicial nominations,
including that of John M. Walker of New York, a cousin of President
Bush.
   John Walker _ no relation to Vaughn Walker _ is a U.S. district
judge in New York. He has been nominated for a vacancy on the 2nd
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Controversy surrounding Vaughn Walker concerned his 15-year
membership in the Olympic Club of San Francisco, which had no black
members until last year and still excludes women. He resigned Feb.
15 but critics said the move came too late and questioned his claim
to have opposed the exclusion of women.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., told the panel the resignation
and evidence of strenuous opposition to discrimination amounted to
``nothing more than a cynical effort to get himself confirmed.'' He
was joined by Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., in opposing the nomination.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., asked the committee in February to
reject Walker because of the club issue. Neither he nor Wilson is a
member of the panel, but the wishes of home-state senators in such
cases often carry weight.
   It has been many years, however, since a home-state senator's
``blue slip,'' as lawmakers call it, would automatically stop a
nomination cold.
   ``I haven't found enough in the record to cause me to vote
against his nomination,'' said Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio.
   He said he had spent more time studying the nomination than any
other and added that in rejecting a nominee, ``we are indeed
placing a blot on that individual's record for the rest of his or
her life.''
   ``Frankly, I think that Vaughn Walker did far less than he
should have done or could have done,'' Metzenbaum said. But he
added: ``Frankly, I haven't found enough in the record to vote
against his nomination.''
   Presidential cousin John Walker had been opposed for the appeals
bench by Harvard law Professor Alan Dershowitz, who said the
nomination represented a violation of the nation's anti-nepotism
law. But no opponents surfaced on the Judiciary Committee.
   Also recommended by the committee were U.S. District Court
nominees Edwin L. Nelson of Alabama, G. Thomas Van Bebber of
Kansas, Susan Webber Wright of Arkansas, Edward W. Nottingham of
Colorado, Arthur D. Spatt of New York and Edward J. Lodge of Idaho.
   The panel approved the nominations as U.S. attorneys of Joyce J.
George of Ohio, Jean Paul Bradshaw of Missouri, Timothy D. Leonard
of Oklahoma and Gene W. Shepard of Iowa. It endorsed Cindy Shinga
Daub of Nebraska as a commissioner of the Copyright Royalty
Tribunal. She is the wife of former Rep. Hal Daub, R-Neb.
</TEXT>
