<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-StelloNomination     11-17 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stello Nomination,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outlook for Quick Stello Confirmation Appears Bleak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's chances of winning
quick confirmation of Victor Stello Jr. as chief of nuclear weapons
production appear lost.
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins, in an unusual personal plea
to the Senate Armed Services Committee, said the administration
wanted Stello confirmed before Congress starts its two-month
recess, probably next week.
   But Thursday, after two days of hearings on Stello's fitness for
the post, the committee acknowledged it was unsure how and when to
act on the nomination.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the panel chairman, said the 20-member
committee would meet in closed session this afternoon to consider
its next step. He said one option was to bring Stello back to
supplement the testimony he delivered Wednesday.
   Watkins told the committee Wednesday that he urgently needed a
confirmed assistant secretary for defense programs to carry out the
reforms needed to get the weapons production complex in full
operation again. Key elements of the complex have been shut down in
recent months for safety reasons.
   Stello, the chief of staff of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission,
is accused by opponents of being lax on nuclear safety matters. He
has stoutly denied that and contended he's fully qualified for the
weapons post.
   ``Mr. Stello should not be in this kind of position of
responsibility,'' Rep. Peter Kostmayer, D-Pa., told Nunn's
committee Thursday. Kostmayer is chairman of a House Interior
investigations subcommittee that held hearings earlier this year on
Stello's NRC activities.
   At least two committee members, Democratic Sens. Timothy Wirth
of Colorado and Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts, oppose the
nomination, and Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, has strongly hinted that
he believes Stello is ill-suited for the post.
   Wirth took the lead during the first two days of hearings in
seeking to draw out details of numerous allegations of professional
misconduct and poor judgment by Stello during his tenure at the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission, which regulates commercial nuclear
power.
   Wirth's questioning of opposition witnesses Thursday prompted
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., to accuse the panel's Democratic
majority of using stalling tactics to scuttle the nomination.
   ``This is becoming hauntingly familiar to me,'' McCain said
later, referring directly to the committee's lengthy confirmation
hearing on John Tower as President Bush's nominee for defense
secretary. The panel voted not to recommend Tower's confirmation,
and he was rejected by the Senate in March.
   ``I am very sorry to see it happen again to a candidate of
proven qualifications,'' McCain said, adding that he believed it
was ``pretty predictable'' that the committee would not vote
favorably on Stello's nomination.
   McCain left the hearing and did not return.
   Two former chairmen of the NRC during Stello's tenure at the
agency, Lando Zech Jr. and Marcus Rowden, praised Stello and urged
his nomination be confirmed.
   ``I know him as a man of honor, integrity, competence,'' said
Zech, who retired in July after three years as NRC chairman. ``Adm.
Watkins is absolutely correct in the choice he has made.''
   Robert Pollard, a former NRC staffer who worked under Stello in
the 1970s, said he had no doubts about Stello's personal character
but that his record as a nuclear regulator showed he was willing to
put production goals ahead of safety concerns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
