<FIRST>r w PM-SouthAfrica-Arms     11-17 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Arms,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Government Denies Link With Illegal Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The South African government says it has no
connection with an alleged conspiracy to illegally ship missile
guidance equipment worth $50 million to its state-owned arms
company.
   Three South African businessmen and two Americans were indicted
Thursday as part of a U.S. Customs Service sting operation aimed at
stemming the illegal export of high-technology items and military
hardware.
   The five were accused of plotting to ship gyroscopes
manufactured by Northrop Corp. through Israel to Armscor, the South
African national arms company.
   Armscor, which stands for the Armaments Development and
Production Corp., makes more than 95 percent of the South African
military's weapons and sells to 32 countries.
   At a news conference, U.S. Attorney Jay Stephens said ``the
inference to be drawn'' is that Armscor ``either requested'' the
defendants to get the gyroscopes or that the arms brokers knew
Armscor would be an ``interested purchaser.''
   However, Patrick Evans, a spokesman at the South African Embassy
in Washington, said his country was ``well aware'' of the U.S. laws
and regulations, ``particularly in the field of the arms boycott,''
and would do nothing to circumvent them.
   ``The natural extension of that statement is that there is no
one in South Africa or its agencies who is involved in this
matter,'' Evans said.
   Stephens said the investigation was over.
   Congress, to encourage an end to apartheid, in 1986 prohibited
the export of a wide array of military items to South Africa.
   The conspirators had supplied material to the South Africans in
the past and the South African government is ``going to have a lot
of business flowing our way,'' one of the conspirators, Frank J.
Randazzo, 32, of Virginia, told the undercover agents, according to
an affidavit by a Customs agent.
   One of the South Africans charged, Symone Morris Behrmann, 32,
said that Israel Aircraft Industries, a state-owned concern, would
help obtain the gyroscopes for a price that would be ``very high,''
according to the affidavit.
   Behrmann reportedly met with the owner of IAI in Israel, the
affidavit added.
   The affidavit said the Israeli company contacted Northrop in
1988 and made a request for gyroscopes that ``is nearly identical''
to those sought by the five people charged.
   In addition to conspiracy, the five were indicted on charges of
violating the Arms Export Control Act and the Anti-Apartheid Act.
   In addition to Randazzo and Behrmann, those charged by a federal
grand jury were: Guy Perfezou, a South African resident and his
company, Perfezou Imports &amp; Exports Ltd. of Maraisburg in South
Africa; Lester George Buckingham Talbot, a South African resident;
and Maryanne E. Callaghan of Warwick, R.I. Behrmann lives in
Toronto. Behrmann, Perfezou and Randazzo also were accused of money
laundering.
   Behrmann, Callaghan and Randazzo have been arrested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
