<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Poland     11-17 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Poland,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negotiators Trying to Get Poland Aid Back on Track</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate and House negotiators are trying to get
a derailed $938 million three-year aid plan for Poland and Hungary
back on track before Solidarity leader Lech Walesa ends his U.S.
visit.
   The bill authorizing the aid funds hit a sudden snag Thursday
night after Republican senators complained that most of the
safeguards they had added to the measure to prevent misuse of the
money had been removed by Democratic staff members.
   One such amendment would terminate the program if the aid were
converted into military assistance to Nicaragua or Cuba.
   After hours of consultations, Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, halted Senate consideration of the measure,
reinstituted the chamber's original bill with the GOP amendments
intact and sent it to a formal conference with negotiators from
both chambers.
   Although Mitchell called for speedy action, the development will
delay final passage of the aid measure that Walesa has said will
give his country a badly needed boost as it attempts to build
democratic institutions and moves to a free-market economy. Walesa
leaves the United States on Monday.
   The Senate impasse developed hours after the House approved a
version of the measure authorizing $846.54 million for Poland and
$91.5 million for Hungary.
   The House added a $200 million standby trade credit insurance
program for Poland, a provision not included in the Senate-passed
bill.
   But when the measure was sent back to the Senate for approval,
Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the ranking GOP member of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, angrily objected.
   ``This measure was mutilated by Democratic staff members,''
Helms complained.
   ``Staff members of the majority party were allowed to rip apart
this bill. They hijacked this bill on the way to the House. Many of
the most worthy provisions have been eliminated.''
   Earlier, the House voted 372-47 to approve the measure.
   As approved by the House, the bill authorizes $200 million to
help Poland shore up the value of its currency, which has been
battered by inflation and creates a $240 million private enterprise
fund to bolster free-market reforms.
</TEXT>
