<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-17 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Share Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
Friday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange hit a fifth
straight record high.
   The dollar closed at 143.98 yen, up 0.13 yen from Thursday's
close of 143.85 yen. After opening at 144.17 yen, the currency
ranged between 143.95 yen and 144.25 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues added 87.40
points, or 0.24 percent, to close the week at 35,963.74. It gained
24.11 points Thursday.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's firmness to a
better-than-expected improvement in the U.S. trade deficit in
September.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Thursday that the nation's
trade deficit with the rest of the world fell to $7.9 billion, down
21 percent from $10.2 billion in August.
   ``After quickly digesting the trade news, the exchange market
moved slowly in the morning because of a lack of new incentives,''
said Kenichi Nakao, a dealer with the Mitsubishi Bank.
   Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told a news conference Friday
that Japanese monetary authorities are continuing to watch
developments in the foreign exchange market carefully, while
maintaining contact with other Group of Seven industrial nations.
   A strong dollar tends to boost the U.S. trade deficit by making
imports cheaper and pushing up the prices of American goods on
foreign markets.
   The Group of Seven is comprised of the United States, Japan,
Britain, France, West Grmany, Italy and Canada.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index rose following the
favorable reaction to the improvement in the U.S. trade balance.
Many market players had predicted a deficit of $8.9 billion.
   ``Investors actively sought shares over a broad range,'' said a
dealer with a major Japanese securities firm who spoke anonymously.
</TEXT>
