<FIRST>r a PM-ShamirSpeech     11-17 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shamir Speech,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite US Pressure, PLO Not Welcome at Peace Talks, Shamir Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY KINNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel will not accept the Palestine
Liberation Organization at Middle East peace talks, despite
pressure from the Bush administration, Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir told Jewish leaders.
   Shamir, speaking to a gathering of American Jewish groups on
Thursday, called the PLO a brutal terrorist organization ``totally
disqualified as a partner to peace.''
   ``On this issue, we have a difference of view with some of our
American friends,'' Shamir told the 3,300 representatives from the
Council of Jewish Federations, which includes some 200 Jewish
communities.
   Shamir met with former President Reagan in Cincinnati earlier in
the day and praised the ``understanding and support'' of the Reagan
administration. But he indicated disagreement with President Bush,
at least on the PLO question.
   ``There are legitimate differences between us,'' Shamir said.
``After all, it is only natural that the United States government
wants to see tranquility and peace in the Middle East, and regards
the ways and means to that end as secondary in importance.
   ``But, for Israel, every step towards that common objective is
fraught with risk. One blunder can be fatal. These differences
cannot, and will not, change the very solid friendship between our
nation. Israel is a loyal and dependable ally.''
   Outside the Cincinnati Convention Center, a small group of PLO
supporters carrying signs urged united peace talks. Earlier, Shamir
had been given a statement from a group of American Jews
criticizing him for his hard-line stand.
   ``Take back this message to the people of Israel: There is a
very high cost for your endless stalling,'' the letter said. ``We
who support Israel are deeply concerned that unless you make a
realistic commitment to pursue a political settlement, you will do
lasting damage to the State of Israel and to the Jewish people.''
   The letter was delivered by Michael Lerner, editor of Tikkun, an
Oakland, Calif.-based magazine of liberal Jewish thought. Lerner
said the statement was endorsed by a meeting of 900 Jewish
intellectuals last Sunday in San Francisco.
   Uri Dromi, a Los Angeles-based representative of the World
Zionist Organization, said presenting the letter to Shamir was an
embarrassment.
   ``It's unfair to twist Israel's arm by putting pressure on the
prime minister in this way,'' Dromi said. ``He is the elected prime
minister of Israel and we should support him.''
</TEXT>
