<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     11-17 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's presidential turkey will escape
the oven, but not the Frying Pan.
   The Frying Pan Park petting farm in Fairfax County, Va., that is.
   The 50-pound bird, donated by the National Turkey Federation,
dined on grains prepared by a chef at a hotel blocks from the White
House on the eve of today's presentation to President Bush at a
Rose Garden ceremony.
   The turkey and its understudy were two of about 15 to 20 birds
picked out of a flock raised in Detroit Lakes in northwest
Minnesota. They were isolated from 5,000 other turkeys so they
could be pampered in preparation for their ``photo opportunity''
with the president.
   ``This year we're expecting something that's just a little bit
different,'' said Eddie Aldrete, a spokesman for the turkey
federation in Washington. ``It will be a little more ceremonial
because the Bush family is very, very traditional, and they're big
turkey lovers.''
   The Bushes will donate the Broadbreasted White turkeys to the
Frying Pan Park, a petting farm which has horses, cows, pigs,
sheep, chickens, ducks, goats and peacocks _ but no turkeys yet.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GAYLORD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business stinks for Tom Boughner. But the
man who runs ``Skunkbusters'' wouldn't have it any other way.
   ``It started out kind of as a big joke,'' Boughner, a former
sheriff's deputy in Otsego County in northern Michigan, said of his
family business. ``We were having big problems with them here.''
   When Boughner found out the Department of Natural Resources
doesn't make skunk calls, he decided he would do it. At first he
picked up the skunks for free.
   ``It started more or less as a community service, helping people
who couldn't get help anywhere else,'' he said.
   In four years, Boughner estimates, he's removed as many as 100
skunks from beneath houses, inside barns and a variety of other
places. Once he evicted 17 skunks from the yard of a lawyer.
   Another time he had to shove _ from the front, of course _ a
skunk stuck in a basement window.
   He claims he has never been sprayed, although his traps
certainly have. Even so, he reserves a special pair of overalls and
an otter-skin hat for the task.
</TEXT>
