<FIRST>r w PM-Ethics-Frank     11-17 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethics-Frank,275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Panel To Delay Frank Probe Until Penthouse Interview Published</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ethics Committee will delay its
investigation of Rep. Barney Frank, who has admitted paying for the
services of a male prostitute, until early next year, according to
a published report.
   The panel is postponing its probe to allow members to see what
male prostitute Stephen Gobie told Penthouse magazine in an
interview scheduled to be published in February, committee sources
told the Washington Times in a story in today's editions.
   Frank, an admitted homosexual, has admitted paying Gobie $80 for
sex in 1985 and subsequently hiring him with personal money to
serve as a housekeeper and driver from July 1985 through August
1987.
   Gobie went public with the relationship this past August, and
has said the congressman knew he was running a prostitution ring
from Frank's Capitol Hill apartment. Gobie also has accused the
Massachusetts Democrat of engaging in sex in the House gymnasium.
Frank has denied the charges.
   Originally the ethics panel hoped to complete its investigation
of Frank by the end of the year, but news reports that Gobie plans
a ``graphic'' story in the sex-oriented Penthouse magazine have
changed some minds on the panel, the committee source told The
Times.
   Meanwhile, the Justice Department has begun a ``preliminary
investigation'' into Frank, law enforcement sources said.
   ``We are not yet investigating any possible illegal activities
on the part of Mr. Frank,'' said the Justice Department official,
who requested anonymity. ``We have opened a file; that's all I can
tell you.'' The file on Frank includes news reports and other
public documents about Frank's activities, the source said.
</TEXT>
