<DOCNO> AP891117-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SalvadorPriests-US Bjt   11-17 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador Priests-US, Bjt,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Clergy Press White House for Justice in Murders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM BUERKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. clergy decried the murder of six Jesuit priests in El
Salvador as an unspeakable atrocity, with the National Council of
Churches urging Congress to halt delivery of military aid to El
Salvador.
   ``We fear for the lives of our brothers,'' said the Rev. Joseph
Berra, a fellow member of the Roman Catholic order who knew the
victims and worked in San Salvador before moving to Texas in August.
   The Bush administration, readying a new shipment of arms to
confront a rebel offensive, said it will press for an
investigation, and congressmen are threatening cuts in military aid
unless the murderers are brought to justice.
   ``If the government does not bring to justice those responsible,
we would have no choice but to try to severely limit Salvadoran aid
next year,'' said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., chairman of the House
Appropriations subcommittee with jurisdiction over foreign aid.
   William Walker, U.S. ambassador to El Salvador, called the
slayings ``a barbaric act,'' and compared them to the 1980 killings
of three nuns and a laywoman. Five former Salvadoran national
guardsmen were convicted of those killings.
   ``It is obviously going to have a negative impact on the
government of El Salvador,'' Walker said.
   The Salvadoran government denied responsibility and condemned
the slayings as ``savage and irrational.'' President Alfredo
Cristiani said he had ordered an investigation.
   In Austin, Texas, Berra held a news conference with two other
Jesuits who also worked in San Salvador before coming to the
University of Texas.
   The Rev. Doug Marcouiller said fellow Jesuits in El Salvador
told him 30 armed, uniformed men carried out the killings.
   ``Their bodies were riddled with bullets, and their heads had
been smashed,'' he said. ``This while an attachment of 80 soldiers
was encamped about 100 yards away.''
   Marcouiller said the Jesuits had been denounced ``as sources of
subversion'' on Salvadoran radio and subjected to threats. The
Jesuits' house was bombed, but no one was killed.
   The extreme right, now in power, has for more than a decade
accused local Jesuits and their university of fostering subversive
ideology.
   The National Council of Churches' governing board, holding its
semiannual meeting in Pittsburgh, unanimously approved a resolution
urging the Bush administration to halt military aid to El Salvador
and do everything possible to end the 10-year-old civil war there.
   ``We certainly hope the action we have taken will help prevent
further atrocities happening there,'' said the Rev. Syngman Rhee,
installed Thursday night as the council's president-elect.
   The resolution also calls on El Salvador's government and rebel
forces to protect civilians and cooperate with humanitarian
agencies, and asks that churches and religious groups have
unrestricted access to endangered civilians.
   The council, America's largest ecumenical body comprising 32
denominations with a combined membership of 42 million Christians,
including most major Protestant denominations, also advised members
to be ready to provide emergency aid to churches in El Salvador.
   Seattle Roman Catholic Archbishop Raymond G. Hunthausen called
the killings ``an unspeakable atrocity,'' and urged an end to U.S.
military aid to El Salvador.
   About 75 people gathered near the Salvadoran consulate in
Chicago Thursday evening, some carrying white crosses bearing the
names of those killed, while the Rev. Raymond Baumhart, president
of Jesuit-run Loyola University, said the school was ``stunned'' by
the deaths.
   ``These are men who dedicated their lives to service of others;
they committed themselves to living and serving the poor and the
uneducated; they ministered to men and women who suffered the
effects of the war in San Salvador,'' Baumhart said. ``We pray that
they will not have died in vain.''
   Baumhart noted that one of the slain priests _ the Rev. Ignacio
Ellacuria, rector of Jose Simeon Canas Central American University
_ received an honorary doctorate from Loyola in 1986.
   The Rev. Thomas Schubeck, professor of religious studies at
Cleveland's Jesuit-run John Carroll University, interviewed
Ellacuria in April for a book on liberation theology. He said the
Jesuits' work on behalf of the poor made them targets for the right.
   ``They've removed a number of important educators, good thinkers
who stood for people,'' he said. ``It was a vengeful kind of
execution.''
   The dead included Ellacuria; university vice-rector Ignacio
Martin-Baro; the Revs. Segundo Montes, Amado Lopez, Juan Ramon
Moreno and Joaquin Lopez Lopez; their housekeeper, Julia Elba
Ramos, and her 15-year-old daughter Celina.
   Late Thursday, uniformed security officers raided a downtown
office of the Lutheran Church and arrested 12 foreigners, including
four U.S. citizens, who work with the church, said Michel Gagne, a
consular officer in the Canadian Embassy.
</TEXT>
