<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-17 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikkei Sets Another Record, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed
at a record high today for the fifth straight day, while the dollar
inched up against the yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which rose
24.11 points Thursday, added another 87.40 points, or 0.24 percent,
closing the week at 35,963.74.
   The dollar closed at 143.98 yen, up 0.13 yen from Thursday's
close of 143.85 yen. After opening at 144.17 yen, the U.S. currency
ranged between 143.95 and 144.25 yen.
   ``The dollar stayed in a narrow range, attracting generally
bullish sentiment in the market,'' said Shinji Tanaka, a dealer
with Mitsui Bank.
   A rumor that Japan's central bank would raise its official
discount rate resulted in some temporary dollar-selling pressure,
but the currency bounced back in the afternoon session as the rumor
proved to be groundless, Tanaka said.
   In the stock market, the Nikkei index continued to rise, with
investors buying a broad range of issues, securities dealers said.
   An estimated 900 million shares changed hands on the market's
first section, down from Thursday's 1.1 billion shares.
   During the past five trading days, the index has gained a total
of 300.54 points.
   ``A glut of money in Japan is contributing to the booming stock
market,'' said Masahiko Fujia, a stock analyst at Yamaichi
Securities, a major Japanese brokerage.
   Fujita said some of the surplus funds were flowing into the
stock market from the short-term money market, where interest rates
have been higher than in the long-term market in recent days and
are expected to possibly decline.
   The Tokyo market also was awaiting the release of the U.S.
wholesale price index for October, scheduled next Tuesday, he said.
</TEXT>
