<DOCNO> AP891117-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0617EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-West     11-17 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-West,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary, First in Eastern Europe, Asks to Join Council of Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary has become the first East
European country to apply for membership in the Council of Europe,
a Western European political organization.
   Yugoslavia and Poland also indicated they would apply.
   Hungary applied for membership Thursday. Foreign Minister Gyula
Horn said membership would provide ``a very good basis that will
enable us in the near future to enter into close cooperation with
the European Community.''
   The 12 nations belonging to the European Community trading bloc
also are members of the Council of Europe, but the organizations
are not formally linked.
   Horn, who met Thursday with foreign ministers attending a
regular meeting of the council in Strasbourg, said he hoped that
Hungary ``might even become a member of the European Community.''
   He said he expected his country to join the Council of Europe
``within six to nine months, or at all events in 1990.''
   Catherine Lalumiere, secretary-general of the 23-nation Council
of Europe, said if Hungary maintains its pace of political reform,
it could become the organization's first East European member in a
year or so.
   Set up in 1949, the Strasbourg-based council is particularly
active on the issues of human rights and legal and cultural
cooperation.
   Horn said membership would not be incompatible with Hungary's
position in the Warsaw Pact, the Soviet-led military alliance.
   ``We don't want to break away from that alliance or even want to
call our membership of that alliance into question,'' Horn said.
   Foreign Minister Budimir Loncar of Yugoslavia said he had
outlined his nation's reforms to the council.
   Asked if Belgrade planned to apply for membership next spring,
he replied, ``It will most likely be as you predict.''
   Poland's foreign minister, Krzysztof Skubiszewski, said,
``Poland has the intention to apply, but we did not file any formal
demand today.''
   He said it was difficult to say when Poland could seek
membership, addding,``I think it's too early for us to do it.''
   Membership is open only to European countries with democratic,
multiparty parliaments.
   Hungary plans multiparty elections for next year. In August,
Poland formed the East Bloc's first government led by a
non-Communist since they consolidated power in Eastern Europe after
World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891117-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Gorbachev     11-17 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev: Multiparty System Possible in Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev indicated in
remarks published today that multiparty government might someday
come to the Soviet Union, but he ruled out private ownership of
farms and factories.
   The Soviet leader rejected current calls for allowing political
parties other than the ruling Communist Party.
   The official news agency Tass quoted him as saying there was
``no other political force capable of both renewing the bodies of
Soviet power ... and consolidating society.''
   However, he also said any constitutional provision, including
the article giving the Communist Party the leading role in shaping
Soviet society, ``may be subjected to a reassessment,
transformation and editing, if the need arises, even to its
deletion from the constitution.''
   The East bloc has been swept by a wave of political reform this
year.
   Poland formed a government led by a non-Communist in August and
Hungary plans to switch to multiparty rule after elections next
year. East Germany and Bulgaria appear to be undertaking more
limited reforms.
   Gorbachev's remarks were made Wednesday during a
question-and-answer session that followed a speech to a national
forum of students. The speech was broadcast Wednesday night on
official media, and the question-and-answer session late Thursday.
   The president said he was open to ``a large variety of different
forms of running the economy which would, through lease,
cooperation, individual farms, etcetera, make the individual the
master'' with authority to manage the means of production.
   However, Gorbachev said that although many changes are possible
in the era of perestroika, he remained committed to the Marxist
concept that the state should own the means of production.
   He said he believed in the Communist Manifesto, which calls for
state ownership of production to ensure that workers get full value
for their effort without factory owners taking a share as profit.
   The Manifesto was written in 1848 by Karl Marx and Friedrich
Engels as the blueprint for communism.
   The Soviet legislature is currently debating bills to define
various forms of property, including proposals that would permit
private ownership of some property and long-term leasing of state
farms and industry.
   ``I do not think that at the stage of preparing a law on
property and ownership we should put forth and lay down the
advancement toward private property,'' Gorbachev told the students.
   Addressing international issues, Gorbachev said German
reunification was hardly realistic today, but ``as to how history
will turn out in the future, we will live and see.''
   Gorbachev and Soviet spokesmen have previously expressed strong
opposition to any possibility of reunification of East Germany and
West Germany.
   There has been speculation about reunification since East German
leaders opened their borders to the West earlier this month in
response to street protests for reform and the exodus of citizens
to the West.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891117-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0627EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     11-17 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Blankets Midwest; Temperatures Drop in East, South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell in the Midwest early today, hours after a powerful
storm system brought strong winds and heavy thunderstorms to the
Northeast.
   Violent storms Thursday caused widespread wind damage and
flooding in the Northeast and claimed the lives of seven children
when a wall collapsed on a school cafeteria near Newburgh, N.Y.
There were three other weather-related deaths Thursday in New
Jersey and New York.
   Storms knocked over trees and ripped roofs off houses in West
Virginia, caused flooding in Washington, D.C., blew the windows out
of skyscrapers in Philadelphia, destroyed a house in Piscataway,
N.J., and overturned cars and blew the roof off a shopping mall in
Quebec.
   There were reports of damage from strong thunderstorms and gusty
winds in eastern Virginia, Maryland, Delaware, New Jersey, eastern
Pennsylvania and eastern New York state. Winds gusted to 65 mph in
Baltimore, 76 mph in Lancaster, Pa., and 100 mph in Philadelphia.
   Tornadoes touched down at King of Prussia, Pa., Lakehurst, N.J.,
and Peekskill, N.Y.
   Temperatures dropped into the 20s and 30s throughout the Midwest
as snow fell in North Dakota, Ohio, Pennsylvania and Michigan
today. Rain out West dampened parts of Oregon and Washington.
   Colder weather also extended into the South, with temperatures
in north and middle Georgia dropping into into the 20s today.
Workers at homeless shelters across the state prepared for a busy
weekend.
   More than a foot of snow fell Thursday over parts of northeast
and south-central upper Michigan, including 14 inches at Marquette.
   Snow also fell Thursday evening over southeast Minnesota,
northern and western Wisconsin, Indiana, Kentucky, Tennessee,
northeast Alabama, western North Carolina, western Virginia, West
Virginia, Pennsylvania, and western New York.
   The high temperature for the nation Thursday was 90 degrees in
Miami and in California at Borrego Springs, Palm Springs and
Thermal.
