<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-USCommunists     11-17 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US Communists,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Communist Chief Hews to Moscow's Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The longtime leader of America's communists is
hewing to the party line on reforms in the Eastern bloc, portraying
them as harbingers of a stronger socialism.
   ``Socialism is going through a phase and there's some basic
changes in its nature,'' Gus Hall, 79, chief of the Communist Party
U.S.A. for 30 years, said Thursday. ``That doesn't mean socialism
is dead.''
   ``It's becoming what I would call people's socialism, socialism
in which the Communist Party is not the sole political leader and
the communist parties have to share power in building socialism,''
Hall said.
   The notion of communist power-sharing is as surprising coming
from Hall as from his counterparts in the East. Long rigid in his
ideology, Hall still expresses admiration for Joseph Stalin and
chafes at communist flirtations with private enterprise.
   But sudden and remarkable reforms have swept communist Eastern
Europe, culminating last week in East Germany's opening of the
Berlin Wall, which split communist East Berlin and democratic West
Berlin for 28 years.
   ``That's great,'' said Hall, who has supported Moscow's moves as
they ranged through the decades from crackdown to growing openness.
``I said long ago that the Berlin Wall will come down. ... I don't
think it's needed now.''
   In a telephone interview, he expressed views that diverged
sharply from his hard-line history, including support for free
elections in Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union. He predicted that
socialists would win them.
   ``It will result in loosening the so-called political monopoly
that the (communist) parties have had,'' he said. ``That was
necessary in the initial stages and in difficult periods of war.
But they're not necessary now and they haven't been for some time.
That's old habits.''
   Hall's view left one student of American communism unimpressed.
``Hall is obviously very upset with what's going on in the
socialist world,'' said Harvey Klehr, a political science professor
at Emory University in Atlanta.
   ``You can keep saying the communist system is reforming itself.
What's really happening is the people of those countries have
decided to abolish communism,'' said Klehr, a specialist in
American radicalism.
   ``That's tough for someone like Hall, who's been a communist all
his life, to accept _ that people who live under it can't tolerate
it.''
   During the communist scare of the early 1950s, Hall spent eight
years in federal prison at Leavenworth, Kan., for conspiring to
overthrow the government by force, a charge he rejects.
   He said the Communist Party U.S.A. has 20,000 members; Klehr
said 10,000 to 15,000 is probably closer.
</TEXT>
