<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-17 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher as Interest Rate Prospects Assessed, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was higher in calm European trading
this morning, with investors uncertain what direction U.S. interest
rates will take. Gold prices also were higher.
   Although traders said the dollar reacted positively Thursday to
a smaller-than-expected U.S. trade deficit in September, the
outlook for the currency was still unclear.
   ``There's no real trend,'' one analyst in Milan said.
   Traders in Frankfurt said the dollar's failure to rise
decisively underscored the market's preoccupation with interest
rates.
   Because of this, they said, today's release of U.S. housing
starts data also probably would have little impact.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.13 yen to close at 143.98 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 144.345 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Thursday:
   _1.84315 West German marks, up from 1.8375
   _1.6350 Swiss francs, up from 1.6290
   _6.3000 French francs, up from 6.2550
   _2.07945 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0750
   _1,356.50 Italian lire, up from 1,354.00
   _1.1685 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1700
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.57485 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5805 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $392.25 a troy ounce,
down from late Thursday's $393.00. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price of $393.85.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $393.00, up from $392.50 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.59 to close at a bid $392.21.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.65 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's $5.60.
