<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--HighSeasCollision     11-17 0132</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--High Seas Collision,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Crushes Fishing Boat, Four Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 538-foot oil tanker crushed a 90-foot
fishing boat outside Los Angeles Harbor, injuring four fishermen
and causing a small petroleum spill, a U.S. Coast Guard official
said today.
   The fishing vessel Shogun remained afloat despite the damage
from the tanker Antarctica about two miles offshore late Thursday
night, said Petty Officer Robert Beals.
   Lifeguards from Long Beach rescued the Shogun's four-member crew
and took them to a hospital, Beals said. He said he didn't know how
badly they were injured.
   The cause of the crash was under investigation. Both vessels
were thought to be based in Long Beach, Beals said.
   The accident caused a petroleum spill about 100 yards square
that was quickly contained, he said.
