<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0646EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-BoysKilled     11-17 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boys Killed,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigrant Community Angered By Police Slaying of Two Boys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INVER GROVE HEIGHTS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The shooting deaths of two
sixth-grade boys at the hands of a police officer has outraged
members of the Laotian immigrant community in this St. Paul suburb.
   Thia Yang and Basee Lor, both 13, were killed Wednesday by a
single blast from a 12-gauge shotgun fired by officer Kenneth
Murphy, said Mark Shields, superintendent of the state Bureau of
Criminal Apprehension.
   Shields said Murphy, 54, a 20-year-old veteran of the force,
mistook a screwdriver in the hands of one of the boys for a gun.
The boys had been pursued earlier in a stolen car, police said.
   ``Why would police shoot a young kid? Why didn't they just stop
him? Those questions weren't answered,'' said Sau Thao, a friend of
Thia Yang's family.
   ``Officer Murphy, fearing his life was in danger, discharged his
weapon,'' Shields said.
   Murphy was placed on paid administrative leave pending a grand
jury investigation, said Dakota County Attorney James Backstrom. A
special prosecutor will present the evidence, he said.
   ``My mom says she doesn't understand why they didn't just put in
him jail, why they had to kill him,'' said Blia Lor, 18-year-old
sister of Basee Lor. Her mother, who had been shot several times
while fleeing Laos, sobbed.
   ``She says why don't the police kill her instead,'' Blia Lor
said, speaking for her mother, who does not speak English.
   Minnesota has the second largest contingent of Laotians in the
United States, after California. The Hmong tribesmen began arriving
from Laos in 1975, at the close of the Vietnam war.
   Outraged Laotians have been calling Yang Vang, director of the
Lao Family Community of Minnesota, he said.
   ``They're calling because when they heard about police officer
using shotgun to kill the two kids. Members are very, very upset,''
Vang said.
   ``The officer is trained and knows how to deal with people and
he should have known how to deal with those kids not firing a
gun,'' said Ge Yang, coordinator of the Lao center's delinquency
prevention program.
   The shootings followed a brief chase by police responding to an
auto theft call, according to Shields. The pursuit continued after
the car went into a ditch and three boys fled on foot, he said.
   Murphy pursued the boys on foot through a field. He took cover
behind a hay wagon, identified himself as a police officer and
shouted at the boys, who fled. The officer saw Yang raise his hand
with what Murphy thought was a gun, Shields said.
   Murphy was about 30 yards away from Yang when he shot, and Lor
was about 15 feet behind and to the side of Yang, Shields said.
   The third boy, a 14-year-old, was arrested after the shooting,
authorities said.
</TEXT>
