<DOCNO> AP891117-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-DeathSquad     11-17 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Death Squad,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officer Tells of Anti-Apartheid Death Squad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white former police captain
has admitted leading a death squad that he says was responsible for
assassinating several anti-apartheid activists, a newspaper
reported today.
   National police headquarters denied the existence of any police
hit squads, but said the ``wild allegations'' would be investigated.
   Dirk Coetzee, who resigned from the force in 1986, told the
Afrikaans-language newspaper Free Weekly that he participated in a
police hit squad until August 1982 and described several killings
in great detail.
   Coetzee said he had kept in contact with the unit's members and
knew of further misdeeds committed after he left the group.
   Free Weekly said it interviewed Coetzee on the Indian Ocean
island of Mauritius after he left South Africa last week with his
family to start a new life.
   Coetzee said the death squads included former African National
Congress guerrillas who chose to work with police after they were
captured.
   A statement from police headquarters said, ``The minister of law
and order and the commissioner of police have repeatedly stated
that no so-called hit squads exist.''
   Top-ranking police officials and the attorney general of the
Orange Free State Province will investigate Coetzee's charges,
police said.
   But the statement added, ``It seems strange that Capt. Coetzee
... now makes these unfounded, untested and wild allegations from a
foreign country where he cannot be questioned to verify these
claims.''
   Police did acknowledge the previously secret unit made up of
blacks who formerly belonged to the ANC, the main black group
fighting to oust the white-led government. ``They provide the force
with valuable intelligence and also play a cardinal role in the
identification of ANC terrorists infiltrating South Africa,''
police said.
   Coetzee told the newspaper: ``I was the commander of the South
African Police's death squad. My men and I had to murder political
and security opponents of the police and the government.''
   ``I myself am guilty or at least an accomplice to several
murders,'' the newspaper quoted him as saying.
   Coetzee is the second former policeman recently to admit being
part of a death squad. Last month, a black former security
policeman on Death Row was reprieved the day before his scheduled
execution when he said he had killed black anti-apartheid attorney
Griffiths Mxenge in Durban in 1981.
   The former policeman, Butana Nofomela, said he had participated
in nine police killings of anti-apartheid activists.
   Nofomela was sentenced to hang for a murder-robbery of a farmer
which took place after he had left the force and had no apparent
political overtones.
   According to Free Weekly, Coetzee listed the Mxenge murder among
the acts committed by the squad to which he belonged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
