<SECOND>PM-US-El Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Members of Congress Threaten Cuts in Military Aid to El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs graf 7, She said, with two grafs to include Walker
quote.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military aid to El Salvador's government
will be stepped up in light of its war with leftist guerrillas, but
members of Congress are threatening future cuts unless the fighting
stops and the murderers of six priests are brought to justice.
   ``This is probably another case of right-wing death squad
activity,'' said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., referring to the brutal
torture and killing of six Jesuits at a university in San Salvador.
   ``If the government does not bring to justice those responsible,
we would have no choice but to try to severely limit Salvadoran aid
next year,'' added Obey, chairman of the House Appropriations
subcommittee with jurisdiction over foreign aid.
   ``There is brutality and murder on both sides,'' said Sen.
Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., Obey's Senate counterpart. ``The right
justifies it in the name of the Lord, the left justifies it in the
name of liberation, and the people die in the middle.
   ``In many ways, I feel like saying, `A pox on both your houses.'
If our aid means nothing, if our influence means nothing, everybody
has to understand that at some point ... we will leave,'' Leahy
said.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Thursday
that Ambassador William Walker was asking Salvadoran President
Alfredo Cristiani for ``a full inquiry into this horrendous act.''
Both the government and the military have denied involvement in the
killings of the priests and two housekeepers.
   ``We do not know who it was and that's one point I would like to
emphasize,'' Walker said today on ``CBS This Morning.''
   Ms. Tutwiler said the Salvadoran military has asked the United
States to speed up deliveries of munitions already purchased,
primarily light weaponry and riot control equipment, and that ``we
are moving to address their needs.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater later said an
investigation into the killings had already begun and added, ``We
will be watching this investigation closely.''
   On Capitol Hill, several lawmakers said the United States should
join in a Red Cross call for a 72-hour cease-fire to evacuate
civilians and the wounded. ``It would be a good first step,'' said
Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan.
   Congress is poised to send an additional $85 million in military
aid and $12 million for police training and equipment to El
Salvador for the current fiscal year, but the money has been held
up by unrelated disputes over other items in a $14.6 billion
foreign aid bill.
   Ms. Tutwiler said the United States is confident of the
Cristiani government's ability to defeat the guerrillas who began a
major offensive earlier this week.
   ``We believe the Salvadoran government is able to manage the
situation,'' she said.
</TEXT>
