<HEAD>Jaruzelski Names New Polish Ambassador to the Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Wojciech Jaruzelski has named a
longtime Communist Party official as ambassador to Moscow, the
official news agency PAP reported today.
   Stanislaw Ciosek, a former member of the party's ruling
Politburo and a member of its policy-making Central Committee,
handled trade union affairs for the previous Communist government
during Solidarity's first legal phase in 1980-81 and when the union
was banned after martial law.
   He lost his spot in the Politburo as well as his post as Central
Committee secretary at a party plenum in July.
   Ciosek is expected to take up his job in Moscow on Monday, four
days before the arrival of Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a
former Solidarity editor elected to lead the first non-communist
government in the East bloc on Aug. 24.
   Solidarity supporters in the government or legislature are
well-acquainted with Ciosek, who participated in round-table talks
this spring that resulted in the legalization of Solidarity in
April after a seven-year ban and partially free elections in June.
