<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     11-17 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosions Damage Homes of Lebanese Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bombs damaged the homes of two
legislators who defied a Christian leader and participated in
presidential elections aimed at solving Lebanon's political crisis,
police said today.
   Also today, the Central Bank stopped sending cash to banks and
government institutions in east Beirut and the Christian enclave to
the north. The move was seen as yet another attempt to pressure the
Christian leader, Gen. Michel Aoun, to drop his opposition to newly
elected President Rene Mouawad.
   No casualties were reported in the explosions Thursday night
outside the homes of deputies Michel Sassin, a Greek Orthodox, and
Farid Serhal, a Maronite Catholic, police said. But window glass
was shattered and doors blown out.
   Neither of the Christian parliamentarians was at his residence
at the time. Sassin is abroad, and Serhal is at his hometown of
Jezzine in south Lebanon.
   Similar explosions have damaged the homes of Christian deputies
Tarek Habshi, Elias Hrawi, Elias el-Khazen and August Bakhos as the
inter-Christian feud escalated in recent weeks.
   The explosions were another violation of a cease-fire that began
in September after six months of intense fighting in Beirut between
Christian forces and Syrian-backed Moslem militias that killed more
than 2,000 people.
   Christian legislators have not returned to the enclave to avoid
Aoun's wrath after they approved without his consent a peace plan
to settle the civil war during a special session in Saudi Arabia in
October.
   Mouawad was elected Nov. 5, one day after Aoun, head of an
interim Cabinet that had ruled Christian regions for 13 months,
declared he had disolved the 99-seat Parliament. But legislators
said the move was illegitimate because under the Constitution only
a president can dismiss the chamber.
   Aoun has insisted on a Syrian troop withdrawal from Lebanon
before the election of a president. He rejected the peace pact
reached in Saudi Arabia because it contained no fixed timetable for
a Syrian evacuation. Syria has 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a
1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   Mouawad designated Salim Hoss, a veteran Sunni Moslem
politician, to form a Cabinet of national reconciliation. Aoun has
threatened to cut ``the throats and tongues'' who defy his
rejection of Mouawad's election and the peace plan, and agree to
take part in Hoss' government.
   Central Bank governor Edmond Naim, a Maronite based in
Syrian-policed Moslem west Beirut, said in a statement he stopped
the cash flow to east Beirut to force Aoun to deposit tax revenues
collected in the Christian enclave.
   A source at Naim's office said Aoun has collected about $28
million ``in taxes and fees for public services'' in the past two
months but refused to deposit them at the Central Bank. However,
the move was also seen as an attempt to force Aoun to support the
new president.
</TEXT>
