<HEAD>Christmas Tree Comes to Rockefeller Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's beginning to look a lot like Thanksgiving _
the Christmas tree has arrived at Rockefeller Center.
   The tree, harbinger of Christmas and huge crowds at the
mid-Manhattan landmark, arrived today by special New York City
police escort from Montebello in Rockland County, where it had
lived peacefully for many years before getting the ax on Thursday.
   The Norway spruce's blue-green majesty awaits enhancement _ or
tarting up, depending on your taste _ with more than 20,000
electric lights. The lighting ceremony is scheduled for Dec. 4.
   This year's evergreen is 70 feet tall, shorter than the 75-foot
conifers of the past two years but a bit taller than the 68-foot
tree from 1986.
