<FIRST>r a PM-NavyStand-Down 1stLd-Writethru a0498 11-17 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy Stand-Down, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0498,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailors Spend Time on Safety</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf, `Navy Secretary...' to UPDATE
with Navy secretary's speech.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy boat was swamped as it returned to
base to participate in an unprecedented service-wide ``stand-down''
for safety. None of 10 sailors aboard was injured.
   The accident Thursday occurred as most of the Navy began two
days of safety exercises for its sailors around the world after 10
accidents in the past three weeks killed 10 people and injured at
least 71.
   The 36-foot Navy Seafox was swamped in stormy weather on the
nearby York River. A Virginia Institute of Marine Science vessel in
the area picked up the 10 sailors, who were not injured, said Lt.
Cmdr. Steve Burnett, an Atlantic Fleet spokesman in Norfolk.
   ``At no time was it a life-threatening situation,'' he said.
   For most of the Navy, whether in port or at sea, Thursday began
48 hours of drills, lectures, inspections and dialogue about the
service's job and how to do it safely.
   ``It gives us a chance to step back from the trees and see the
forest,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Mike John, another Atlantic Fleet
spokesman.
   Navy Secretary H. Lawrence Garrett III and Adm. Carlisle A.H.
Trost, chief of naval operations, on Tuesday ordered all Navy units
to complete 48 hours of safety work within 72 hours. Most Atlantic
Fleet units began the stand-down Thursday morning, though some
began Wednesday, Burnett said.
   Garrett defended the Navy's safety record in a speech in
Jacksonville, Fla., in spite of the string of accidents. He said
that although no common problem linked the accidents, the
stand-down would be a success simply because of the number of
people involved.
   ``It is the human error that we will allow them to reflect upon
during this time,'' Garrett told the Jacksonville Council of the
Navy League.
   On the guided missile cruiser USS Josephus Daniels, the seamen
were gathered in compartments going over the procedures for
everything from the handling of surface-to-air missiles to the
electrical safety checking of personal radios.
   Lt. j.g. Paul Ward, the ship's assistant damage control officer,
saw the stand-down as a good way to stress safety to all hands.
   ``Everyone here has to be a capable firefighter. When there is a
fire on board, you can't just run away. ... There is nowhere to
run,'' Ward said.
   Stand-downs are not unusual, but Capt. Ferguson Norton,
commander of the Naval Safety Center and the Navy's top safety
officer, said this is the first service-wide stand-down in memory.
   At the Oceana Naval Air Station near Norfolk, pilots and flight
crews of ``The Black Aces,'' Squadron VF-41, were going over their
F-14 Tomcats.
   ``After a while, you start equating safety with combat
readiness,'' Lt. Cmdr. Ken Heimgartner, the squadron commander,
said as he watched his young ground crew go over his aircraft.
``When you start seeing something unsafe, that's an indicator you
may not be combat ready.''
   At the Miramar Naval Air Station in San Diego, Rear Adm. Phil
Anselmo joined about 1,000 sailors in a walk around runways,
taxiways and aprons looking for potentially hazardous litter. They
found about 50 pounds, including industrial bolts and chunks of
epoxy.
</TEXT>
