<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-Fighting 2ndLd-Writethru   11-17 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Fighting, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0533,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers, Insurgents Battle After Bombs Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with British reporter shot and
wounded today in San Salvador. Pickup 10th pvs, `Fighting also...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government forces and leftist
insurgents fought into early today after warplanes bombed rebel
positions and the two sides battled block to block in the capital.
   By daylight, fighting had tapered off, and San Salvador woke to
its quietest morning since a rebel offensive began six days ago.
The latest casualties included a British journalist who was shot
and seriously wounded.
   The offensive _ the rebels' biggest in their 10-year-old war
with the U.S.-backed government _ has killed at least 800 people
and wounded 1,600 nationwide, according to hospitals and the
government.
   Although gunfire was heard throughout the night, it was mild
compared to the intensity of previous days. An overnight curfew
made it impossible to reach battle zones to assess the situation.
   U.S. Ambassador William Walker told The Associatd Press today
that the United States was prepared to offer protection to anyone
who would come forward with information about the massacre Thursday
of six Jesuit priests.
   Walker said he would contact officials at the Jesuit university
who have said two witnesses saw about 30 men in army uniforms enter
the priests' residence just before the shooting began.
   The entire capital seemed to be under fire Thursday. Air force
jets screamed overhead, followed by thundering explosions as bombs
dropped on rebel strongholds.
   Several hundred guerrillas descended overnight from the hills
above the northern neighborhood of Mejicanos to try to take control
of the main streets.
   That is where the British journalist, David Michael Blundy of
the Sunday Correspondent of London, was caught in a crossfire and
wounded early today. Blundy was shot in the right shoulder and
taken to Rosales Hospital, where he was listed in serious condition.
   In Soyapango on the eastern side of the city, the rebels
appeared to have backed down after intense house-to-house combat.
   Fighting also raged in northern Zacamil, a neighborhood the
rebels have held since Saturday.
   About 1,500 guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front are thought to be involved in the attack in San
Salvador.
   Thousands of Salvadorans have been forced to flee their homes,
and many have blamed the guerrillas for their misery.
   ``We were caught in the cross fire,'' Angel Erazo said Thursday
as she clutched a kitten in one hand and a bag of clothes in the
other. ``It was a horrible night.''
   Residents of one neighborhood who had been without food for days
looted a marketplace.
   ``We have no food, no money, nowhere to go,'' sobbed Adilia
Hernandez of Zacamil.
   Rebel leaders have acknowledged they cannot win the war. The
guerrillas, estimated to have 7,000 full-time fighters and 11,000
backups nationwide, are heavily outnumbered by the 56,000-member
Salvadoran army and other security forces.
   The rebels said they attacked to prove the army also cannot win.
   They say rightist President Alfredo Cristiani cannot govern
without granting a role to their front.
   The guerrillas began their attacks Saturday, three days after
they broke off peace talks with the U.S.-backed government,
claiming it was not serious about reaching a settlement.
</TEXT>
