<FIRST>r a PM-MillionaireSlaying     11-17 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Millionaire Slaying,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Millionaire's Wife Faces Death Penalty in His Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of a millionaire developer killed in his
bedroom with his own handgun faces the electric chair after she was
convicted of offering three thugs $100,000 to shoot him.
   Prosecutors painted Joyce Cohen as a once-poor jet-setter who
was trying to avoid a divorce from Stanley Cohen, while her
attorney blamed the slaying on her husband's supposed drug
connections.
   A Circuit Court jury Thursday convicted Mrs. Cohen, 39, of
first-degree murder, conspiracy to commit murder, and using a
firearm in the commission of the March 7, 1986, shooting at the
couple's upscale house in Coconut Grove.
   Cohen, 52, was shot in the head four times.
   ``We're very, very relieved,'' said Cohen's brother, Arthur
Cohen. ``This has been 3{ years. It was hard _ going to the police
station, listening to what the police had found, listening to the
trial.''
   Mrs. Cohen was indicted after one of the three hired men, Frank
Zuccarello, agreed to cooperate in return for immunity.
   Zuccarello testified that Mrs. Cohen offered him and two other
men $100,000 to kill her husband. She supplied a map of the house,
disconnected security alarms, unlocked the door and even gave them
Cohen's own gun, Zuccarello testified.
   A police expert testified there was gunpowder residue on a
tissue found in a wastebasket in Mrs. Cohen's bathroom.
   Prosecutors are seeking the death penalty. The penalty phase of
the trial was scheduled to begin Monday with the same jury. Mrs.
Cohen had been free on $1 million bond but was jailed after her
conviction.
   Mrs. Cohen's attorney, Alan Ross, tried to blame the killing on
her husband's supposed drug connections, a tactic the victim's
brother called ``a bunch of absolute lies.''
   The couple were married for 11 years. Mrs. Cohen was once her
husband's secretary and soon got used to the life of a jet-setter,
commuting by private jet to their Colorado ranch and using cocaine,
according to testimony.
   Prosecutors said the marriage eventually soured. According to
testimony, Mrs. Cohen feared a divorce would end her posh lifestyle.
   Mrs. Cohen admitted turning off the alarm system and locking up
the dog the night of the murder, but said she had insomnia and
wanted the system off while she wandered around the house preparing
items for a garage sale.
</TEXT>
