<FIRST>r i PM-Pope-Salvador     11-17 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Salvador,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Deplores Killing of Jesuits in El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II today decried the murder
of six Jesuits in El Salvador as an act of ``abominable violence''
and said he was praying for reconciliation in the Central American
country torn by civil war.
   In a telegram to the archbishop of San Salvador, Monsignor
Arturo Rivera Damas, the pope said he was deeply disturbed by the
news of the ``barbarous assassination'' of the Jesuits, their
housekeeper and her 15-year-old daughter.
   John Paul said he wanted to assure the archbishop and the
families of the victims of his ``deep pain for this act of
abominable violence'' and his prayers for the eternal rest for the
dead.
   The pope said he prayed that the sacrifice of the Jesuits would
induce everyone to ``reject violence and respect the lifes of their
brothers to bring peace and reconciliation to this suffering
country.''
   Jesuit headquarters announced that the leader of the religious
order, the Rev. Peter-Hans Kolvenbach, will preside at a special
Mass in Rome on Monday for the murdered Jesuits and ``all the
victims in El Salvador.''
