<FIRST>r a PM-Medflies     11-17 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medflies,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Say Pesticide Used to Fight Medflies Poses Health
Risk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aerial assaults of the pesticide malathion to
fight Mediterranean fruit fly infestations have renewed the
controversy over what some environmentalists and politicians say is
a health risk.
   Aerial spraying of a 22-square-mile area about 15 miles north of
downtown was completed early today in the latest effort by
agriculture officials to eradicate the pest. More spraying was
scheduled over several areas next week.
   The latest fertile fly discovery occurred Wednesday in Hacienda
Heights, with the trapping of a male insect. Earlier this week, a
pregnant Medfly was found in North Hollywood, a previously
unaffected San Fernando Valley suburb.
   The Green Party, a political group dedicated to environmental
issues, scheduled a demonstration Monday to protest use of the
chemical, party chairman Randall Toler said.
   He said the cancer-causing potential of malathion remains under
review by the federal government. The group calls for the use of
sterile Medflies instead of pesticides to halt the infestation.
   Toler said agriculture officials ``were caught flat-footed
without adequate supplies of sterile Medflies.''
   Millions of the laboratory-sterilized flies were released after
sprayings to fight previous infestations, with the goal of breeding
fertile flies out of existence.
   Officials authorized double malathion sprayings over infested
communities, including North Hollywood, Burbank, Studio City and
Toluca Lake, after a supply of sterile Medflies ran out.
   City Councilman Richard Alatorre, who represents an infested
district, wrote to state Food and Agricultural Director Henry Voss:
``Clearly, the Mediterranean fruit fly is a serious menace to the
welfare of this region and ultimately the state. It is equally
clear, however, that one of the weapons used in the battle to
eradicate this menace, malathion, is itself of questionable safety
to the health of humans exposed to it.''
   Carol Ward, spokeswoman for the Los Angeles County Department of
Health Services, defended malathion's use against the Medfly, which
lays its eggs in more than 250 varieties of fruits and vegetables,
threatening the state's $16-billion-a-year agriculture industry.
   ``We feel strongly that the doses that are sprayed are not going
to cause any health problems,'' Ms. Ward said. She said less than
an ounce of malathion is spayed per acre.
</TEXT>
