<FIRST>u a PM-WalesaVisit 2ndLd-Writethru a0549 11-17 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walesa Visit, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0549,0875</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capitalists Fete Walesa in New York City</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Walesa-Humor, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Gov. Mario...' with one graf to CLARIFY that
Lincoln will be published in Polish by Harper &amp; Row, not by state.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa kissed the hand of
a Rockefeller and wowed a gathering of industrial leaders and union
bigwigs upon his triumphant arrival in the capital of the
capitalist world.
   The shipyard electrician from Gdansk whose labor movement
changed Poland met with American union leaders this morning and
praised this country's willingness to help his homeland.
   Starting his second day in New York, Walesa told a gathering of
labor chiefs that in Poland, ``we fight, we risk. ... This is the
greatness of America. We have to fight. We have no choice. You do
not have to fight.''
   Gov. Mario Cuomo joined the meeting and announced plans by
Harper &amp; Row to publish a collection of Abraham Lincoln's speeches
and writings on democracy in Polish and English next year.
   Cuomo said he conceived of the ``Lincoln on Democracy Project''
during a meeting in June with teachers from Poland who told him
books on Lincoln were not available in their country.
   In thanking Cuomo for the Lincoln project, Walesa alluded to the
pace of political change throughout Eastern Europe. ``I don't know
if you can keep pace with translations for other languages because
the line is already forming.''
   Walesa's schedule today also included meetings with the
Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations,
and the editorial boards of The New York Times and The Wall Street
Journal; and a lunch with business leaders and John C. Whitehead,
former U.S. deputy secretary of state.
   He will fly to Chicago tonight.
   Walesa, the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize winner, received several
gifts at the labor meeting, including an electrician's tool belt, a
clock and a set of knives. He accepted the knives in mock protest,
saying, ``I'm all for non-violent struggle. I will not use these
against anybody.''
   On Thursday night, Walesa gave a pep talk to capitalist
heavyweights and union bigwigs who celebrated the success of his
Solidarity movement.
   ``Please believe your possibilities are endless; if you have
self-confidence you can move mountains,'' Walesa said at a dinner.
   ``Please care for this country, because this country is a beacon
of hope for people elsewhere.''
   Walesa said through an interpreter that his own role in
democracy is ``simply a question of fate; the fates forced us to
take some initiatives. If I were here, I would most probably fix
refrigerators or irons.''
   Some 700 industrial and union leaders, government officials and
private citizens attended the dinner of the International Rescue
Committee, a nonsectarian, voluntary agency that runs relief,
medical and resettlement for refugees fleeing political, religious
or racial persecution.
   The committee gave Walesa its Freedom Award. Past recipients
included Winston Churchill, George Meany, Hubert Humphrey and Elie
Wiesel.
   The dinner was Walesa's first appearance in a two-day visit to
New York after he spent four days in Washington, where he met with
President Bush, addressed a joint session of Congress and received
the cheers of U.S. labor leaders.
   At a reception before the dinner Thursday night, Walesa kissed
the hand of socialite Happy Rockefeller, the widow of Nelson
Rockefeller.
   Peter G. Peterson, former U.S. commerce secretary and the
dinner's co-chairman, introduced Walesa as ``the hero of the
Western world; the hero, indeed, of the entire world.''
   Walesa bowed to the audience, then flashed two-fingered ``V's''
for victory with both hands raised above his head.
   Only a handful of his admirers showed up outside the midtown
Manhattan hotel where Walesa received his award. But inside the
Sheraton Centre ballroom, many spoke of the significance of the
Solidarity leader's triumph.
   ``It proves to us in the union movement what we've been saying
all along ... that you can't really have democracy without free
unions,'' said Robert G. Porter, secretary-treasurer of the
American Federation of Teachers.
   ``I think he's remarkable,'' said George Gellert of Oradell,
N.J., whose company, Atalanta Corp., in Elizabeth, N.J., imports
Polish hams. His father-in-law, who started the company in 1945,
owned meat factories in Poland before World War II.
   Companies like American Express and Price Waterhouse, as well as
a variety of American labor unions and private donors, paid $300 to
$2,500 a head to attend the banquet, which benefited the committee.
   Earlier Thursday in Washington, Walesa told a packed luncheon at
the National Press Club that ``the Iron Curtain is no more.'' But
he also said the West will be to blame if Poland's experiment in
democracy fails for lack of economic support.
   ``If we do not succeed in evolution, a revolution may come,''
Walesa said.
   Walesa also found time Tuesday to tape a 30-second commercial
for the AFL-CIO's ``Union Yes'' advertising campaign. In the ad he
speaks in Polish, with a translator, until the end when he switches
to English and gives the ``Union Yes'' slogan.
   The taping took about 90 minutes, partly because Walesa had such
trouble pronouncing ``union.''
</TEXT>
