<FIRST>r a PM-ElderlyShooting     11-17 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elderly Shooting,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury to Hear Case of 101-Year-Old Woman Charged With Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 101-year-old woman accused of shooting at
her granddaughter has missed a court appearance, and authorities
said the case will be forwarded to a grand jury.
   ``Sure I tried to shoot her, damned right I tried to shoot
her,'' said Irene Phillips. ``She's as mean as the devil.''
   Ms. Phillips, of Lawnside, was scheduled to appear Thursday
before Superior Court Judge David A. Keyko on aggravated assault
charges stemming from a Nov. 4 domestic dispute at her home. No
arrest warrant was issued but Camden County Prosecutor Samuel
Asbell said a grand jury would hear the case next month.
   Police allege Ms. Phillips shot at her granddaughter, Ruby
Jones, 46, with a .32-caliber handgun after the pair argued about a
radio.
   Ms. Phillips, who was partly paralyzed by a stroke and uses a
walker, was arrested and released into the custody of another
granddaughter after posting $5,000 bail.
   Ms. Jones told police that her grandmother pointed the gun at
her and said, ``I'm going to kill you.'' A bullet narrowly missed
her, police said.
   Ms. Phillips said she became angry after she woke up during the
night and found that her granddaughter had taken her radio. She
said she uses the radio because she cannot get to church anymore
and needs ``to hear good preaching on Sunday.''
   Asbell said he cannot not dismiss the complaint against Ms.
Phillips, who faces a mandatory three-year minimum jail sentence if
convicted.
</TEXT>
