<FIRST>r a PM-F-16Crash     11-17 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-F-16 Crash,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighter Jet Crashes in Bay; Pilot Picked Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOMESTEAD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force F-16A jet crashed in
Biscayne Bay today but the pilot ejected safely and was later
picked up by helicopter, Coast Guard and Air Force officials said.
   The $16 million, single-seat fighter went down during a routine
training mission in good weather near Elliot Key, about 10 miles
east of Homestead, around 8:30 a.m. EST. It was assigned to the
308th Tactical Fighter Squadron at Homestead Air Force Base.
   Within 10 minutes, the pilot was picked up from a life raft by
an Air Force helicopter, said base spokesman Sgt. Anthony Roland.
   A Coast Guard jet flew over the life raft until the helicopter
arrived, and the pilot appeared to be in good condition, said Coast
Guard Petty Officer Veronica Cady. Crew members said the plane was
visible in the shallow water, she added.
   A board of officers will investigate, an Air Force statement
said.
   An F-16A from the same base crashed into a swampy Dade County
field in August. The pilot ejected and suffered only minor injuries.
</TEXT>
