<FIRST>r w PM-Flight103 1stLd-Writethru a0452 11-17 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Head Promises Thorough Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing throughout, with testimony.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a presidential commission today
promised a thorough investigation of the government response to the
bombing of Pan AM Flight 103 and told relatives of its victims,
``We won't let you down.''
   Nearly a year after the bombing over Lockerbie, Scotland, which
killed 270 people, former Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin opened the
first of several hearings planned before the commission reports its
findings to President Bush next May.
   ``We will let the chips fall where they may,'' Mrs. McLaughlin
said, speaking for the seven-member commission which includes four
members of Congress and two prominent military figures.
   She said the commission's inquiry would evaluate existing
aviation security procedures, the handling of threats against
airlines and whether the public should be notified of them, and the
government's treatment of victims of aviation terrorism.
   Four relatives of people killed aboard the Boeing-747 airliner
testified at the opening of the hearing, including Bert Ammerman,
president of Victims of Pan Am Flight 103, which had called for the
investigation.
   ``The American government has broken faith with its citizens. It
has turned its back on its responsibility to protect the lives of
American citizens at home and abroad,'' Ammerman said. He said
security measures taken since the bombing have been ``little more
than a lot of words.''
   He said those killed in the flight were ``caught up in an
inescapable web of foreign intrigue, evil forces, unscrupulous
airline practices, government double standards, and bureaucratic
unaccountability.''
   In emotional testimony, Victoria Cummock of Coral Gables, Fla.,
described the badly damaged attache case of her husband, who died
aboard the flight, and said, ``Ladies and gentlemen, this is what
remains of John Cummock.''
   The widow said one of her three children, 4-year-old Matthew,
one morning asked for a gun.
   ``I asked him why he wanted a toy gun,'' she said. ``He said he
didn't want any toy gun. He wanted a real gun to shoot himself so
we could all shoot ourselves in order to be with daddy.''
   Mrs. Cummock said she wanted the commission to feel the effects
of the disaster on her family so it would not be considered just an
``unfortunate isolated incident or an inconvenience in a system
that occasionally goes on the blink.''
   ``We won't let you down,'' Mrs. McLaughlin promised.
   Members of the commission include Sens. Frank R. Lautenberg,
D-N.J., and Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., Reps. James Oberstar, D-Minn.,
and John Hammerschmidt, R-Ark., former Assistant Navy Secretary
Edward Hidalgo and retired Air Force Gen. Thomas C. Richards. They
were appointed by President Bush last month.
   Relatives of some of the 189 Americans killed returned last week
from a trip to Frankfurt, West Germany, where the Dec. 21, 1988,
flight originated. They have been trying to get the German
government to reveal more details about the flight.
   The relatives are asking the Presidential Commission on Aviation
Security and Terrorism to ``fully and thoroughly investigate all
leads into the cause of the bombing,'' including Pan Am's security
procedures.
   They also want the commission to find out what the U.S., British
and West German governments knew about terrorist threats before the
Frankfurt-London-New York flight.
   The explosion over Lockerbie, Scotland, has been traced to a
radio cassette player in the cargo hold, but investigators have not
determined who placed it there.
   Richard Lally, vice president of the Air Transport Association,
which represents U.S. airlines, cited what he called a ``serious
flaw'' in Federal Aviation Administration security programs.
   ``The FAA should impose the same security requirements on
foreign carriers serving the U.S. as it imposes on U.S. carriers,''
Lally said in his prepared testimony.
   He noted that in 1985 and again after the Lockerbie bombing, the
FAA imposed extraordinary security requirements on U.S. airlines at
airports in Western Europe, the Middle East and Far East, while
foreign airlines don't have to meet the same requirements.
   The Transportation Department has ordered airlines to pay for
sophisticated explosives detection devices, but a bill pending in
Congress would require the government to pay the bill.
   Lally criticized the government program to install 150 of the
thermal neutron analysis (TNA) systems in airports by the end of
1991, saying the equipment needs more testing.
   ``All experts appear to be in complete agreement that TNA does
not present a full or final answer to the problem of explosives
detection,'' Lally said. The devices cost about $1 million each.
   Lally also urged the United States to adopt the Montreal
Protocols, that would increase the amount of damages victims can
claim in terrorist attacks on commercial aviation.
</TEXT>
