<FIRST>r a PM-Lottery-Refugee     11-17 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lottery-Refugee,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Refugee Wins $6 Million Lottery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 23-year-old Vietnamese refugee has won
$6 million in an Ohio Lottery game, six years after he fled his
homeland with only the clothes on his back.
   Anhtinh Ton Giang will receive $300,000 a year, before taxes,
for 20 years.
   Giang said he will quit his $5.75-an-hour job at HFI Inc., which
makes interior trim for automobiles. Giang, who has worked in
construction, said he might go into partnership with friends to
remodel and sell old houses.
   ``Even if I have money, I won't be a lazy guy,'' he said. ``I'd
like to do work that would improve myself. ... A few years ago,
when I came here, I was very poor, but I always worked hard.''
   Giang was the only person with the six winning numbers in
Wednesday's Super Lotto drawing. He said he let the lottery's
computer pick the numbers, from one to 44, on his $1 ticket.
   He said he's not sure how he will spend the money, except to pay
his brother Cam's way through college. Cam is a freshman at Ohio
State University.
   ``In the next few days, I'll have to do a lot of thinking, he
said. ``I'm talking to a lawyer, trying to find the best way for
the future.''
   Giang said he fled Vietnam because his family was politically
persecuted.
   ``My family was involved with the former government and with
Americans. It was very tough,'' he said.
   After spending 18 months in a refugee camp in Indonesia, he came
to the United States and was sent to Columbus by a resettlement
agency five years ago.
   Besides his brother, Giang has an uncle and a cousin in the
United States. He said the rest of his family is still in Vietnam.
   ``I always dreamed about winning the lottery, but I know the
chances are so small,'' he said. ``I didn't spend a lot of money.
It's cost me about $6 over five years.''
</TEXT>
