<FIRST>r a PM-Adoption     11-17 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Adoption,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advocates Demonstrate Against Judge in Lisa Steinberg Civil Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adoption advocates say a judge was wrong when he
ruled that a woman ``abandoned'' her daughter by giving her up for
adoption and cannot sue for the child's wrongful death at the hands
of a foster father.
   ``Adoption is not abandonment,'' Michele Launders, the
biological mother of abuse victim Lisa Steinberg, said Thursday.
``Having a baby in a parking lot and leaving it there _ that's
abandonment.''
   In 1981 at age 19, Launders, unwed, put her baby up for adoption
through lawyer Joel Steinberg. Steinberg promised her he would
place the baby with a middle-class Catholic family. Instead, he
kept the child without legally adopting her and named her Lisa.
   The girl died of brain injuries at age 6. Steinberg, 48, was
convicted last year of manslaughter and sentenced to up to 25 years
in prison.
   ``I feel moral outrage that birth mothers, after choosing life
over abortion, are further traumatized through public humiliation
of having to wear the label of abandonment,'' said Launders'
mother, Anita.
   About 15 people from five adoption advocacy groups joined
Launders in the protest march against state Supreme Court Justice
Eugene Nardelli, who ruled that Launders had no standing to sue
Steinberg.
   ``I feel he's very, very wrong,'' said Launders, 28.
   Carol Gustavson, head of Adoptive Parents for Open Records, an
advocacy group based in Long Valley, N.J., called Nardelli's
comments ``cutting.''
   ``We're very upset that the word `abandonment' is used to
describe Michele,'' said Gustavson, who said she adopted four
children, now adults.
   On Nov. 2, 1987, Lisa, 6, was taken comatose from Steinberg's
Greenwich Village apartment to a hospital where she died of brain
injuries three days later.
</TEXT>
