<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceProbe     11-17 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Probe,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Investigates Use of Drug Money by Top Detroit Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents are investigating allegations that
high-ranking police officials have diverted more than $1 million in
department funds for personal use, according to published reports.
   The probe focuses on the Police Department's drug forfeiture
fund, which contains cash and assets seized in drug cases, and the
secret service fund, which finances undercover operations and
payments to informants, the Detroit Free Press reported today. The
paper said its information came from sources familiar with the
investigation who spoke under condition of anonymity.
   Agents from the FBI, the Internal Revenue Service and the U.S.
attorney's office are investigating, according to The Detroit News,
which also quoted anonymous sources today.
   The News said command-level officers told investigators they had
been told by their bosses to convert secret service assets to cash.
Agents are trying to determine who spent the money and how.
   Police Chief William Hart said Thursday that money had not been
misused by his department.
   ``If there was, we would make some arrests or be in the process
of investigating the persons that we believe abused the laws,''
Hart said.
   Neither U.S. Attorney Stephen Markman nor Hal Helterhoff, agent
in charge of the Detroit FBI office, would comment on the case.
