<FIRST>r w AM-US-Libya     11-17 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Libya,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Concerned About French Connection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision by France to return three Mirage
fighter-bombers to Libya is raising concern at the State Department.
   The partial lifting of a French arms embargo was linked by the
department to an accord Libya signed in August for a peaceful
settlement in Chad.
   Libya and France were on opposite sides in a war in the African
country.
   The department said Libya is supporting rebels in violation of
an explicit prohibition in the agreement.
   Also, the department said in a statement distributed Friday,
Libya continues to pursue development of chemical weapons and to
support terrorism.
   France decided this week to return to Libya three Fench-made
supersonic Mirage fighter-bombers that had been held after being
returned to Aerospatiale factories for repairs in 1986.
   Foreign ministry sources in Paris, requesting anonymity, said
the return of the three aircraft _ one Mirage F-1 and two
Mirage-5's purchased in 1970 _ did not conflict with a decision by
the European Community in 1986 ruling out the delivery of new
armaments to Libya.
   The sources said the return of the planes was authorized
following the Aug. 31 agreement for a peaceful solution to the
border dispute between Libya and Chad.
   But the State Department said, ``We are quite concerned and
disappointed with this decision. We do not believe that now is the
time to weaken sanctions against Libya.''
   The statement said Libya had not demonstrated concrete changes
in its policies of supporting terrorism and destablization.
</TEXT>
