<FIRST>u a PM-RapeTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0559 11-17 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rape Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0559,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Oklahoma Football Players Convicted of Rape, Third Player Acquitted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with third player acquitted, quotes
from lawyer. Picks up 5th graf, `The jury reached...' SUBS grafs 13-14
bgng `A solemn....' with 1 graf to remove first reference to Cox and outdated
material. A version moved on sports wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORMAN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors convicted two former Oklahoma
football players of first-degree rape but found a third player
innocent today.
   Nigel Clay of Fontana, Calif., and Bernard Hall of Detroit were
found guilty late Thursday in the Jan. 21 rape of an Oklahoma City
woman at the school's athletic dorm. Jurors recommended 10-year
sentences and $10,000 fines for both.
   The jury foreman said Thursday the panel was split 9-3 on Glen
Bell, of Muskogee, without saying which way jurors were leaning.
The jury resumed deliberations this morning and after 1{ hours
returned the acquittal.
   Bell did not take the stand; his former teammates did.
   Bell's attorney, Charles Cox, was asked before today's verdict
was announced if he thought the fact that his client had not
testified while his former teammates took the stand had an impact
on the jury.
   ``It's pretty obvious that the jury didn't believe Nigel and
Bernard,'' Cox said. Hall and Clay had testified that they were not
in the dormitory room at the time.
   Cox added, ``I think everyone thought Glen was in the most risk
from the beginning.''
   The jury reached verdicts on Clay and Hall after hearing two
days of testimony and deliberating nearly 12 hours.
   On Tuesday, the woman testified that on the night of Jan. 21 she
was grabbed by someone as she came out of the bathroom in a suite
of rooms at the dormitory and was thrown to the floor in the
bedroom.
   She said she was raped at least three times and that other
attempts were unsuccessful. She told the court she could not
identify her attackers because it was dark in the room.
   Hall, Clay and Bell were suspended from the team and the
university when charges were filed in February, one of a series of
off-field incidents that rocked Oklahoma's football program.
   The state's key witness was a former teammate of the three
defendants who said he witnessed the rape.
   Several friends and relatives of Clay and Hall cried when
District Judge Preston Trimble read the guilty verdicts. The two
were taken to Cleveland County jail in handcuffs.
   Fred Shaeffer and Joel Barr, their attorneys, left the courtroom
without comment.
   ``I'm pleased with the jury's verdicts on the two defendants,''
District Attorney Tully McCoy said. ``It was a very difficult
case.''
   A solemn-faced Bell was hurried out of the courthouse after the
verdicts.
   The 20-year-old woman was not in the courtroom for the verdicts.
McCoy said she was informed of the verdict by phone.
</TEXT>
