<FIRST>u w PM-AbortionRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0438 11-17 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Lawmakers Introduce Bill Making Abortion Legal</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Leads with abortion-rights lawmakers introducing new bill and
saying it will be focus of efforts next year; edits throughout and adds
two grafs on D.C. bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Accepting defeat on their main abortion
battleground this year, pro-choice House members today set up
future fights by introducing a bill that would write into law the
1973 Supreme Court ruling that legalized abortion.
   The bill also would, in effect, overcome a high-court decision
last summer that gave states greater leeway to impose restrictions
on abortions, supporters said.
   Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., a sponsor, said the bill would
forbid states to limit a woman's right to have an abortion before
the time her fetus becomes viable for life outside the womb.
   Although no action was expected until next year, abortion-rights
backers said the bill could become the central focus of future
congressional and political debate on the abortion issue _ and
could thrust the abortion issue even further into the 1990
congressional races.
   ``This bill is the moral equivalent for women of the 1964 Civil
Rights Act,'' said Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore.
   A version also will be introduced in the Senate, supporters said.
   Abortion-rights supporters in the Senate on Thursday ended their
efforts to overcome President Bush's veto of a bill that would
extend Medicaid abortions to women who are victims of rape or
incest.
   ``I leave it on the conscience of the president that poor women
will continue to be denied their right of choice when they become
pregnant by an act of extreme sexual brutality,'' Sen. Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa, said Thursday.
   The Senate followed the House by a day in acceding to Bush's
demands when he vetoed a bill that would have permitted federal
money to pay for Medicaid abortions for poor women who are victims
of rape or incest.
   Both chambers gave voice-vote approval to a $157 billion
spending bill for labor, health and education programs that
included language insisted upon by Bush. It continues the
prohibition on federally financed abortions in all cases except
when the life of the mother is in danger and she cannot afford to
pay for the abortion.
   The president last month vetoed a similar version of the
appropriations bill that contained a provision expanding the
abortion financing to cover rape and incest. The House failed by 51
votes to override.
   Although the rape and incest provision would cover a relatively
small number of additional abortions, by most estimates, the issue
became a symbolic battleground in the political struggle over
abortion.
   That struggle has taken on increased intensity since the Supreme
Court last summer gave states more leeway to regulate abortions,
and proponents of abortion rights won key elections last week in
Virginia and New Jersey.
   The action ended for now the main congressional fight over
abortion, although there were other abortion-related skirmishes as
Congress pressed toward adjournment.
   In another abortion issue, a $14.6 billion foreign aid bill was
stymied by differences over a provision giving $15 million to the
U.N. Population Fund. The House reversed itself and voted down a
move by abortion opponents to strip the money out of the bill
because the agency operates in China, where a one-child-per-family
policy has led to forced abortions.
   Both sides also were watching to see whether Bush would sign or
veto a spending bill for the District of Columbia. He vetoed an
earlier version because it permitted funding of abortions. Congress
passed a new version that prohibits the D.C. government from using
federal money on abortions, but permits the city to use local money
for abortions.
   ``If he signs it, it will be a victory for us,'' AuCoin said.
</TEXT>
