<FIRST>r a PM-DoctorsArrested     11-17 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctors Arrested,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI and State Charge 22 Physicians in Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-two physicians learned that the FBI
``still makes house calls'' when agents arrested them for allegedly
trying to steal Medicaid money by prescribing expensive equipment
for nonexistent patients.
   The doctors, as well as several physician's assistants, office
managers, physician impersonators and a pharmacist, were accused of
demanding kickbacks in return for writing bogus prescriptions for
items such as oxygen tanks and wheelchairs.
   The distributor of such equipment _ in this case a businessman
who was working undercover for the authorities _ would then be free
to bill Medicaid for an item he never had to provide to a patient.
   William Doran, head of the criminal division of the bureau's New
York office, said such a scheme was ``as much a moral violation as
a legal violation. ... Fraud like this drives (Medicaid) costs even
higher.''
   Most of the physicians were arrested in a series of raids
Thursday by state and federal agents. ``They are now painfully
aware of the fact that the FBI still makes house calls,'' Doran
said.
   Kickbacks in the case ranged as high as $29,000, according to
U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney. Only one of those accused was a
first-time violator, he said.
   Edward J. Kuriansky, a state special prosecutor, said the
accused physicians, most of them foreigners, were part of ``an
influx of foreign nationals'' from places such as Pakistan,
Indonesia and Haiti ``who have come here principally to rip off the
Medicaid system.''
   Such doctors have few community ties and frequently flee before
they can be caught, he said.
</TEXT>
