<SECOND>PM-Bulgaria, 5th Ld-Writethru,a0554,0905</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zhivkov Ousted as Head of State; Bulgarians Cheer in Streets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 6th pvs, ``They continued...'' and recasts
14th, ``Deputy Slavcho...'' to UPDATE with 10,000 demosntrators cheering
reforms and calling for Zhivkov to be tried in court. Pickup 15th, ``He
called...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament today ousted former Communist
Party leader Todor Zhivkov as head of state and replaced him with
Petar Mladenov, the new party leader, who promised radical
political and economic reforms.
   Lawmakers also approved a series of government changes that
drove out some hard-liners loyal to Zhivkov and put reformers into
positions of power.
   The lawmakers removed article 273 of the penal code, which was
broadly used to punish anyone deemed to have slandered the state or
Communist Party. This means that independent groups, which have in
the past have been harrassed by authorities, will have more freedom.
   The National Assembly also created an Ecology Ministry to
address enviornmental concerns raised by one of those groups,
Ecoglasnost.
   Today's moves, along with harsh criticism of Zhivkov, came
during the first live television broadcast of a Parliament session
in the history of Bulgaria.
   They continued the dizzying pace of reform that began in
Bulgaria on Nov. 10 when the hard-line Zhivkov was suddenly ousted
as party leader after a 35-year tenure and replaced by Mladenov,
who was the foreign minister.
   After the parliament meeting, 10,000 chanting Bulgarians
attended a state-sponsored rally in downtown Sofia to support the
leadership changes and call for Zhivkov to be tried in court.
   They loudly cheered lawmaker Slavcho Trnski, who launched an
unprecedented attack on Zhivkov during today's parliamentary
session.
   Mladenov, in his acceptance speech today, said he would
implement sweeping political and economic reforms, but he did not
give specifics.
   The ``new socialist Bulgaria'' will have more respect for
``rights and freedom for all Bulgarians,'' said Mladenov.
   The new leader also called on the unicameral Parliament _
traditionally, as in other Soviet bloc countries, a rubber-stamp
body for party decisions _ to take a more active role in
``controlling'' party and government work.
   Dropped from the government today were Petko Danchev, a deputy
premier, and Stoyan Ovcharov, minister of economy and planning.
Both were Zhivkov men, who were ousted as non-voting members of the
Politburo on Thursday.
   Stoyan Mihailov, a reformer who was removed from the Central
Committee and stripped of his ideology portfolio under Zhivkov last
year, was made minister of eduction and culture. The post could
prove to be important as Mladenov seeks to garner support from
intellectuals in carrying out reforms.
   Nikolai Dankerov was appointed to head the new Ecology Ministry,
an Voyko Dimitrov was named Mladenov's successor as foreign
minister.
   The 400-member National Assembly voted unanimously by a show of
hands to oust Zhivkov as head of state and to replace him with
Mladenov. Deputies praised Mladenov for his ``enthusiasm'' for
perestroika, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform program.
   Trnski delivered a scathing attack on Zhivkov to the stunned
deputies, accusing the former leader of having led the country into
deep economic crisis while leading a ``flamboyant lifestyle.''
   He called for the ``real truth'' to come out about Zhivkov, who
he said owned 30 homes around the country. ``Not even the richest
countries in the world could stand those expenses,'' he said.
   He also charged that Zhivkov was ``hungry for fame'' and held
onto power by pursuing a policy of ``divide and rule.''
   Zhivkov often carried out personnel changes in the top party and
government echelons to consolidate his power.
   Trnski called for an investigation into what he described as
misuse of funds by Zhivkov's son Vladimir. He was purged from the
Central Committee Thursday and was rumored to be involved in
several scandals.
   Also Thursday, the Central Committee ousted three hard-line
Politburo members and promoted four liberal Communists, who are
expected to back Mladenov's reforms.
   In other changes today:
   _Andrei Lukanov, who was elevated to Politburo member and
Central Committee secretary Thursday, was relieved of his duties as
minister of foreign trade. Observers speculated he would be
Mladenov's No. 2 man in the party. His deputy, Georgi Pirinski,
replaced him.
   _Kiril Zarev was named minister of economics and Belcho Belchev
was named finance minister, a new post.
   _Mincho Yovchev, who was promoted to the Politburo on Thursday,
was named to head a new ministry of industry and technology.
   Under Zhivkov, this Balkan nation had been one of Moscow's most
loyal allies during the rule of former Soviet leader Leonid
Brezhnev. Despite a program outlined by Zhivkov in July 1987 which
seemed to call for reforms, little was done to implement them and
those who tried were removed from power.
   Mladenov is considered a well-connected politician with good
relations in Moscow, where he was educated. State media have said
Mladenov has already been in contact with Gorbachev, who greeted
his appointment as party leader.
   Mladenov has emphasized the continued leading role of the party
but at the same time has initiated direct dialogue with prominent
non-conformist intellectuals who belong to independent groups.
   He has moved quickly to secure his position in the party.
Informed sources said further top-level changes were expected in
the party and government to clear Communists loyal to Zhivkov's
rule.
</TEXT>
