<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Ride     11-17 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Ride,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Returning Home From the `Consumer Temple'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Beginning a reporting trip to East Germany,
Associated Press correspondent Hanns Neuerbourg shared a train ride
with some East German visitors returning home from West Germany.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAALFELD, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The animated chat about a shopping
spree just completed in the West came to a sudden halt as the
Nuremberg-Leipzig express crossed into East Germany.
   In the border zone where Communist guards with submachine guns
once shot to kill would-be escapees, the watchtower stood empty.
   As the train drew to a halt at Probstzella, the first stop in
East Germany, only a bearded man in a windbreaker, holding a
half-empty bottle of beer, kept talking.
   ``Any official check gives me an uneasy feeling, something like
going to the dentist,'' said a middle-aged woman returning from her
first trip to the West in 34 years. ``But maybe this time it will
be different.''
   It was. A smiling East German policewoman looked only passingly
at the identity papers. These included a passport, stamped with a
visa that authorized a reporter to make five days of unlimited
travel in East Germany.
   A second policeman followed, then a woman customs official.
   There were no questions, and no checks of the luggage, the
parcels and the shopping bags piled up to the compartment's ceiling.
   The police officer did not react when the man with the beer
bottle slapped him jokingly on the shoulder.
   ``They are completely insecure now,'' said the man later. ``They
have no instructions, so they just don't do anything.''
   ``It is really the new beginning,'' said a woman in her mid-30s,
peeling an orange as the train resumed its voyage.
   ``I still have my doubts,'' countered her neighbor. ``There are
too many Wendehaelse,'' she added, using a word that is used to
refer to turncoats.
   ``I feel a bit embarrassed,'' said another woman as the talk
returned to shopping.
   ``Taking those 100 marks ($54) `welcome money' makes you almost
feel like living on the dole,'' she said of the money provided the
visitors by the West German government.
   ``Don't worry,'' she was reassured. ``All that money stays in
West Germany anyway. But how will things look back here in the
East?''
   ``Prices will go up,'' replied a woman who said she was the wife
of a baker. ``We are told that bread will go up from 93 pfennigs to
2.80 marks in January.''
   East German marks are nominally equal in value to West German
marks, which are worth about 54 cents. But on the black market, or
at West German currency exchanges, the East German currency only
goes for one-tenth the nominal rate.
   ``It's evident,'' said another woman, ``that these subsidies
will have to go. Imagine, I pay 60 marks per month in rent for a
5{-room apartment.''
   ``And I paid 36 marks for a pair of designer stockings in the
Exquisit,'' chimed in another, referring to a state-owned chain of
East German luxury stores. ``It's completely crazy.''
   As the train rolled into Saalfeld, the bearded man emptied his
last bottle and put it carefully into the shopping bags, where it
joined several others. Empty bottles can be returned for five
pfennigs in East Germany.
   A woman said, ``I am homesick. It was an amazing experience in
this consumer temple. But now I am glad to be back.''
   The bearded man started singing what was once a popular tune,
``In der Heimat angekommen, faengt ein neues Leben an.''
   Back home, a new life begins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891117-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DriverlessDestruction     11-17 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Driverless Destruction,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Driverless Car Hits 2 Buildings, Causes $4,000 Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLARKSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quick stop for pastries cost $4,000
Friday when a car rolled from its parking spot and hit one
building, then changed direction and slammed into a restaurant. No
one was injured.
   ``I've been a policeman for five years and this by far and above
is the most unusual thing I've ever seen,'' said Patrolman Mark
Waggamon.
   Ramona Wagner, 52, of Wallace, parked in front of a bakery and
left her car's motor running while she went inside, Waggamon said.
   The transmission apparently slipped from park into reverse and
the car ``traveled backward and up the street across three lanes of
traffic and struck the front of the Galleria Mini Mall,'' the
patrolman said.
   He said the force of the collision then shifted the transmission
into either neutral or drive, and the car rolled off in another
direction.
   ``The car struck a newspaper vendor rack, which fell over and
hit a parked van, and traveled on eastward and through the front
window of McCrory's restaurant,'' Waggamon said.
   The buildings are within 75 yards of each other.
   Sandra Cunningham, 41, of Clarksburg, was the only person in the
restaurant.
   ``I was putting money in the cash register getting ready to open
up when the car came through,'' Cunningham said. ``I couldn't
hardly go anywhere. There was glass flying everywhere. All I could
do was stand and scream.''
   Wagner remained in the bakery during the incident. ``She didn't
even know it happened until she came out and said `That's my car,'
'' Waggamon said.
   He estimated damage to each store at $2,000, with just $100
worth of damage to the car. No charges will be filed.
</TEXT>
