<FIRST>u a PM-Storm-School 1stLd-Writethru a0500 11-17 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Storm-School, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0500,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Closed In Wake of Storm Deaths</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with officials meeting, wall inspection
found rotten wood, critically injured up from two to three. Picks up 6th
graf pvs, ``Kulisek said....''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Northeast Storm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWBURGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents volunteered to give blood at
hospitals and schools were closed in mourning today after a
cafeteria wall collapsed in a violent wind, killing seven
elementary schoolchildren.
   School and town officials spent most of this morning in private
meetings. About 100 of the 150 town employees met to bring the
``family of this town together,'' said town supervisor Robert
Kirkpatrick.
   The wall, about 30 feet high and 50 feet wide, caved in on a
group of first-, second- and third-graders as they were eating
lunch Thursday at the East Coldenham Elementary School in Newburgh,
about 60 miles north of New York City.
   The wall was last inspected in 1984 and rotten wood was found
around some windows, Valley Central School Superintendent James
Coonan said today. But he said the rotting wood was replaced and
``it was as strong as it could be.''
   While school was closed today for about 4,000 students in the
district, Coonan said he was already worrying about next week,
``when we have seven funerals to deal with and children sitting
next to empty seats.''
   ``We're just overcome by this tragedy,'' said Bob Kirkpatrick,
supervisor of the town of about 23,000 residents.
   Between 113 to 125 students were eating in the cafeteria when
the brick, cinder-block and glass wall blew in, said police chief
John Kulisek. The dead and injured children were between 6 and 9
years old. Three children were in critical condition today.
   Kulisek said that witnesses reported a tornado, but the National
Weather Service said it had no evidence an actual twister was
responsible for the damage.
   Firefighters and police arrived at the scene of the disaster
within 15 minutes and began freeing children trapped under bricks
and cinder blocks.
   ``A lot of the kids were crushed,'' said Robert Markisello, one
of the first paramedics at the scene.
   Mayor Donald Presutti praised emergency workers, saying they
were ``treating this like they were members of their own families
... it was a very moving experience.''
   St. Luke's Hospital spokeswoman Debra Sgroe said many people
came to give blood to help victims. Crisis counselors were meeting
with parents at the hospital in rooms set aside for families of the
dead and injured.
   Police Lt. John J. Mahoney said he arrived at the school ten
minutes after the wall collapsed to find children calling out from
under the rubble.
   ``Some were screaming, some were lying there very quiet,''
Mahoney said. ``You could hear them under the debris calling for
help, calling `Take me home, take me home.'''
   The children were freed from the rubble within half an hour.
   Children wandered in a daze around the school grounds calling
for their parents, Markisello said.
   A woman arrived at St. Luke's shouting, ``I want my daughter, I
want my daughter!'' She later learned her child was not among the
dead.
   One boy who approached the wreckage saw food on some of the
tables and milk spilled on the floor.
   ``There's two lunch boxes still sitting there,'' 12-year-old
Shawn Dearborn said.
   State Education Department spokesman Christopher Carpenter said
the state would send counselors to help survivors deal with the
grief.
   ``There are two things we now have to deal with. One is the
physical aspect of getting the children into school. The second is
dealing with the emotional and psychological problems,'' he said.
   Carpenter said the state would send a structural engineer and an
architect to the site to help determine why the wall collapsed.

</TEXT>
