<FIRST>r i AM-Swiss-Hostages     11-17 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swiss-Hostages,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Says Still No Sign of Kidnapped Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Committee of the Red Cross said
Friday there is still no sign of its two relief workers kidnapped
in Lebanon six weeks ago, although it believes the men are not in
immediate danger.
   Red Cross delegate Andre Pasquier said the humanitarian
organization might withdraw its operations from Lebanon if Emanuel
Christen and Elio Erriquez remained in long-term captivity.
   The Red Cross stopped work two weeks ago in Sidon, the southern
city where the men were seized. The orthopedic center where
Christten and Erriquez helped fit artificial limbs closed
immediately after the Oct. 6 kidnappings.
   Pasquier told Swiss radio that Red Cross chief Middle East
delegate Angelo Gnaedinger had returned Wednesday from 10 days of
talks in the Lebanon. He said there was no clue to the identity of
the kidnappers and no signs of an early release for the two Swiss
workers.
   ``We believe the life of both men is not in immediate danger,''
Pasquier added.
   Another Red Cross delegate, Peter Winkler, was kidnapped a year
ago in Lebanon and released after one month in captivity. Death
threats after Winkler was freed prompted the Red Cross to leave the
country. It returned several weeks later after Lebanese factions
guaranteed there would be no more attacks on the organization.
   There are 18 Western hostages in Lebanon, most of them held by
Shiite Moslem factions loyal to Iran. They are eight Americans,
four Britons, two West Germans, an Italian, an Irishman and the two
Swiss.
   Held longest is American Terry A. Anderson, 42, chief Middle
East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March
16, 1985.
</TEXT>
