<HEAD>Pregnant Woman, Sisters And Children Mistaken For Bank Robbers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four police cars rushed in, lights flashing,
and officers with guns drawn ordered the suspects out of their car
_ three women, one nine months pregnant, and two children, one a
3-year-old boy with a cap pistol.
   ``It was like Miami Vice,'' Kayron Foster, 31, of Salem, said
after the encounter at a U.S. Bank branch Wednesday. ``I thought
for a minute that they were going to shoot me.''
   Police who followed and then surrounded her car acted on a
reliable tip from a bank employee who apparently saw the boy's cap
pistol earlier and feared a robbery might occur, said Sgt. Dan Cary.
   But Foster said it was frightening and unnecessary.
   ``They could see the children bouncing around in the back when
they were following me,'' she said.
   Cary said it didn't take long for officers to realize that
Jessie Myers, toting a toy pistol, was not a bank robber.
   But Foster said police continued to treat them as suspects long
after it was apparent they were no danger to anyone. She said she
was handcuffed and her sister, Janet Easter, 20, whose second baby
was due Tuesday, was ordered to crawl across the car's gearshift to
get out of the front seat.
   Their younger sister, Diane Easter, 18; Foster's 12-year-old
son, Trace Mills; and Jessie, Janet Easter's son, were in the back
seat.
   ``When they saw a pregnant woman and a child step out, they
should have known,'' she said. ``They are supposed to be trained to
read people and situations.''
   Foster said she had driven to her bank but realized she had
forgotten her bank book. She drove home to get it and returned to
the bank.
   Meanwhile, the bank employee had seen the cap pistol and called
police.
   Sgt. Dan Smith defended the officers' actions, saying police
have no way of knowing what kind of situation they are entering.
