<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 6thLd-Writethru a0613 11-17 0902</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0613,0926</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Offers Protection To Witnesses In Massacre of Jesuits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th, `At the...' to ADD dropped word `not.' Pickup 6th,
`Walker...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. ambassador said today
he will personally investigate the brutal massacre of six Jesuit
priests, and he offered protection to any witnesses who come
forward to testify.
   Hours after the killings Thursday, uniformed security officers
raided a Lutheran Church office and arrested 12 missionary workers,
including four Americans, a Canadian consular official said.
   Also today, sporadic fighting was reported six days after
leftist rebels launched their biggest offensive in a 10-year-old
civil war. A British journalist was wounded in cross-fire between
rebels and government troops in the Mejicanos district of San
Salvador and later died in a hospital.
   U.S. Ambassador William Walker said the United States is
pressuring the right-wing government of President Alfredo Cristiani
to investigate the killings of the six Jesuit priests, their cook
and her daughter.
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
the United States would closely monitor the Salvadoran government's
investigation of the killings but did not plan to assist in the
inquiry.
   Walker, however, offered protection to citizens providing
information. He also said in an interview, ``I will try to find and
solicit the testimony of people who are or who claim to be
witnesses.''
   He said he planned to contact officials at the Jesuit university
who have said two witnesses saw about 30 men in army uniforms enter
the priests' residence just before the shooting began.
   He described the massacre as a ``blot on the image'' of El
Salvador's government that could only be erased by a full
investigation and punishment of the guilty.
   The government, which relies heavily on U.S. aid, denied
responsibility and said the murders were ``savage and irrational.''
   The Rev. Jose Maria Tojeira, the Jesuit Provincial for Central
America, said the victims were tortured before they were slain.
Although the bodies were found mutilated, the torture allegations
have not been confirmed.
   Tojeira said terrified witnesses had gone into hiding and did
not trust authorities because troops were implicated in the
killings.
   El Salvador only recently emerged from a period of repression
during which death squads and rightist elements of the military
were accused of killing thousands of people. The Salvadoran right
considers church activists and church intellectuals to be
subversives.
   An annual reported presented today at the United Nations said
accused El Salvador's government of presiding over a ``resurgence
of torture'' this year and a crackdown on trade unions and
organizations.
   The annual report by Jose Antonio Pastor Ridruejo, a special
representative of the U.N. Commission on Human Rights, criticized
both the government and rebels for kidnappings and assassinations.
   Cristiani, who took office June 1, told reporters Thursday the
government was not involved in the priest slayings and that he had
ordered an investigation. ``The killers will jeopardize further the
critical situation in our country,'' he said.
   The guerrillas of the leftist Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, who have been waging a 10-year-old war with the
government, called the slayings an ``absurd massacre.''
   Uniformed security officers on Thursday raided a downtown office
of the Lutheran Church and arrested 12 missionary workers, said
Michel Gagne, a consular officer at the Canadian Embassy.
   He said they were being detained at Treasury Police
headquarters. Police refused to confirm the report.
   The detainees included four U.S. citizens, a Canadian, and a
Spaniard. The rest were West Germans.
   The Americans were identified as Paula Brentlinger, a physician
from Seattle; Thomas Gabriel, a nurse from Seattle; Bradley Fields,
a social worker from San Diego; and Paul Fitch, a U.S. volunteer
whose hometown was not known.
   The Rev. William Dexheimer, a pastor of the Evangelical Lutheran
Church of America, said he had received a telephone call Tuesday
threatening him with death if he didn't leave. After the slayings
Thursday, he flew home to Florida.
   At the Vatican, Pope John Paul II today decried the murder of
the Jesuits, calling it an act of ``abominable violence'' in a
telegram to the archbishop of San Salvador, Monsignor Arturo Rivera
Damas.
   Rivera Damas compared the killings to the slaying of his
predecessor, Oscar Arnulfo Romero, in March 1980. Romero had been
denouncing years of killings by right-wing death squads and
kidnappings by guerrillas.
   On Dec. 2, 1980, troops killed U.S. Maryknoll nuns Ita Ford and
Maura Clarke, Ursuline sister Dorothy Kazel and lay worker Jean
Donovan.
   More than 800 people have died and twice as many have been
wounded since government forces and the guerrillas began fighting
Saturday, according to reports by the military and hospitals.
   Michael Blundy, 44, a correspondent for a British newspaper, the
Sunday Correspondent, died at Rosales Hospital where he had been
rushed by fellow reporters after he was shot in the shoulder today.
British vice-consul Adele Taylor said Blundy's body will be sent to
London for burial.
   Col. Rene Emilio Ponce, the armed forces chief of staff, late
Thursday appealed to people to return to work. But a dusk-to-dawn
curfew, a state of siege declared by the government and a ban on
traffic decreed by the rebels made it seem doubtful many would heed
his call.
   The guerrillas are estimated to have 7,000 full-time fighters
and 11,000 backups nationwide. The guerrillas are heavily
outnumbered by the 56,000-strong Salvadoran army and other security
forces.
</TEXT>
