<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     11-17 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Envoy Fails to Break Deadlock Between Iran, Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. envoy trying to restart the peace
talks between Iran and Iraq failed to break the deadlock but
scheduled more meetings next month, Iranian media said Friday.
   Jan Eliasson ended his 17-day shuttle and left Tehran for New
York, the Islamic Republic News Agency said, and Iranian President
Hashemi Rafsanjani blamed the mission's failure on Iraq.
   Rafsanjani said Iraq was still not ready to accept U.N.
Resolution 598, a plan aimed at reaching a peace accord between the
two counties that ended eight years of fighting nearly 16 months
ago.
   IRNA, monitored in Cyprus, quoted Eliasson as saying he arranged
for separate meetings between the foreign ministers of the two
countries and U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar in New
York next month.
   ``Not surprisingly, the positions (of Iran and Iraq) are in some
respects wide apart,'' he told the news agency. He declined to
elaborate.
   Eliasson said Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz and his Iranian
counterpart, Ali Akbar Velayati, would meet separately with Perez
de Cuellar.
   In a statement released in Iran and Iraq on Thursday, Eliasson
said he had 12 meetings with officials of both countries focusing
on how to implement U.N. Security Council Resolution 598.
   ``In the course of my talks with the representatives of both
governments, I suggested ways to move the talks forward within the
framework of Resolution 598 in order to achieve a comprehensive and
lasting peace in the region,'' he said.
   The resolution, which halted the eight-year war on Aug. 20,
1988, calls for troop withdrawals to internationally recognized
borders, the exchange of prisoners of war and a settlement of the
conflict through U.N.-sponsored negotiations.
   Rafsanjani, in a Friday prayer sermon, said Iraq's insistence
that a release of prisoners of war should come before other parts
of Resolution 598 was a ``mere excuse'' by Baghdad for failing to
carry out the resolution.
   The Iranians want the resolution to be followed point-by-point
in the order listed in the document, insisting the first step
should be an Iraqi withdrawal from Iranian territory they seized in
the final weeks of the war.
   The exchange of POWs should come next, followed by clearing war
debris from the Shatt-Al-Arab waterway, Iraq's main outlet to the
gulf.
   ``Obviously both sides are against the resumption of the war
under any circumstances,'' Rafsanjani said.
   But he stressed that Iranians should remain vigilant: ``We have
to preserve our (combat) readiness.''
   Among the sticking points in the talks has been Iraq's claim on
the Shatt-al-Arab waterway which formed part of the frontier
between the two nations before the war. The Iraqis want the border
redrawn to include all of the strategic waterway in Iraqi territory.
   An estimated 100,000 POWs are held by both sides and Iraq has
offered that they be swapped outside the framework of the
resolution. Iran refused, insisting on an Iraqi withdrawal first.
</TEXT>
