<FIRST>r w AM-Ethics-Frank     11-17 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethics-Frank,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frank Probe to Continue Over Congressional Recess</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House investigation into Rep. Barney Frank's
relationship with a male prostitute will continue over the year-end
congressional recess, an official involved in the probe said Friday.
   The House ethics committee has no meetings scheduled at present,
but committee staff will continue working on the Frank case, said
Mark Davis, a staff member.
   ``It's still open and ongoing,'' Davis said. ``The adjournment
of Congress has no impact on what the staff does or will be doing.''
   The ethics panel initially hoped to complete its investigation
of Frank, D-Mass., by the end of the year. Davis had no comment on
a report in The Washington Times that the investigation was being
extended while members await publication of a magazine article
about Frank.
   The newspaper reported Friday that members want to see what male
prostitute Stephen Gobie told Penthouse magazine in an interview
expected to be appear in the February issue.
   Penthouse spokeswoman Leslie Jay said the February issue is
slated to be published Jan. 2 but that no decision has been made on
whether the Frank article will appear in that issue.
   Frank spokesman Doug Cahn said, ``The question of timing of the
ethics committee is not a question for Barney Frank. Barney is
cooperating with the ethics committee.''
   Frank, who is homosexual, has admitted paying Gobie $80 for sex
in 1985 and subsequently hiring him with personal money to serve as
a housekeeper and driver from July 1985 through August 1987.
   Gobie made public the relationship in August, and claimed the
congressman knew he was running a prostitution ring from Frank's
Capitol Hill apartment. Gobie also accused Frank of engaging in sex
with him in the House gymnasium. Frank has denied the charges.
   The Times also reported that the Justice Department is
maintaining a file on the Frank case. A Justice Department
official, who requested anonymity, said, ``We are not yet
investigating any possible illegal activities on the part of Mr.
Frank.''
</TEXT>
