<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 2145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Maine-CruiseMissiles     11-17 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Maine-Cruise Missiles,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Action To Enforce Cruise Missile Ban Impossible, Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS X. QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maine's attorney general said Friday his
office knows of no way the state could legally force an end to
cruise missile test flights over the state, an action approved by
voters.
   The results of the non-binding referendum on Nov. 7 prompted
Gov. John R. McKernan to send letters to federal and congressional
officials, urging them to ``recognize this opposition and reassess
the need'' for test flights of the unarmed missiles over Maine.
   Maine is one of five states where Tomahawk missiles are flown by
the Navy. Missiles are launched from submarines off the coast and
fly at 500 to 6,000 feet above the ground to the Navy Survival
School at Rangeley.
   There have been three tests over Maine.
   State Attorney General James E. Tierney, releasing a letter to
McKernan, said that under the supremacy clause in Article VI of the
U.S. Constitution, ``the states are without constitutional power to
interfere with such actions.''
   But Tierney also said the state's inability to take legal action
against the federal government over the tests was undoubtedly in
the minds of advocates of the ban, because their resolution
specifically called on the governor to ``intervene with the federal
government to stop the testing.''
   Tierney said McKernan's letter-writing ``appears to be clearly
what was contemplated by the resolution, and satisfies your legal
obligation under it.''
   ``Consequently,'' Tierney said, ``the department urges you to
continue to pursue that course in the hope that, through such
forceful advocacy, the views of the citizens of Maine on the matter
may prevail.''
   Eric Johnson, campaign manager for proponents of the
anti-testing measure, did not respond immediately Friday to a
telephone request for comment on Tierney's letter.
   The deputy director of public affairs for the Navy project said
Friday there had been no change in status.
   ``Yes, we are going to continue to go with our plans as always
until we're ordered to do otherwise,'' Susan Boyd said in a
telephone interview from project headquarters outside Washington.
   Boyd would not comment on details of future tests, saying
planned flight dates are kept secret.
   In unofficial tallies of the Nov. 7 balloting, the issue was
approved by 52 percent of the voters. Opponents of the testing had
presented 66,142 valid signatures to force their advisory question
onto the ballot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
