<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Thanksgiving     11-17 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Thanksgiving,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>The President Pardons a Turkey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush bestowed a ``presidential
pardon'' Friday on a noisy 50-pound turkey whose gobbles punctuated
a Rose Garden speech declaring next Thursday as Thanksgiving.
   ``Come on, this is serious stuff,'' Bush scolded the turkey.
   Unlike the bird that lunged at President Reagan several years
ago, this year's turkey quieted and bobbed his head calmly as Bush
left the podium to stroke its back.
   Bush was presented the 28-week-old turkey at a ceremony marking
the 200th anniversary of presidential Thanksgiving proclamations.
   Before signing this year's proclamation, Bush observed, ``two
hundred years ago, George Washington signed the original
proclamation for a day of Thanksgiving, a day of thanks for the
bounty we enjoy. ...''
   From that point, Bush continued haltingly as both the turkey's
gobbles and the crowd's laughter rose in volume.
   Bush told his audience, which included a group of 30 elementary
school children, ``our special guest ... seems understandably
nervous.''
   ``But let me assure you, and this fine tom turkey, that he will
not end up on anyone's dinner table, not this guy. He's granted a
presidential pardon as of right now.''
   Bush said the turkey would ``live out his days'' on a children's
petting zoo in the area.
   The turkey was raised in Detroit Lakes, Minn., by John
Wickliffe, the president of the National Turkey Federation, and his
wife, Eleanor.
   Wickliffe told Bush the turkey ``weighs 50 pounds, one for every
state in the union.''
   The federation said in a fact sheet that, this year's White
House turkey notwithstanding, Americans next Thursday will consume
45 million turkeys.
   The president said that the family dog, Millie, who loves to
chase squirrels and pigeons on the White House grounds, had been
dispatched ``upstairs, looking wistfully out of the window, I'm
sure.''
   Bush called two children from the audience _ third grader
Shannon Duffy, 8, and fifth grader Danny Benyam, 10, both from
Brenmar Park elementary school in Fairfax County, Va. _ to join him
in petting the turkey.
   At a similar ceremony several years ago, the turkey lunged at
and startled Reagan. The following year, the turkey was sedated.
   This year's turkey was not sedated but was presented ``live and
kicking,'' said presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   A bit later, addressing an arts ceremony, Bush said: ``I've been
out there trying to calm the national turkey. It all worked out
pretty well.''
   The tradition of presenting a live turkey to the president goes
back 42 years, to the administration of President Truman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
