<DOCNO> AP891117-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 2118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     11-17 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A temporary-employment agency means business
when it hires and trains Santas by the sleighload every year.
   ``We take this very seriously,'' said Nancy Franklyn, manager of
the Pittsburgh branch of Western Temporary Services.
   A part-time Santa Claus must meet strict standards, she said.
   ``They must have twinkling eyes. They must know Christmas songs
and the names of all the reindeer,'' she said.
   ``They have to love wearing a 40-pound suit in a little room
that is not well ventilated, handling up to 200 children a day. ...
And they must be able to do this six hours straight and enjoy every
minute of it.''
   ``Don't `ho, ho, ho' around the children,'' she told the
surrogate Santas during a training session Thursday. ``It scares
the daylight out of them.''
   Although primarily an agency that provides temporary clerical
and medical support services, Western has been recruiting and
training Santas for retail stores and private parties across the
country since 1968.
   More than 3,000 Santas are recruited by Western offices across
the nation every year during the holiday season, she said. They
usually work 20 to 30 hours a week and earn $6 to $7 an hour, she
said.
   She passed on tips for handling awkward questions children
sometimes ask: Animals don't travel well in Santa's sleigh, so a
request for a pet is referred to parents. Requests for baby
brothers or sisters are referred to the stork.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MITCHELL, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Jerry Hancock went to visit friends
in Orlando, Fla., and wound up being grand marshal of the city's
Queen Kumquat Sashay.
   Hancock said he was thrilled to ride in a pickup truck and throw
kumquats to parade watchers Saturday, despite being the festival's
second choice.
   According to the Orlando Sentinel, organizers had wanted Zsa Zsa
Gabor until her agent informed them of her $5,000 appearance fee.
   Hancock was suggested as an alternative by Mary Lee Mannix of
Orlando, who has distant ties to Mitchell and knew Hancock was
coming to visit some friends of hers.
   ``She asked me after I got there, and they already had it in the
paper,'' the 22-year mayor of the town of 4,600 said this week.
   One parade-watcher held a sign proclaiming ``I've been to
Mitchell,'' and someone else asked him how the limestone industry
was doing in southern Indiana.
   ``Saved 'em $5,000, I reckon,'' said Hancock, who performed his
ceremonial duties for free.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lizard love can be helped along by a few
months in the fridge, a zoo official says.
   Wichita's Sedgewick County Zoo and the Oklahoma City Zoo are two
of the few zoos in the nation that have successfully hatched Gila
monsters in captivity, said Eric Rundquist, a herpetologist
formerly with the Oklahoma zoo and now with the Wichita zoo.
   The trick is making the Gila monsters think they have
hibernated, he said, which is accomplished by putting the lizards
in a refrigerator. The zoo's six adult Gila monsters went in a
large commercial refrigerator in December and were taken out in
March. After hibernation, the warmer temperatures stimulated the
males' sperm production. The lizards bred in May.
   Two months later, the zoo's three females laid 13 eggs, about
half of which turned out to be fertile.
   The six baby Gilas hatched earlier this month go on display this
weekend.
</TEXT>
