<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CasonNomination     11-17 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cason Nomination,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Leaders Turn Back Cason Nomination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders agreed Friday to send back to
President Bush the nomination of James Cason for a top natural
resources job and ask that someone else be selected.
   It was the first time since the vote against John Tower for
defense secretary earlier this year that a nomination got as far as
the Senate floor, only to be turned back.
   ``It will mark the first time that any assistant secretary
nominee would be defeated after being reported out of committee
with a favorable recommendation,'' said Republican leader Bob Dole
of Kansas.
   Cason, a high-ranking official at the Interior Department since
1982, was nominated to be assistant secretary of agriculture for
natural resources and soil conservation.
   After two days of hearings, the Agriculture Committee voted 12-7
to send the nomination to Senate floor, despite vocal opposition
from committee chairman Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., and some other
committee members.
   Cason was strongly opposed by environmentalists because they
said he showed a preference at Interior for private development
over environmental concerns.
   Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., called Cason ``a James Watt clone,'' in
reference to the former interior secretary who favored development
of government land.
   Dole expressed disappointment at the mounting opposition, saying
a ``campaign of distortion has successfully poisoned the debate.''
   ``A cheap way to get a good environmental vote is to vote down
this nominee, whether he deserves it or not,'' said Dole. ``I can
see the handwriting on the wall.''
   After conferring with Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter and
the White House, Dole requested that the Senate not act on the
nomination.
   Leahy said Friday the nominee would have been defeated by a
20-vote margin, with opponents including more than five
Republicans, if a vote had been taken.
   Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, agreed to send the
nomination back to Bush with ``a strong urging that this nominee
not be made the subject of a recess appointment or that he be
resubmitted'' when Congress comes back in January.
   ``I'm sure they're practical realists,'' said Leahy. ``I'm sure
they won't send the name back up here.''
</TEXT>
