<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Choe     11-17 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Choe,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former South Korean Foreign Minister Dies in Pyongyang</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former South Korean Foreign Minister Choe Dok-shin,
who has lived in North Korea after becoming affiliated with a
dissident group that leans toward the Communist government, has
died at the age of 75.
   President Kim Il Sung visited Choe before he died Thursday night
in a hospital in the North Korean capital of Pyongyang, the Korean
Central News Agency reported Friday.
   Choe served as South Korean foreign minister in 1961-63
following a military coup led by Park Chung-hee, another army
general, on May 16, 1961.
   He headed the Chondoist Church, a Korean native religious group,
before seeking political asylum in the United States in 1977.
   After affiliating himself with a North Korean-leaning dissident
group Hanmintong _ the Korean Conference for Democracy and
Unification _ he went to North Korea in 1984. He has lived there
since 1986.
   In Pyongyang, Choe held such titles as chairman of the Central
Committee of the Chondoist Chong-wu Party, vice chairman of the
Committee for the Peaceful Reunification of the Fatherland and
chairman of the Korean Religionists Council.
   Funeral arrangements were not announced.
</TEXT>
