<FIRST>r w AM-IowaHearing 1stLd-Writethru a0629 11-17 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Schedules Hearings on Navy's Iowa Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 6th graf pvs, bgng, ``I want..., with congressional
sources saying new evidence centers on FBI analysis and forensic evidence.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Armed Services Committee said Friday
it will hold hearings next month on the Navy's inquiry and
subsequent finding that a troubled sailor apparently caused the
fatal explosion aboard the USS Iowa.
   ``We have unearthed significant new evidence that casts new
light on the Navy's conclusion that gunner's mate Clayton Hartwig
committed suicide and mass murder in the gun turret,'' Rep.
Nicholas Mavroules, chairman of the Armed Services subcommittee on
investigations, said in a statement.
   Mavroules said his panel has been reviewing ``several aspects of
the Navy investigation _ especially its technical competence and
its psychological analysis.''
   Questioned later about his comments, Mavroules declined to
provide specifics, but expressed concern about a ``question of
interpretation'' of the evidence.
   The Massachusetts Democrat has said he ``seriously questioned''
the Navy's report, and cited an FBI report that said its laboratory
investigation on the incident was inconclusive.
   ``I want documentation,'' Mavroules said in an interview.
``Unless the Navy does that it's a discredit to the investigation.
The investigation was thorough but the conclusion was not
thorough.''
   Congressional sources, who requested anonymity, said the new
evidence centers on the FBI's psychological analysis of Hartwig and
the forensic evidence compiled by the FBI and the Navy.
   The House hearings, scheduled for Dec. 12 and 13, will include
witnesses from the Navy and FBI, Mavroules said.
   ``Let's get it all out on the table,'' he said.
   The House announcement of hearings came one day after the Senate
Amed Services Committee held the first in a series of hearings on
the Iowa incident.
   Navy officials on Thursday defended their conclusion that the
April 19 blast in gun turret No. 2 was ``most likely'' caused by
Hartwig, who had the responsibility of inserting the detonator into
one the battleship's 16-inch guns.
   Hartwig and 46 shipmates died in the explosion on the World War
II-era battleship.
   Rear Adm. Richard Milligan, who oversaw the Navy's technical and
criminal investigation into the blast, testified Thursday that
additional technical tests conducted since he issued his report
Sept. 7 found ``unique foreign material'' on the projectile from
the exploding gun barrel that would not have been present during a
normal firing.
   The new tests identified the material as iron wires coated with
calcium, chlorine and oxygen, which would be produced by ``some
types of non-electronic explosive devices,'' Milligan said in his
statement.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said in a statement that the Navy's conclusion is based
on the premise that Hartwig had the skill and motivation to cause
the explosion and a technical explanation has been ruled out.
   ``If any one of those three legs fails to stand up, the entire
Navy conclusion collapses,'' Aspin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
