<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Kohl     11-17 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Kohl,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Appeals For `Trust' of Neighbors on Reunification</HEAD>
<HEAD>With East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl appealed Friday
for the ``trust of all our neighbors'' in dealings with beleaguered
East Germany.
   Speaking to the Bonn diplomatic corps on the eve of a European
Community summit of Western European leaders in Paris, Kohl also
called for help in making sure East German reforms do not collapse.
   Kohl said he realizes ``anxious questions are being put to the
Germans'' as East Germany heads into an uncertain future, among
them the question of prospects for German reunification.
   ``Our countrymen in the German Democratic Republic (East
Germany) must be able to state clearly which course they want to
take. Whatever their decision is, we will respect it,'' Kohl said.
   ``We need the trust of all our neighbors in East and West'' on
this question.
   He sought to allay any fears that prospects of ever-closer
relations with struggling East Germany could result in the rebirth
of German nationalism.
   ``This is not the birth of a new German nationalism, as some
suspect,'' Kohl said.
   Kohl said West Germany will be consulting with East German
leaders about what kinds of financial assistance Bonn might provide
to help support East Germany's sputtering economy.
   Helping the reform process in East Germany, Poland and Hungary,
``should be the concern for all Europeans,'' Kohl said.
   There has been concern among some West Europeans that events in
East Germany might sidetrack the European Community's moves to
strengthen itself by creating a single barrier-free market in late
1992.
   But Kohl pledged West Germany will ``continue its efforts, in
close cooperation with France and all other European partners, to
enhance European integration.''
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters, who attended the diplomatic
corps reception, said the United States would not be averse to
German reunification if that's what the East Germans choose. But he
stressed that others' view on the matter are also important to
consider, including the Soviet Union's.
   Walters said President Bush ``has said very clearly the United
States has no problem with this providing it can be done
peacefully, which means with some sort of consent from the Soviets,
and through the free choice of the people,'' Walters said.
   ``After all, they have 16 divisions stationed in eastern
Germany,'' he said.
</TEXT>
