<FIRST>r a AM-AZT-AIDS     11-17 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AZT-AIDS,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burroughs Wellcome Seeks To Extend AZT To Those With AIDS Virus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burroughs Wellcome Co. is
seeking federal approval to market its anti-AIDS drug, AZT, to
people who have the AIDS virus but do not yet show signs of the
disease, the company said Friday.
   Permission for wider sales is being sought from the Food and
Drug Administration after clinical studies released in August
showed that AZT slows the onset of AIDs in people infected with the
virus, said company spokeswoman Kathy Bartlett.
   FDA approval for broader use would greatly expand demand for the
drug by extending it to several thousand HIV-infected people, she
said.
   AZT, the only FDA-approved drug for treatment of AIDS in the
United States, can be used now only on patients who show symptoms
of AIDS and those who are critically ill.
   Officials said there was no timetable for when the FDA might
approve the request.
   Meanwhile, Wellcome PLC, the British parent company of Burroughs
Wellcome in London, reported dramatic increases in sales of AZT,
also known as azidothymidne or Retrovir _ up 49 percent to $225
million.
   In September, North Carolina-based Burroughs Wellcome announced
a 20 percent price cut that effectively reduced the drug's retail
price from $8,000 per year per patient to $6,400.
   But Ms. Bartlett said there are no plans for another price cut
even if use of the drug is extended.
   AIDS activists have criticized Wellcome for reaping huge profits
from AZT, but the company has never disclosed financial results
from the drug.
   ``Our research work with this drug is by no means over, and it
will continue to absorb substantial (research and development)
resources,'' the company said in a statement Thursday.
   In the past year, Wellcome spent $317.5 million on research and
development. About 36 percent of the research-and-development
budget was spent on antiviral drugs such as AZT, up from 31 percent
in the previous year.
   Wellcome PLC reported Thursday it had posted sales of $2.4
billion in the year ended Aug. 26, up from $2.2 billion the
previous year. The company reported net income of $279.2 million,
or 33 cents per share, up from $223.7 million, or 27 cents per
share.
   Burroughs Wellcome accounted for about $1.5 billion, or 64
percent, of Wellcome's sales.
   Zovirax, an antiviral treatment for genital herpes, remains
Wellcome's leading seller at $492.2 million, up 36 percent.
</TEXT>
