<SECOND>AM-Polish-Ambassador,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Official Says Polish Ambassador Expected to be Replaced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Polish ambassador to Washington is
expected to leave by the end of the year to make room for someone
who ``better symbolizes the changes taking place in Poland,''
according to a senior Solidarity figure traveling with Lech Walesa.
   ``There are a number of names under consideration, but nothing
is settled yet,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``Because of our need for U.S. assistance, it is felt
that we need in Washington a figure who better symbolizes the
changes taking place in Poland.''
   The current ambassador, former deputy foreign minister Jan
Kinast, is a holdover from the Communist administration that was
replaced in Warsaw last August by the Solidarity-led government.
   Westerners in Warsaw also have picked up signals that Kinast may
be replaced by the end of the year, but say that the Solidarity
prime minister, Tadeusz Mazowiecki, ``plays cards very close to his
chest'' and has said publicly that there will be no purge of the
diplomatic corps.
   Walesa, during his visit this week to Washington, went out of
his way to reassure Kinast and other Communist Party members
working at the embassy that the Solidarity government has no plans
to withdraw him.
   But because of Kinast's association with the previous communist
government, he is likely to be replaced, said the Solidarity figure
who accompanied Walesa on his week-long visit to the United States.
   Polish embassy officials interviewed during the Walesa visit
said Communist Party members assigned to the embassy were bending
over backwards to faithfully represent the interests of the first
non-Communist government in the Soviet bloc.
   The embassy officials, who also spoke on condition of anonymity,
said Solidarity had not assigned watchdogs to monitor the
activities of Poland's overseas embassies.
   They also noted that Mazowiecki had said repeatedly in public
that Communist Party officials employed in the diplomatic corps and
other branches of government would be given a chance to show
loyalty to the state and would not be purged simply because of
party membership.
</TEXT>
