<DOCNO> AP891117-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 2138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Slayings     11-17 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Slayings,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Police Captain Names Officials as Part of Death Squad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former police captain said
high-ranking members of the national police were part of a death
squad that killed government opponents and staged terrorist attacks
in six countries, a newspaper reported Friday.
   Anti-apartheid figures said they were not suprised at the
allegations published by the Afrikaans-language Free Weekly
newspaper, since there have been dozens of unsolved killings of
activists and bombings of anti-government organizations in the past
10 years.
   Dirk Johannes Coetzee, who left the police force in 1986, was
quoted as telling the Free Weekly, ``I was the commander of the
assassination squad of the South African Police. My men and I
killed and eliminated political enemies of the government.''
   Coetzee said five death squad units were formed in 1980, all
based at a farm near Pretoria, where the government acknowledged
that former guerrillas were housed and made part of an anti-terror
unit.
   Coetzee said he left the squad in 1982 and that its activities
continued after he left the police force.
   The interview was conducted in Mauritius, where Coetzee said he
fled a week ago after being named by a former black security
policeman, Butana Nofomela, as being part of the death squad.
   Nofomela was spared from death row after giving information
about the operation and the long-unsolved killings of political
activists.
   Coetzee corroborated Nofomela's story that a police unit killed
black anti-apartheid lawyer Griffiths Mxenge in Durban in 1982,
poisoning his guard dogs, mutilating his body and trying to make it
look like a robbery.
   The newspaper also quoted Coetzee as saying:
   _ Security police smuggled explosives into Britain that were
used to blow up the African National Congress offices there in 1982.
   _ The death squad was responsible for the 1982 assassination of
Ruth First, wife of South African Communist Party leader Joe Slovo
and the highest ranking white member of the ANC.
   _ Several prisoners were poisoned with a special concoction
developed by a police general.
   _ Prisoners were shot or stabbed to death, then their bodies
were burned and the ashes scattered into rivers.
   _ Bombs were set in public places, and in one case, killed a
child.
   He said actions were carried out in Lesotho, Botswana,
Swaziland, Mozambique, Britain and South Africa.
   Maj. Gen. Herman Stadler, head of the police public relations
division, said, ``It seems strange that Capt. Coetzee, who several
years ago was suspended from the South African police, now makes
these untested and wild allegations from a foreign country where he
cannot be questioned to verify his claims.''
   Stadler said the allegations would be investigated.
   While Stadler said Coetzee was suspended, the newspaper said
Coetzee left under a medical discharge and that it had seen the
discharge papers.
   ``I know all the secrets of this unit, which is above the law,''
Coetzee was quoted as saying. ``I myself am guilty or at least an
accomplice to several murders.''
   Regarding the murder of Ms. First, Coetzee said his union broke
into a U.N. office in Swaziland, stole an envelope with an official
seal on it, and used it to mail a letter bomb that killed Ms. First
in Maputo, Mozambique.
   He identified more than a dozen other officers, including the
former head of the security police, a current police general,
brigadiers, and others who have since been promoted to high ranks
in the police force, as having knowledge of or participating in the
death squad activities.
   The South African Council of Churches, whose headquarters was
blown up in a case that remains unsolved, said in a statement that
Coetzee's story ``comes as no surprise to us. We have repeatedly
called for the police to include themselves in whatever
investigations they may conduct on the attacks of anti-apartheid
people and their property.''
   The anti-apartheid Democratic Party called for a judicial
commission, recommended that all the officers named by Coetzee be
suspended from duty, and said the charges ``undermine completely
the credibility of the police.''
   The African National Congress office in London said Coetzee's
report of the 1982 bombing there ``requires immediate action by the
British government.'' It called for the South African Embassy to be
closed.
   The British Foreign Office said it would await the results of a
South African investigation.
</TEXT>
