<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Berlin 1stLd-Writethru a0584 11-17 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Berlin, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0584,0827</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Berliners Begin a Second Weekend Exploring the West</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with East Germans arriving, color, details.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of East Germans snacked
in the streets and gazed into the windows of electronics stores
Friday night as they began a second weekend celebrating
theirnew-found freedom in West Berlin.
   Although the city was busier than usual as the visitors from the
East began pouring in, there was little of the tumultuous street
party atmosphere that engulfed the western sector a week ago.
   City officials said 500,000 East Germans had arrived in West
Berlin by Friday night.
   ``We'd like to stay all night and make a party,'' said
18-year-old East Berliner Ellen Eversberg. ``But already we can see
a party here costs a lot of money.''
   Ms. Eversberg and two friends were picking up free maps set out
in the lobby of a bank. They planned to go home after a look around
and return in the morning to line up at banks for their 100 marks
($54) in welcome money.
   For the second straight weekend, West Berlin banks will open
Saturday and Sunday to dispense the welcome money.
   Electronics stores in the Kurfuerstsendamm, the main shopping
street, were closed like most other stores by evening, but they
attracted the biggest groups of window-shoppers.
   The aroma of grilled bratwurst drifted across the sidewalks from
steet stalls.
   On the steps of the bomb-scarred Church of Remembrance, two men,
each clutching a can of beer, chanted ``East Berlin _ there is no
wall!''
   Outside the offices of Berliner Morgenpost, the main daily
newspaper, staffers dispensed free coffee to lines of East
Berliners.
   ``We'd like East Germans to get to know us,'' one said as the
new arrivals started curiously at the displays of Friday's edition.
   At Checkpoint Charlie on the Berlin Wall, a steady trickle of
Trabbi cars and pedestrians moved through.
   At a U.S. Army base at Mariendorf in the west of the city,
American troops set up a soup kitchen, at the requst of the West
German authorities, to feed 1,400 East German families who want to
stay permanently.
   The families were being sent to government reception centers for
the night.
   As West Berliners girded for the influx, there were signs that
the welcome mat might be wearing a bit thin.
   ``Of course, it's a wonderful thing they are free to come
here,'' said Gertie Starke, manager of an upmarket clothing store,
Heinemann, on the Kurfuerstendamm.
   ``But commercially it's a disaster. Our customers are simply not
prepared to come into town with these sort of crowds. They've been
driven out, and if this keeps up we can forget Christmas.''
   Last week, immmediately after East Germany's abrupt decision
Nov. 9 to let its citizens travel freely, 1.3 million East Germans
poured in and West Berlin, already crowded home to 2 million,
turned into a giant street party.
   This weekend, it could be even better _ or worse depending on
one's perspective.
   Heinemann, where a cashmere jacket costs about $680, has the
sort of customers who don't need to go where shopping means
fighting for space on the sidewalk.
   And it has absolutely nothing for customers whose spending power
consists of the once-a-year welcome money from the West German
government.
   But others were adapting. Street stalls selling nail polish,
trinkets, oranges and bananas proliferated.
   Electronic goods stores spent the week organizing stock of cheap
items they don't stock normally, such as no-frills portable stereos
at $25.
   And there were are the Levi jeans posters for those who can't
afford to go home with the real thing _ the ultimate badge of
Western consumerism.
   Ron Marcus, who runs a large jeans store, stocked up with
several thousand Levi posters. He said he was opening an additional
section on Saturday selling T-shirts and, for East Germans only,
half-price jeans at $35.
   ``They just freaked out over the jeans last weekend,'' said
Marcus. ``But most of them haven't got money for anything, so we
thought of the posters as something we could do.''
   Fast-food chains, which are within the range of East German
pockets, were laying in for a seige.
   McDonald's manager Martin Meissner ran job ads for part-time
helpers through the week, but got a poor response,. He said he was
offering double time to keep the regular staff on 12 and 24 hours
shifts.
   ``The East Germans have turned our worst month of the year into
the best,'' said Meissner.
   Hurbert Plura, who has a pretzel stall on the sidewalk, was also
prepared. Last weekend, Plura was home an hour after he set up the
stall _ the time it took to sell his day's supply of 500 pretzels.
He's ordered 4,000 for this weekend.
</TEXT>
