<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-CubaMiGs     11-17 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Cuba MiGs,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say MiG Delivery to Cuba Normal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry said Friday that U.S.
complaints about the delivery of MiG-29 warplanes to Cuba were an
attempt to worsen relations on the eve of the Bush-Gorbachev
summit, Tass reported.
   Presidents Bush and Mikhail S. Gorbachev are to meet Dec. 2-3
for a shipboard summit off the Mediterranean island of Malta.
   The State Department complained Wednesday that shipping MiGs to
Cuba was ``wholly inconsistent'' with Moscow's stated desire to
promote peace in Central America. Department spokesman Richard
Boucher would not say how many MiGs the Soviets were sending.
   Gennady Gerasimov, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, said two
training MiGs had been delivered to Cuba as part of an agreement
signed several years ago. ``The U.S.S.R. is not undertaking
anything in Cuba which would violate'' a 1962 agreement with the
United States, the official news agency quoted him as saying.
   Gerasimov apparently meant the agreement that ended the Cuban
missile crisis, which prohibits the Soviets from giving Cuba
nuclear weapons capability. Some MiGs are capable of carring
nuclear weapons.
