<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 2246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     11-17 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamil Militants Attack Police Stations, 27 Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavily armed Tamil militants attacked
four police stations Friday in eastern Sri Lanka and 27 people were
killed, military officials said.
   The simultaneous attacks that began before dawn in the Ampara
district, 125 miles east of the capital Colombo, were launched by a
new Tamil militia called the Tamil National Army, said the
officials who cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   Government officials say the illegal militia was formed as fears
of attacks by Tamil guerrilla groups increased with the ongoing
departure of Indian troops ahead of a Dec. 31 deadline.
   The troops were first sent more than two years ago as part of a
peace plan aimed at ending the insurgency. Members of the Tamil
minority claim discrimination by the Sinhalese majority, and Tamil
rebels are fighting for autonomy in the north and east.
   At least eight police and four soldiers were killed and 40 more
were wounded in the fighting at Kalmunai, Sammanturai, Akkaripattu
and Chavalakady, the officials said without elaborating. At least
24 militants were wounded, they said.
   The villages are in a radius of 15 miles from Ampara, the town
that bears the same name as the district.
   The attacks continued for nine hours, they said. Rockets,
machine guns and rocket-propelled grenades were used, they said.
   Three helicopter gunships strafed the area, providing cover to
troop reinforcements sent to the beseiged police stations, the
officials said.
   Residents in Ampara and Batticaloa, 30 miles further north, said
schools, shops and offices had closed and streets were deserted.
The residents, contacted by telephone, spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The Tamil National Army is believed to have been set up by three
former rebel groups that control the Northeastern Provincial
Council, the local government.
   Officials said the militants killed at least four policemen and
wounded five more in scattered attacks in Ampara during the week.
   India deployed an estimated 47,000 soldiers under the terms of a
July 1987 peace accord that sought to end a Tamil rebellion for a
separate homeland by providing limited political autonomy to the
Tamil minority.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people and allege discrimination in jobs and education
by the Sinhalese, who are predominantly Buddhist and make up 75
percent of the population and control the government and the
military.
   The Indian soldiers were initially deployed to supervise an arms
surrender but became involved in a guerrilla war when the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the dominant militant group,
reneged on the agreement.
   Days after all Indian soldiers withdrew from Ampara district
last month, Tamil Tigers raided two camps of the Tamil National
Army and at least 33 people were killed, prompting the government
to deploy 900 troops in the district.
   About 900 more soldiers were sent to Ampara this week after the
Tamil National Army attacked the camps of Eelam Revolutionary
Organization of Students, another rival group.
   More than 1,100 Indian soldiers have been killed since 1987, in
addition to the more than 10,000 Sri Lankans who have died in the
insurgency that started in 1983.
   India joined the peace effort on the island off its southern
coast because of its role as a regional power and the concerns of
the politically powerful 60 million Tamil minority in India.
</TEXT>
