<FIRST>u i AM-SovietStrikes     11-17 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Strikes,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Premier, Striking Coal Miners Have Heated Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a heated meeting Friday with Premier Nikolai I.
Ryzhkov, striking coal miners said the government is not keeping
its promises to improve their working and living conditions, the
Tass news agency reported.
   It said that during the meeting in the Kremlin, the miners
demanded that officials responsible for the lack of progress be
punished.
   Tass said Ryzhkov told the miners each side must ``bear its
share of responsibility.'' It indicated the premier stopped short
of directly asking the 15,000 miners from the Soviet Arctic to
return to work.
   Miners began the walkout Oct. 25 at 12 of the 13 mines near
Vorkuta, 950 miles northeast of Moscow, to press the government to
fulfill promised increases in pensions and wage differentials for
hazardous working conditions and improvements in living conditions.
The government made the promises to end strikes that affected
virtually all the country's coalfields in July.
   In renewing their walkout, the Vorkuta miners added political
demands, including removing language in the Soviet Constitution
making the Communist Party the leading force of society. They also
demand that power be turned over to local governing councils, land
to farmers and factories to workers.
   They have defied earlier appeals by Ryzhkov, President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev and other officials to return to work, even though the
strike is depleting fuel supplies as the country heads into winter.
   Tass reported Ryzhkov told the miners at the meeting held in a
``heated atmosphere'' that the strikes have caused a shortfall of
14 million tons of coal.
   He said pension increases for miners and longer vacations were
provided for in legislation now before the Soviet legislature,
according to Tass.
   It reported the miners' representatives said ``significant
changes in the (coal) sphere and the solution of social problems of
miners have not yet occurred.''
   ``More than once at the meeting demands were heard to punish
those who hinder or delay'' improvements, Tass said.
   Miners who attended the meeting could not be reached for
comment. Soviet authorities have refused to permit The Associated
Press to visit Vorkuta _ an area long closed to foreigners.
   On Tuesday, the miners lost an appeal of a court ruling that
their strike was illegal. The decision by the Supreme Court of the
Russian Federation, the republic where the miners are from, means
the strike organizers face firing from their jobs and fines of
$1,620 each.
   Soviet reports have said Vorkuta's electricity and heating
supplies are threatened because of a coal shortage and First Deputy
Premier Lev Voronin warned that rationing may be necessary.
</TEXT>
