<FIRST>u w AM-DrugMoney     11-17 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Money,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Returns $4.6 Million in Seized Cash to Houston Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thorburgh returned
nearly $4.6 million in confiscated drug revenues to the Houston
Police Department on Friday, saying ``booty of the drug trade can
be turned into offensive weapons for law enforcement.''
   Thornburgh's decision personally to present a check for the $4.6
million to Assistant Police Chief Dennis Storemski ``sends a
signal'' that Houston is being recognized as one of the major
points for illegal drugs entering the country, said Rep. Jack
Fields, R-Texas.
   But Thornburgh declined to say whether the Justice Department
would recommend Houston and the Texas-Mexico border be declared a
high-intensity drug trafficking zone, which would make the region
eligible for increased federal help in attacking the narcotics
trade.
   The $4.6 million returned to Houston was seized in a joint
investigation earlier this year involving the Internal Revenue
Service and Houston police.
   A two-week, around-the-clock surveillance led to raids on two
``stash houses'' in which $4 million in cash was seized. Another
$1.69 million was taken from a vehicle. The federal government gets
to keep part of such seized cash, in this case slightly more than
$1 million.
   ``We're here to illustrate a new twist on an old maxim _ that
is, to illustrate the notion that crime does pay for effective law
enforcement,'' Thornburgh said.
   Storemski said the money would be used to pay informants and to
buy vehicles, surveillance equipment and other equipment.
   Since its creation in 1985, the Asset Forfeiture Fund has shared
more than $290 million with local and state agencies.
</TEXT>
