<FIRST>u w AN-Salvador-Forensic     11-17 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AN-Salvador-Forensic,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Says Forensic Investigation Has Begun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-trained team of Salvadoran forensic
experts has begun an investigation of the slaying of six Jesuit
priests and two others in El Salvador, the State Department said
Friday.
   ``Regardless of who the perpetrators are, we want punishment for
those attempting to hinder the process of peace and democracy in El
Salvador,'' said spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   She noted that Salvadoran President Alfredo Christiani had
assured U.S. Ambassador William Walker that even if members of the
Salvadoran armed forces were involved, ``they will feel the full
weight of the law.''
   ``The United States expects him to meet that commitment,'' said
Ms. Tutwiler.
   She said U.S. officials ``will certainly be forthcoming in our
help'' if asked by the Salvadoran government to assist directly in
the investigation.
   ``The special investigative unit ... is equipped and trained and
funded by the United States,'' Ms. Tutwiler told reporters. ``It is
conducting a forensic examination of this crime, and they have,
it's my understanding, already taken samples from the scene and
will conduct the autopsies.''
   She said the unit was formed about six years ago.
   ``When it has been deployed, it has been effective,'' Ms.
Tutwiler said, recalling that in one case its investigation had led
to the arrest of two army officers and seven soldiers, who are in
jail awaiting trial.
   She said she was unable to confirm or deny reports that
witnesses had said they had seen men in uniform enter the Jesuit
rectory before the slayings.
   She said there were no American advisers out in the field with
the investigative unit.
   Ms. Tutwiler said the State Department had heard reports that
threats were made against the Jesuits in a national radio call-in
program before the slayings.
   ``We condemn that call for violence as we condemn, in the
strongest possible terms, the tragic killings themselves,'' she
said.
