<SECOND>AM-Britain-Rushdie,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>BBC Television Told to Give Police Film of Anti-Rushdie Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ordered the British
Broadcasting Corp. on Friday to give police the television film of
a rally at which Moslems allegedly raised their hands in favor of
killing novelist Salman Rushdie.
   The BBC had refused the police request, but said it would comply
with the ruling by Judge Michael Sachs of the Manchester High Court.
   The film showed a rally in Manchester last month at which
Moslems were allegedly asked to vote on whether Rushdie should die
for the ``blasphemy'' against Islam contained in his novel ``The
Satanic Verses,'' and some raised their hands in favor.
   Manchester police asked prosecutors to consider criminal
proceedings and the prosecutors asked police to obtain transmitted
and untransmitted film of the rally.
   ``The judge viewed a section of the tape and ruled it was
relevant. He ordered it to be handed over and the BBC will comply
with that order,'' said a spokesman for the BBC's Manchester office.
   He would not say the material to be given to police had been
included in a report the BBC broadcast Oct. 21. The hearing before
the judge was closed.
   The spokesman, who requested anonymity, said the standing policy
of all British broadcasters was to refuse to provide film to
authorities.
   ``If the BBC was to allow automatic access to untransmitted
material, our own staff could become victims in hostile actions,
and ... we have a duty to protect our staff and thereby safeguard
our ability to cover the news,'' he said.
   Rushdie has been in hiding since February, when the late
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini of Iran declared that he had committed
blasphemy in ``The Satanic Verses'' and ordered his followers to
kill the novelist.
</TEXT>
