<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Flight103 1stLd-Writethru   11-17 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0693,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skies Still Not Safe, Say Flight 103 Victims' Relatives</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 14-15: ``Mrs. McLaughlin,'' with McLaughlin ties
to Flight 103</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven months after the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 over Scotland, the government and airlines still are
endangering lives with lax aviation security, relatives of the
flight victims told a presidential commission Friday.
   ``The confidence of the public has been badly shaken and will
not return until the truth is told and remedies are put into
place,'' said Paul Hudson, whose 16-year-old daughter was one of
270 people killed in the Dec. 21, 1988, bombing.
   The seven-member Presidential Commission on Aviation Security
and Terrorism held the first of several hearings into government
conduct before and after the destruction of the Boeing 747 airliner
by plastic explosives concealed in a radio-cassette player. British
investigators blame the bombing on terrorists whom they have not
identified.
   ``We won't let you down,'' Commission Chairwoman Ann McLaughlin
told relatives of Americans who died in the crash. The former labor
secretary said the commission would evaluate aviation security, the
handling of terrorist threats against air travel and whether the
public should be told of them, and the government's treatment of
terrorists' victims.
   ``We will let the chips fall where they may,'' Mrs. McLaughlin
said. The commission is to make recommendations to President Bush
in May. The panel, which has a $1 million budget for six months,
includes four members of Congress and two prominent military men.
   The panel also is considering the similar destruction of a
French UTA DC-10 over the African country of Niger on Sept. 19,
which killed 174 people, including seven Americans. The goal is to
find ways of protecting U.S. citizens who fly on foreign carriers.
   Alexander Alimanestianu of New York City, whose father, Mihai,
died aboard the Chad-Paris flight, compared aviation terrorists to
serial murderers. ``We know the next one is being plotted right now
_ another bomb, another plane; it's just a matter of time,'' he
said.
   In other testimony at the daylong hearing:
   _Richard Lally, vice president of the Air Transport Association,
which represents U.S. airlines, said the government should pay for
improved bomb-detection devices and asked for ratification of a
treaty that will give U.S. victims of air terrorism greater
compensation.
   _Christopher Witkowski of the Aviation Consumer Action Project
said aviation security is inadequate because it has been planned by
``a close-knit group of industry representatives and the FAA''
without passenger involvement.
   _Billie H. Vincent, former FAA security director, said aviation
security is ``seriously deficient'' in high-threat areas such as
Europe and the Middle East.
   _Peter Reiss of the Air Line Pilots Association said a thermal
neutron analysis device like the ones the FAA has ordered U.S.
airlines to install at airports throughout the world would not have
detected the Flight 103 bomb without disrupting airline schedules
with false alarms. He said the technology has to be improved before
it can be used widely.
   Relatives of the more than 180 Americans killed in the Pan Am
bombing have formed a nationwide group that had asked for a
full-scale congressional investigation.
   Mrs. McLaughlin said she had ties to three victims of Flight
103: a cousin, Bernie McLaughlin; J.D. Flynn, a son of a college
classmate, and Karen Noonan, a college student who worked in her
office when she was secretary of labor.
   Mrs. McLaughlin said this gave a personal dimension to her
interest in aviation security but said she had never joined the
relatives' organization. She said she was picked to head the
commission because of her government experience.
   ``The American government has broken faith with its citizens. It
has turned its back on its responsibility to protect the lives of
American citizens at home and abroad,'' said Bert Ammerman,
president of the group. He had a brother aboard Flight 103, which
had just left London en route from Frankfurt to New York City when
it blew up.
   Victoria Cummock of Coral Gables, Fla., held up the badly
damaged attache case of her husband, who died aboard the flight,
and said, ``Ladies and gentlemen, this is what remains of John
Cummock.''
   Mrs. Cummock said she wanted the commission to feel the effects
of the disaster on her ``all-American family'' so the bombing would
not be considered just an ``unfortunate isolated incident or an
inconvenience in a system that occasionally goes on the blink.''
   Members of the commission include Sens. Frank R. Lautenberg,
D-N.J., and Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.; Reps. James Oberstar, D-Minn.,
and John Hammerschmidt, R-Ark.; former Assistant Navy Secretary
Edward Hidalgo and retired Air Force Gen. Thomas C. Richards.
</TEXT>
