<FIRST>r i AM-Lithuania     11-17 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lithuania,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lithuanian Communists Meet, Argue with Kremlin Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lithuanian Communist Party leaders who seek a
multiparty system and some independence said Friday that President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev appeared angry during a 7{-hour meeting to
which the Politburo summoned them.
   But Algirdas Brazauskas, first secretary of the Lithuanian
party, told Lithuanian television the meeting Thursday ``went well;
it was successful.''
   Brazauskas and the entire Lithuanian party leadership met with
the national party's ruling Politburo in Moscow.
   Kestutas Zalauskas, party chief in the Vilnius, the Lithuanian
capital, told the republic's presidium that, when the meeting
began, ``Gorbachev was sitting with a very angry face, but at the
end of the meeting everything calmed down,'' said Longinas
Vasiliauskas, a party member who heard Zalauskas' report.
   Brazauskas said he told the Kremlin leaders Lithuanian
Communists must ``have a program that is acceptable to the people
and understandable to them'' for local elections scheduled in
February.
   Sajudis, the Lithuanian People's Front, trounced regular
Communist Party candidates in the Soviet Union's first multiple
candidate elections last spring. Sajudis candidates, including
Communist Party dissidents, won 36 of the 42 parliamentary seats in
the Lithuanian republic.
   The Lithuanian Communist Party has called a special congress for
Dec. 19 to prepare for the election and consider a program designed
to make the party ``a political force in the creation of an
independent, law-governed Lithuanian state.''
   A draft of the program endorses a multiparty system and creation
of a democratic socialist society. It does not call for secession
from the Soviet Union but would establish ``a sovereign Lithuanian
state that has cultural and economic ties with the U.S.S.R.'' It
makes no mention of political ties.
   The congress also will consider splitting the Lithuanian
Communist Party from the Soviet Communist Party, a move strongly
opposed by Gorbachev.
   Brazauskas said in the television interview that the Lithuanian
party's entire Central Committee will face election at the congress
to ensure that it represents party members.
   Zalauskas told the presidium the Moscow meeting centered on the
Soviet Politburo's objection to any separation of the Soviet and
Lithuanian parties, according to Vasiliauskas.
   He said Brazauskas calmed the Soviets by promising there would
be no immediate split, but the Lithuanians also told the Kremlin
leaders that ``democratization has gone so deep in Lithuania that
not everything depends on the Communist Party anymore.''
   The Kremlin has always maintained an element of control over the
Communist Parties in the various republics, naming its own man to
the number two spot and influencing the selection of the first
secretary.
   A report by the Tass news agency said Thursday's meeting
stressed ``the special responsibility which rests on the Lithuanian
Communist Party as one of the detachments of the Communist Party of
the Soviet Union.''
</TEXT>
