<HEAD>Former South Carolina Governor Among Bush Nominees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Friday announced he would
nominate former South Carolina Gov. James B. Edwards to serve on
the board of directors of the Communications Satellite Corp.
   Edwards, president of the Medical University of South Carolina
in Charleston, would serve until 1992 if confirmed by the Senate.
   Edwards, 62, who served as governor from 1975-81, would succeed
Michael A. McManus Jr.
   Bush also said he would elevate John J. Maresca, 51, who heads
the U.S. delegation to international talks in Stockholm on easing
East-West tensions, to the rank of ambassador.
   He is a former deputy assistant secretary of defense for
European and NATO policy and was officer in charge of NATO
political affairs at the State Department before getting his
current post in 1988.
   Bush also announced his intention to nominate Jerome G. Cooper
of Mobile, Ala., to be assistant secretary of the Air Force for
Manpower and Reserve Affairs. If confirmed by the Senate, he would
succeed Karen R. Keesling.
   Bush also announced he would nominate:
   _J. Steven Rhodes to be ambassador to Zimbabwe. Rhodes, 38, is
managing director of the public finance office of Smith Barney in
Los Angeles. He would succeed James Wilson Rawlings.
   _Robert William Farrand, a career diplomat, to be ambassador to
Papua New Guinea, Solomon Islands and to the Republic of Vanuatu.
Farrand, 55, of McLean, Va., has been senior deputy assistant
secretary of state for human rights since 1987. He would succeed
Everett E. Bierman.
   _Carol Mayer Marshall, 54, a San Francisco attorney and
consultant, to be superintendent of the U.S. Mint at San Francisco,
a new position.
   _Gail Roggin Wilensky, 46, to be administrator of the Health
Care Financing Administration. Currently vice president of the
health affairs for Project Hope in Chevy Chase, Md., she would
succeed William L. Roper.
   _John W. Lyons to be director of the National Institute of
Standards and Technology. Lyons, 59, has served as director of the
National Engineering Laboratory at the National Bureau of Standards
since 1983. He lives in Mt. Airy, Md. He would succeed Ernest
Ambler.
   _Robert F. Gilbert of Laconia, N.H., to be U.S. marshal for the
district of New Hampshire. Since 1983, Gilbert, 49, has been
sheriff of Belknap County, N.H. He would succeed Ronald D. Daniels
Jr.
