<FIRST>u i AM-Greece 1stLd-Writethru a0647 11-17 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Left, Right Meet on Forming Government; Street Clashes Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to include no deal reached and Athens riot
report; picks up 6th `Political observers ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the three main political
parties tried to form a joint government Friday, but failed,
increasing the possibility that a third election will follow two
that have ended in deadlock.
   ``The political consultations will continue on Monday at noon,''
conservative leader Constantine Mitsotakis of the New Democracy
party told reporters afterward.
   He met with Andreas Papandreou, the former Socialist premier,
and Communist leader Harilaos Florakis. Since the Nov. 5 elections,
each has failed in a separate effort to form a coalition with a
majority in the 300-set Parliament.
   None of the three indicated whether progress was ade on Friday.
   If the three leaders cannot get together, President Christos
Sartzetakis is expected to call another election.
   Police meanwhile fought running battles Friday in central Athens
with youths who rioted on the fringes of a march commemorating a
student uprising Nov. 17, 1973.
   Three riot policemen and a reporter were slightly injured by
stones thrown by about 200 rioters who firebombed a police bus, a
department store and the entrance of an apartment block.
   More than 20 young people were killed in the revolt at the
Athens Polytechnic. The military regime collapsed in 1974 after
seven years in power.
   During Friday's melee, the rioters built burning roadblocks and
smashed the windows of six banks. Police said no one was arrested.
   Political observers believe the results of the next election
would be the same: no one party would win enough seats in the
300-member Parliament to govern alone.
   In the Nov. 5 balloting, New Democracy took 148 seats, three
short of an absolute majority, Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist
Movement won 128 and the Coalition garnered 21. Two independents
and an environmentalist took the remaining three seats.
   On June 18, elections also failed to produce a winner. A
conservative-communist government led the country until the
November elections.
   All three political leaders have said they want to avoid new
elections but differ on its goals and duration.
   Mitsotakis and Florakis said they favor an all-party government
that would govern until March when presidential elections will make
another poll mandatory if no candidate receives at least 180 votes
in Parliament.
   According to the constitution, new elections are called if
Parliament fails to choose a President. The newly elected
Parliament can then pick a president with a simple majority vote.
   Papandreou agrees with Florakis the electoral system should be
replaced by simple proportional representation, but Mitsotakis says
such a change would create unstable governments.
   The three parties are also divided over negotiations with the
United States on the continued presence of their military
installations in the country. A U.S.-Greek defense accord expired
in December.
   Despite 17 rounds of negotiations with a PASOK government before
it failed to be re-elected in June after eight years in office, the
bases issue remains unsolved.
   Papandreou said he wants one more round of negotiations before
the draft agreement is put to a national referendum. The
communist-led coalition said it would support an all-party
government only if the U.S. bases were shut down while Mitsotakis
said retaining the bases is vital to Greece's security.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
