<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     11-17 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill 5, Including 2 Newly Elected Mayors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels killed five people, including
two newly elected mayors, authorities said Friday.
   The slayings Thursday brought to more than 135 the number of
officials and candidates killed by the Maoist rebel movement
Shining Path in an attempt to disrupt elections.
   Hundreds of officials have resigned out of fear, but millions of
Peruvians voted in municipal elections Sunday despite rebel threats.
   Mayor-elect Rosario Gomez of Uco, 185 miles north of Lima, was
shot down with three other people in the town plaza after a brief
``people's trial,'' said Domingo Huaman, an official of Ancash
state.
   Huaman said Gomez was elected on the ticket of the center-right
Democratic Front, a coalition supporting novelist Mario Vargas
Llosa, the front-runner in April's presidential election.
   Police said Shining Path rebels also assassinated Bendezu
Guillen, mayor-elect of San Juan de Castrovirreyna, 140 miles
southeast of Lima. Guillen was a member of the Aprista Party of
President Alan Garcia.
   Garcia said Thursday the Shining Path was ``probably looking for
a way to ruin the festival of democracy that was celebrated Sunday
throughout the country.''
   The National Elections Board said Friday that figures on the
total number of votes cast still were not available.
   The Shining Path began its insurgency in 1980 near Ayacucho and
now operates throughout the Andean highlands and in the
coca-producing jungles of the northeast. More than 15,500 people
have been killed, according to government figures.
</TEXT>
