<FIRST>u w AM-Poindexter     11-17 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poindexter,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Says Reagan Subpoena Requires His Testimony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department regards a subpoena for
President Reagan in the Iran-Contra case of John Poindexter as a
demand for his testimony as well as for documents, a department
spokesman said Friday.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said the Justice Department was
considering how to respond to Poindexter's subpoena for Reagan, but
declined to say whether or not the government would move to quash
it.
   ``That's a matter under consideration,'' Thornburgh said. ``We
have the judge's order and we are examining it in connection with
President Reagan's counsel.'' Telephone calls to the office of
Reagan lawyer Theodore Olson were not returned.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said that ``we think''
the subpoena for Reagan ``calls for his testimony'' as well as for
documents. The national security adviser's trial is scheduled to
start Jan. 22.
   The subpoena demands that Reagan turn over certain documents
next Wednesday.
   On Thursday, U.S. District Court Judge Harold Greene approved
Poindexter's subpoena to Reagan and a separate one to the archivist
of the United States, who has possession of presidential documents
from the Reagan administration.
   Ex-national security adviser Poindexter is accused of
conspiracy, two counts of obstructing Congress and two counts of
making false statements. He says that many of the activities for
which he is now accused of crimes were authorized by Reagan and has
issued the subpoenas in an attempt to help bolster that assertion.
</TEXT>
