<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Visitors     11-17 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Visitors,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Pour Into West Germany, Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They brought downtown Luebeck to
a near standstill, snatched up pineapples in Bavaria, and sipped
tea handed out by British soldiers in West Berlin. The East Germans
were back in force.
   Officials said late Friday that more than 1.2 million East
Germans had already poured into West Germany and West Berlin for a
second consecutive weekend of shopping and sightseeing.
   East Germany's official news agency ADN said the rush to the
West had reached ``a critical point,'' with traffic jams at all the
major crossing points into West Germany.
   West Germans, still a little bewildered by the deluge, did
everything they could to make the visitors feel welcome.
   Strict weekend store-closing laws were suspended in border
states, city tours were organized and stores stocked up on
clothing, fruits and other items that have long been only a dream
for East Germans.
   In Bad Homburg outside Frankfurt, hotels and pensions were
providing free rooms to the visitors, who also received bananas,
kiwis and oranges, courtesy of a local supermarket.
   Many downtown areas were wall-to-wall people, as special trains
brought the East Germans into Luebeck and other cities. At times,
the train platforms were so packed with East Germans that no one
could move.
   In West Berlin, West German rock star Udo Lindenberg led a group
of entertainers performing for the visitors, in one of numerous
free concerts nationwide.
   Hundreds of thousands snacked in the streets and gazed into the
windows of electronics stores.
   On the steps of the bomb-scarred Church of Remembrance, two men,
each clutching a can of beer, chanted ``East Berlin _ there is no
wall!''
   More than half of East Germany's 16.5 million people have
obtained exit visas to visit the West the past week, the ADN news
agency said. Last weekend, more than 3 million East Germans visited
the West.
</TEXT>
