<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Fighting     11-17 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Fighting,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Dodge Gunfire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terrified residents dodged
gunfire in smoldering streets Friday, desperately searching for
food and water after a week of battle between soldiers and rebels.
   Fighting slackened in many of the neighborhoods ravaged by the
exchanges of gunfire and government mortar and rocket fire in the
biggest guerrilla offensive of the decade-old civil war.
   Heavy combat continued in the northern district of Mejicanos,
where David Blundy, 44, a British journalist, was fatally wounded.
More than 800 people have been killed and about 2,000 wounded
nationwide in the offensive, according to a partial count by The
Associated Press.
   Officials say they had incomplete casualty figures for
civilians, many of whom have not been able to escape the fighting.
   ``We can no longer keep count of the dead who come in,''said
Juan Casco of the San Salvador city morgue.
   The International Committee of the Red Cross, the European
humanitarian group Doctors Without Borders and the International
Confederation of Free trade Unions called Friday for a temporary
cease-fire to allow the evacuation of wounded civilians.
   In Zacamil, a suburb west of Mejicanos, rebel forces abandoned
positions in a complex of low-income apartment blocks after days of
savage mortar and rocket attacks by government troops.
   By midday, soldiers of the elite Bracamonte Battalion were
moving through the smoldering, partially demolished buildings,
searching for booby-traps or bodies.
   Several thousand Zacamil residents fled in previous days,
staying with relatives, at a nearby church or sleeping in the open.
   In Soyapango, a poor district on the capital's eastern fringe,
guerrilla forces advanced after paratroopers weary from nearly a
week of heavy fighting withdrew.
   Small army patrols circulated cautiously, at times only a block
or two from guerrilla positions.
   Hundreds of residents, many carrying white flags, others with
empty plastic containers, walked the ruined streets in search of
water or a few ounces of beans or bread.
   Water mains have been damaged by the fighting in many
neighborhoods, and virtually all shops and markets have closed.
   ``We have no water! We have no food!'' dozens of people shouted
in Soyapango, surrounding journalists. ``Tell them to bring food
and water! Tell them to evacuate us!''
   A girl about 14 years old lay dead beside one road, surrounded
by residents who said she was hit by a stray bullet on a search for
provisions.
   ``We have nowhere to go,'' said Marcos Quintanilla, out looking
for food for his family. ``We're terrified by the bombardments.
Tell them to stop bombing us.''
   Soyapango has been one of the areas hardest hit by air attacks.
President Alfredo Cristiani's rightist government has been using
its U.S.-supplied helicopters and warplanes to strafe and rocket
guerrilla positions in these neighborhood-strongholds.
   Quintanilla said dozens of people killed around his neighborhood
had been buried in the soccer field, and the bodies of others were
burned to prevent the spread of disease.
   Fidel Chavez Mena, leader the opposition Christian Democratic
Party, told a press conference Friday that more than 300,000 people
_ almost a third of the capital's population _ have been affected
by the fighting.
   Chavez Mena said the devastation is worse than a disastrous 1986
earthquake that killed 1,500 people died in that disaster, and left
nearly 300,000 homeless or with severely damaged homes.
   Reports from the countryside were sketchy. But journalists in
San Miguel, an eastern provincial capital, said by telephone that
combat was heavy in seven neighborhoods.
   Carlos Rodgiguez and his wife Marta were closing up their house
in the devastated eastern section of Soyapango _ until Thursday the
scene of some of the bloodiest house-to-house combat.
   On Thursday, each of the five members of the family had one
``tortilla,'' and few sips of coffee. They had run out of
everything else except a gallon of water.
   The front of their cinderblock home was pocked with bullets and
shrapnel, and part of the roof was blown off. Mrs. Rodriquez
pointed to the banana tree in the front yard.
   ``Look,'' she said. ``Even the poor little bananas are all shot
up.''
</TEXT>
