<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     11-17 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Report Says Detainees Penned `Like Animals' in Afghan Jails</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Afghan government keeps prisoners
penned ``like animals'' in deplorable cells, forced to stand or
squat for up to seven months while they await trial, according to a
U.N. human rights investigator.
   Malnutrition and infant mortality, meanwhile, are running
rampant in areas held by the Islamic rebels and in their refugee
camps in Pakistan, reported Felix Ermacora, a special
representative of the U.N. Commission on Human Rights.
   Both sides are using weapons against civilians, and ``any such
use must be qualified as terrorism,'' he said.
   Ermacora visited Afghanistan, Pakistan and Iran in September and
October to review human rights conditions and the plight of
refugees from the 10-year-old Afghan war.
   In Kabul, he found ``opponents of the regime are still being
tried by special security courts and the procedural guarantees of
the accused are not in conformity with international human rights
instruments.''
   Ermacora said there are still more than 3,000 political
prisoners in Afghanistan, and the conditions of those awaiting
trial are deplorable.
   ``They are kept like animals in small cells or rooms where they
have to stand or squat for an unspecified period of time (often as
long as seven months) behind iron bars, often with insufficient
light,'' he said.
   Ermacora also found what he said were serious human rights
violations by the Islamic rebels, who call themselves the
mujahedeen, or holy warriors.
   He criticized the rebels for their use of U.S.-made cluster
bombs, ``each of which contains 97 smaller time bombs. They
constitute one of the most frightening types of weapon currently
being used in the conflict.''
   In rebel-held areas and in their camps in Pakistan, Ermacora
said he was informed of ``increasing cases of malnutrition, in
particular among the children, due to food shortages.''
   He said 80 percent of the women and children seeking treatment
at the Kuwaiti Hospital for Afghans, in Peshawar, are suffering
from malnutrition.
   Ermacora estimated 5 million Afghans have become refugees, most
of them in Pakistan or Iran.
   The 2.3 million Afghan refugees in Iran mostly live in the major
cities where they are integrated into the population and hold jobs,
he said.
   They are in much better condition than the refugees in Pakistan
or the displaced Afghans still in their own country, who generally
live in overcrowded camps with little opportunity to become
self-reliant, he said.
</TEXT>
