<DOCNO> AP891117-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 2215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Walesa-Poles     11-17 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa-Poles,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Chief Grabs A Moment _ Among His Own</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Walesa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK BAJAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After an exhausting week of accolades from the
powerful of Washington, Lech Walesa spent a brief 40 minutes Friday
among Poles, the editorial staff of the largest Polish daily
newspaper outside Poland.
   He got the usual hero's welcome at Nowy Dziennik: a 10-foot
banner over the entrance to the midtown Manhattan building,
resounding applause as he entered the reception room, a plaque, and
even a ruby-studded 18-karat gold ring from a Polish-American
jeweler.
   The ring was big and Poland's best-known citizen received it
with the usual string of jokes.
   ``I like it a lot,'' he said. ``It looks very pretty and it's
very heavy so it speaks a lot about the greatness of Walesa.''
   The 50 or so people in the room laughed. Walesa, looking
fatigued, then begged for the gifts and praise to end, for some
Pole-to-Pole talk.
   ``How did you feel in Congress?''
   ``Oh, my God,'' he said to another chorus of mirth.
   The Gdansk shipyard worker whose deft negotiating skills helped
turn a labor movement into the political force that dominates
Poland's government took his now-familiar ``I'm just a simple
electrician'' tack.
   ``I have a complex, standing next to all those greats,'' he said
of the political figures he met in Washington. Walesa has said he
was weak-kneed during his address Wednesday to a joint session of
Congress.
   ``But you too are great,'' offered Boleslaw Wierzbianski,
longtime publisher of the 23,000-circulation Nowy Dziennik (Daily
News).
   The paper has worked hard on Solidarity's behalf, raising about
$200,000 for the spring electoral campaign that led to the free
trade union movement's victory in all but one of the races in which
it fielded a candidate.
   When he arrived, Walesa thanked the staff for all its efforts
but asked them not to expect wisdom.
   ``This is my 10th meeting (today) so I'm worn out and I'm going
to speak to you without any deep thought,'' he said. For the first
time all week, a translator was not needed.
   Walesa squirmed out of an answer when asked what three things he
would do first to revive his country's devastated economy: ``I'm
not the government. I'm Lech Walesa, who makes connections.''
   When asked if he didn't fear that the Solidarity-led government
would alienate the very workers who have been its core of support
by closing down huge obsolete factories, he presented his vision of
Poland's future.
   ``I must open tens of thousands of small manufacturers, butcher
shops, bakeries,'' he said. That would offer people more than they
currently are paid working for state-owned enterprises.
   With foreign investors pouring in to do business, ``we'll solve
the problem,'' he said. ``We'll turn the old factories into museums
to Marxism-Leninism.''
   One questioner asked Walesa why he had not yet found a half hour
to talk to the thousands of Poles in New York who not only have
sent millions of dollars to Poland but also voted for Solidarity in
the June elections.
   Walesa appeared a bit hurt but defended his priority for his
first visit to the United States: meeting with bankers,
industrialists and politicians in search of direly needed
investment. ``Our political victory will be for naught if I don't
cement it economically,'' he said.
   ``I apologize to the workers,'' added Walesa, who was to take
time to meet the people at a rally in Chicago on Saturday. ``I
should be in each Polish house, but I simply don't have enough
time.''
   Soon, he was excusing himself, promising:
   ``I'll do everything that I can so you can have two loves,
Poland and America.''
</TEXT>
