<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 2215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ThanksgivingProclamation     11-17 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thanksgiving Proclamation,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Document Declaring Nation's First Thanksgiving Holiday
Is Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Thanksgiving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare document in which George Washington
proclaimed the nation's first Thanksgiving holiday 200 years ago
was recently discovered and went on display Friday.
   The proclamation, dated Oct. 3, 1789, is one of 13 President
Washington sent to the states, but it is the only original known to
exist today, said Herman Darvick, a New York auctioneer of
autographs and historical documents who confirmed its authenticity.
   Peter F. Paul, president of the non-profit American Spirit
Foundation, said he found the proclamation among a collection of
his mother's historical documents and maps about a month ago.
   ``I was so moved by it when I read it. I asked around and
learned this really is something extraordinary,'' Paul said.
   In his proclamation, Washington called for a day of public
thanksgiving and prayer to give thanks to God for giving Americans
``an opportunity peaceably to establish a form of government for
their safety and happiness.''
   The 18-by-26-inch document was put on display Friday at the
Huntington Library, a prestigious institution in San Marino,
Calif., a Los Angeles suburb. With it is a letter signed by
Washington that was sent with the proclamation to Gov. Thomas
Mifflin of Pennsylvania.
   Mary Robertson, curator of manuscripts at the Huntington, said
the museum tries to highlight holidays with historical displays.
   ``This was a little bit unusual in that it's a rare
proclamation,'' she said.
   Darvick confirmed the document's authenticity, based on
comparisons of the paper size and printing quality with other
government proclamations of the period. He estimated it is worth
between $80,000 and $100,000.
   But both Darvick and Paul said the document's real value lies in
what it can teach Americans on the 200th anniversary of the holiday.
   ``Not many Americans know where Thanksgiving originated,'' Paul
said. ``It's one of the most moving and articulate documents to be
published by the government in its history.''
   Libraries at Harvard and Yale, as well as the Morgan Library in
New York, have smaller versions of the document, Darvick said, but
they apparently were copies printed to spread word of the
proclamation.
   Commemorations of the pilgrim's first harvest celebration in
Plymouth Colony in 1621 were held sporadically during colonial
times, but Washington proclaimed the nation's first Thanksgiving
Day for Nov. 26, 1789.
   Abraham Lincoln revived the custom in 1863, proclaiming the last
Thursday of November as Thanksgiving. Beginning in 1939, President
Roosevelt proclaimed Thanksgiving as the third Thursday in
November, but a Congressional resolution in 1941 moved the holiday
to where it has stayed since _ the fourth Thursday of the month.
   Washington's proclamation called on Americans to give thanks for
the end to the Revolutionary War, ``for the peaceable and rational
manner in which we have been enabled to establish constitutions of
government for our safety and happiness and particularly the
national one now lately instituted; for the civil and religious
liberty with which we are blessed, and the means we have acquiring
and diffusing useful knowledge; and in general, for all the great
and various favors which he hath been pleased to confer upon us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
