<FIRST>u w AM-FitzgibbonDetained     11-17 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fitzgibbon Detained,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trenton, N.J., Woman Said Detained in El Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>F WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Trenton, N.J.,
teacher and peace activist working with a volunteer church group
was arrested Friday by Salvadoran troops, her sister told New
Jersey's two U.S. senators.
   Teresa Fitzgibbon, 53, was arrested with two others around noon
Friday, said Peggy Fitzgibbon, a Catholic nun living in Washington.
   Peggy Fitzgibbon said her sister ``had already been twice to
Salvador. She'd been to Honduras to a camp for refugees. When she
went down for the third trip, everybody said, `you're crazy.''
   According to Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., Teresa Fitzgibbon was
part of a Lutheran church group composed of American, Canadian, and
West German doctors and nurses. They had been given sanctuary in a
church to provide medical care to refugees from the fighting in San
Salvador.
   Peggy Fitzgibbon said she learned of her sister's arrest from
Isabel Torres, a Houston woman whose fiance was a member of the
church group and who has been in telephone contact with the group
in El Salvador.
   ``Last night, the Salvadoran National Guard burst in and
arrested a number of those with whom Teresa had been working; this
morning, the remainder of the group, including Teresa, were
detained in the church,'' Bradley said in a statement. ``At latest
report, the church is now surrounded by El Salvadoran military
forces. This is outrageous and intolerable.''
   Bradley said he was calling up on the government of El Salvador
to release Ms. Fitzgibbon, and upon those participating in the
civil war ``to return to basic humanitarian norms in order to spare
the lives of the people in whose interests they claim to be
fighting.''
   Steven Schlein, a spokesman for Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.,
said the senator had contacted Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence
Eagleburger who said he was looking into the matter.
   According to Schlein, Lautenberg had met Teresa Fitzgibbon on
Nov. 6 and told her he would provide a letter identifying her as a
constituent.
   The letter was written by Lautenberg's Newark office ``as a way
of providing her some added protection,'' another spokesman said.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
told reporters earlier in the day there might be as many as nine
Americans, including at least some members of the Lutheran group,
who were arrested in El Salvador between Wednesday evening and
Thursday afternoon.
   ``Our embassy officials have already contacted the Salvadoran
security forces and have been assured of consular access,'' Ms.
Tutwiler said.
</TEXT>
