<FIRST>u w AM-D'Amato-HUD 2ndLd-Writethru a0780 11-17 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-D'Amato-HUD, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0780,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf: `D'Amato spokesman,'' to give D'Amato preparing
answers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Senators-Lincoln Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate ethics committee on Friday retained
outside counsel to analyze and gather information on allegations
that Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato violated ethics rules.
   The committee previously had asked the New York Republican to
respond to a complaint by a former campaign rival, who contended
D'Amato broke Senate rules in the federal housing scandal and other
matters.
   The panel hired Washington, D.C. criminal defense lawyer Robert
S. Bennett ``to assist the committee in determining whether or not
to proceed to a preliminary inquiry,'' according to a statement by
Chairman Howell Heflin, D-Ala. and Vice Chairman Warren Rudman,
R-N.H.
   The inquiry is the first of three stages of a formal
investigation. Rudman said it could take several months before the
decision on a preliminy proceeding is made.
   ``Sure, let them do it. I'm not concerned,'' D'Amato said.
   D'Amato spokesman Frank Coleman confirmed Friday that the
committee had asked D'Amato for a response to the complaint, which
was filed in July. D'Amato said, ``We're preparing the answers ...
we'll submit them to the committee.''
   The spokesman said D'Amato had not hired an attorney to
represent him ``because at this point, there is no case.''
   Last summer Mark Green, who ran against D'Amato in 1986, filed a
complaint with the ethics committee saying there was ``substantial
evidence'' that D'Amato broke Senate rules and federal law. Green
cited news reports alleging D'Amato involvement in the Wedtech
scandal and influence peddling at HUD.
</TEXT>
