<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil 1stLd-Writethru a0698 11-17 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0698,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidates Plan for Runoff as Vote-Counting Drags On</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with about two-thirds of the vote;
picks up 6th pvs, `Collor de...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservatives and leftists jockeyed
Friday to form alliances for a runoff election next month, and
officials worked to finish counting the votes from the first round
of balloting.
   Conservative Fernando Collor de Mello led the 21-candidate field
with 27.6 percent of Wednesday's vote, the Superior Electoral Court
said with 64.28 percent of the ballots counted.
   Collor de Mello, of the center-right National Reconstruction
Party, appeared to have guaranteed first place in the first free
balloting for president since a 21-year military regime ended in
1985.
   In the runoff Dec. 17, he appeared likely to face off with one
of two leftist candidates who battled for the No. 2 spot.
   Rep. Luis Inacio Lula da Silva, of the radical left Workers
Party, was in second place with 16.4 percent. Leonel Brizola, of
the center-left Democratic Labor Party, was third with 14.1 percent.
   However, more than half the votes from the heavily populated
southern states of Rio de Janeiro and Rio Grande do Sul _ Brizola
strongholds _ had not yet entered the government's computers, the
Superior Electoral Court said in a statement.
   Collor de Mello reportedly was seeking support on the left to
shake an image as the representative of conservatives and the
wealthy. He has made contacts with top advisors of Sen. Mario
Covas, the candidate of the left-center Brazilian Social Democracy
Party who was running a strong fourth.
   ``Anyone we eventually negotiate with must be committed to our
program, which gives priority to industrial development, economic
growth, a fairer distribution of income, social welfare and
strengthening the domestic market,'' Collor de Mello said in a
televised interview at his home in Brasilia, the capital.
   Brizola and Lula pledged to forget the personal rivalry that
marked the campaign and support the winner of their battle for the
second spot.
   Brizola's political advisor, Rep. Vivaldo Barbosa, said the
candidate would seek alliances with ``all progressive forces'' and
with ``lucid conservatives.''
   Workers Party president Rep. Luiz Gushiken said the party would
hold a national convention Nov. 25 to discuss alliances.
   ``We will deepen the ideological debate and show that Collor is
the candidate of the right,'' he said.
   As Brazilians awaited the outcome, financial markets reflected
uneasiness.
   On Thursday, the Rio stock market fell 10 points with news of an
advance by Lula, a former union boss who has scared businessmen
with promises to nationalize banks and limit profits.
</TEXT>
