<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-ArtAwards 1stLd-Writethru a0653 11-17 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Art Awards, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0653,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Presents Arts Medals; Leonard Bernstein Declines Award</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``John Frohnmayer...'' with 5 grafs
to add Bernstein statement; picks up 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``As he...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush presented the National Medal of
Arts to 12 Americans Friday, not including conductor and composer
Leonard Bernstein who had declined the honor in a newly moot
controversy over a federal grant.
   ``Thank you for your achievements, for the passion you bring to
the arts,'' Bush told the honorees, who included novelist John
Updike, trumpeter Dizzy Gillespie, dancer-choreographer Katherine
Dunham, and Czeslaw Milosz, a poet who won the Nobel Prize in 1980.
   ``You have honored this country,'' the president said. ``The
nation is grateful to you.''
   An award also was made, posthumously, to pianist Vladimir
Horowitz, who died Nov. 5.
   Bernstein told the White House on Tuesday he would not accept
the medal, reportedly because the National Endowment for the Arts
cancelled a $10,000 grant for a New York art exhibit about AIDS.
Another winner was hastily substituted, but his or her identity was
not disclosed.
   Bernstein, in a written response published in The Washington
Post's Saturday editions, apologized to Barbara Bush for declining
the invitation to the luncheon and criticized conservatives who
seek to limit arts funding.
   Bernstein's statement said, ``Dear conservatives: What are you
conserving? Democracy and human freedom, I should hope.''
   He added, ``A catalogue is not, nor need be, a work of art,''
apparently referring to the fact that John Frohnmayer, chairman of
the endowment, canceled the grant after seeing the show's catalogue.
   Bernstein also said, ``It has been called to my attention that
in declining the once-accepted invitation to lunch at the White
House I may have offended my hostess, in which case I sincerely
apologize to Mrs. Bush.''
   Frohnmayer reinstated the $10,000 grant on Thursday, saying he
had done so after viewing the exhibition, ``Witnesses: Against our
Vanishing.''
   As he read the awards citation in the East Room of the White
House on Friday, Frohnmayer made no mention of the controversy.
   The medal recipients included one corporation, Dayton Hudson, of
Minneapolis _ a store chain that in the last 10 years has
contributed more than $60 million to arts programs.
   The others were:
   Leopold Adler II, a real estate developer in Savannah, Ga., and
a preservationist, ``for his civic leadership in preserving for all
time the beauty of Savannah;'' Alfred Eisenstaedt, a pioneer
photojournalist, ``for the extraordinary photographs that document
the tragedies and triumphs he has witnessed over a lifetime;''
Martin Friedman, Minneapolis, ``for opening the doors of his museum
to the best of all of the arts of our time;''
   Lee Gerdine, ``the spiritual father of the Arts in St. Louis;''
Walter Hancock, a St. Louis sculptor; Robert Motherwell, a painter
in Greenwich, Conn., ``for reflecting in his art the very essence
of American freedom.''
   Miss Dunham was honored ``for her pioneering explorations of
Caribbean and African dance;'' Gillespie ``for his trail-blazing
work as a musician;'' Milosz ``for glorious poetry and prose;'' and
Updike ``for novels and stories that over a 40-year career have
given us a wryly affectionate yet penetrating analysis of the
complexity of life in today's America.''
   Eisenstaedt, who is 90, was not at the ceremony and his award
was accepted for him.
   The president and Mrs. Bush shook hands with each recipient.
   ``Art defines our civilization,'' said the president. ``You can
see and hear and even feel life through the mind of someone else
for new perspectives. Instead of seeing a single world, we can see
as many worlds as there are artists, writers, dancers and
musicians.''
</TEXT>
