<FIRST>r a AM-Medflies     11-17 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medflies,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Increased Pesticide Use in LA Draws Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increased chemical attacks on pockets of
crop-threatening Mediterranean fruit flies are drawing fire from
politicians and environmentalists citing potential health risks.
   Discovery of a fertilized Medfly in a previously unaffected San
Fernando Valley suburb prompted agriculture officials to schedule
aerial pesticide spraying over the infested 12-square-block area
next Monday.
   Spraying with the pesticide malathion also was planned Thursday
night for a 22-square-mile swath of East Los Angeles and the San
Gabriel Valley, with a second application over the same area
scheduled in two weeks.
   City Councilman Richard Alatorre, who represents an infested
district, wrote a letter to state Food and Agricultural Director
Henry Voss, stating fears about the pesticide.
   ``Clearly, the Mediterranean fruit fly is a serious menace to
the welfare of this region and ultimately the state,'' Alatorre
wrote. ``It is equally clear, however, that one of the weapons used
in the battle to eradicate this menace, malathion, is itself of
questionable safety to the health of humans exposed to it.''
   A protest was planned Monday by the Green Party, a political
group that stresses environmental issues.
   ``The Greens intend to put pressure on public officials to
outright ban the use of malathion,'' said party chairman Randall
Toler. The group is calling for the use of sterile Medflies instead
of pesticides to battle the infestation, he said.
   Toler said agriculture officials ``were caught flat-footed
without adequate supplies of sterile Medflies.'' He said the
cancer-causing potential of malathion remains under review by the
federal government.
   The sterile flies were normally released after sprayings to
breed any remaining pests out of existence.
   A county official and a spokesman for Gov. George Deukmejian
defended malathion's use against the Medfly, which lays its eggs in
more than 250 varieties of fruits and vegetables, threatening the
state's $14-billion-a-year agriculture industry.
   ``We feel strongly that the doses that are sprayed are not going
to cause any health problems,'' said Carol Ward, spokeswoman for
the Los Angeles County Department of Health Services. She said less
than an ounce of malathion is spayed per acre.
   Governor George Deukmejian ``fully supports'' current efforts
and ``believes that the public is supportive because of the clear
damage that the Medfly can bring to California's top industry,''
said his spokesman, Kevin M. Brett.
</TEXT>
