<FIRST>r a AM-PropaneFire     11-17 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Propane Fire,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Evacuated Because of Propane Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JASPER, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the 1,000 residents of this southwest
Missouri town were evacuated Thursday night as firemen battled a
propane fire that sent flames shooting 70 feet into the air.
   No one was hurt in the fire, which erupted at 10:30 a.m. as a
work crew was performing routine maintenance on a submersible pump,
said Jim Gipson, a spokesman for Williams Pipeline Co.
   Propane from an underground cavern escaped and somehow ignited
when it reached the surface, he said. A huge, orange fireball lit
up the sky; the glow from the fire was visible from at least 25
miles away.
   The fire was under control at 9 p.m., company president Steve
Cropper said.
   ``The pipeline facilities have been shut down, all the terminal
and loading facilities have been shut down,'' Cropper said.
   Jasper residents were asked to go to evacuation points in nearby
Carthage and Lamar, and Williams was busing some people to hotels
in Joplin. People were told to expect to be out of their homes all
night.
   ``We're letting the leaking propane burn,'' said Gipson, who was
at company headquarters in Tulsa, Okla. ``It's just making a big
light.''
   Authorities closed a rail line that moves near the pipeline
station as well as part of U.S. 71, which runs north and south
through Jasper. Warnings were issued to aircraft not to fly near
the area.
</TEXT>
