<FIRST>r a AM-AlabamaExecution     11-17 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alabama Execution,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Murdered Cousin on Furlough Slated for Execution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be updated after scheduled execution.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATMORE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court rejected a final
appeal from a man who was slated to be executed at 12:01 a.m.
Friday for raping and murdering his cousin while on an 8-hour pass
from a prison work-release center in 1978.
   The high court refused by a 7-2 vote late Thursday afternoon to
spare the life of Arthur James Julius. Justices William J. Brennan
and Thurgood Marshall, who oppose capital punishment in all
circumstances, supported Julius' emergency plea for a stay of
execution.
   Julius, 43, was condemned to die in the electric chair at Holman
Prison for raping and strangling his cousin, 29-year-old Susie Bell
Sanders, at her Montgomery home. He was serving a life term for a
1972 murder at the time of the violent sexual assault.
   Defense attorney Tommy Goggans of Montgomery argued in
last-ditch attempts to halt the execution that the prosecution
withheld evidence during Julius' trial in Montgomery. But a federal
district judge and a federal appeals court rejected the plea before
Goggans took it to the Supreme Court.
   In January, Julius received a stay of execution less than 48
hours before he was scheduled to die in the electric chair. On that
occasion, Gov. Guy Hunt denied clemency pleas, saying he would not
interfere with the verdict of the judicial system.
   According to court records, Julius left on an 8-hour pass from
Draper prison's work-release center at 11 a.m. on Jan. 29, 1978,
and borrowed a relative's car from 3:30 p.m. to 6:25 p.m. During
that time, according to court records, Julius turned Ms. Sanders'
apartment into a shambles, beating her and dragging her though
rooms and subjecting her to ``grotesque sexual abuse'' before
strangling her.
   Her nude body was discovered by her 5-year-old daughter.
   The victim's parents told reporters in January that the
execution was long overdue. Her father has since died. Family
members declined comment when contacted by phone this week.
   The last person executed in Alabama was Herbert Lee Richardson,
who was put to death Aug. 18 for the pipebomb slaying of a Dothan
child. His was the sixth execution in the state since the U.S.
Supreme Court reinstated the death penalty in 1972.
</TEXT>
