<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Michener'sCaribbean Adv22   11-17 0916</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Michener's Caribbean, Adv 22,0933</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday AMs, Nov. 22, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Michener Writes Blockbuster on Caribbean</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH2 of Nov. 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The riots on St. Croix that followed Hurricane
Hugo, and the racial unrest that threatens this city today, grew
from centuries-old seeds sown in a paradoxical region, as detailed
in James A. Michener's latest novel, ``Caribbean.''
   The Pulitzer Prize-winning author spent three years traveling
among the ``chain of lovely jewels'' and researched more than 400
books to put together a 667-page novel that chronicles more than
six centuries of civilization and destruction in the region.
   ``The idyllic portrait is only partly true,'' said Michener, 82,
as he and his wife, Mari, prepared to set sail on a farewell cruise
to the islands he described in his book.
   ``There were undoubtedly fine black-white relationships and many
were friendly ... and yet each one of the islands had eight or 10
insurrections,'' he said. ``There's a dichotomy there that I think
we all are engaged in.''
   Michener explores the contradictions of the region using his
patented blend of fact and fiction. Historical figures such as
Christopher Columbus, Adm. Horatio Nelson, Fidel Castro and Gen.
Toussaint L'Ouverture, who outfoxed French, Spanish and British
armies in what is now Haiti, brush against imaginary characters
that range from a Mayan priestess to a Jamaican Rasta.
   How the Caribbean islands can be so beautiful and yet so violent
is the central question of the book. In scene after scene, men and
women of ambition build dreams, only to be crushed by tyrants.
   ``In the short run, brutality always wins; it takes longer for
amity to prevail,'' he writes after describing how the Carib
Indians cannibalized the primitive Arawaks, who as the islands'
first residents were satisfied with planting vegetables and
watching the sun set each day.
   The message resonates throughout the island's history,
demonstrating how the legacy of harsh colonial rule provides both a
charm and a curse for the islands of today. Michener draws clear
lines from the slave rebellions to contemporary scenes in which
poverty-stricken blacks prey on tourists, even though the visitors
provide desperately needed cash to their island economies.
   ``The history of this land, and of all the islands Spain has
captured in this lovely sea, will involve the slow and even
reluctant admission that the big black man down there has a soul,''
says a rather forward-looking 16th century priest of Michener's
invention, ruminating on the atrocities Columbus ordered against
Indians, and the oppression his descendents would force on slaves.
   Michener, a lifelong Quaker, says he grew to love and fear for
the people of the islands during his research, which brought him to
back streets and poorer areas American tourists rarely see on their
Caribbean vacations.
   ``I see people beating their brains out to figure out what
they're going to do for money,'' said Michener, who has several
characters suggest all the islands would prosper if the United
States inflated the price of Caribbean cane sugar.
   But because the U.S. sugar industry won't allow it, the region
is headed for revolution, or worse, according to a Haitian-American
professor who flees her island as a child and returns the same way
Michener did this week, as a guest lecturer on a cruise ship.
   ``So we stagger along toward a disaster whose timing we cannot
predict, but whose coming is inevitable. We're a fleet of
magnificent islands, lost in the sun,'' she says in the book.
   Michener also examines Miami, the destination of refugees from
every wave of unrest in the area, through the eyes of a
Cuban-American doctor trying to reconcile his two cultures.
   The doctor admits that he and other white Cubans secretly
despise the Cubans who came to Florida later in the 1980 Mariel
boatlift, because many of the newcomers are black. And yet he
despairs when his white, non-Latin friends suffer ``Hispanic
Panic'' and flee to Palm Beach.
   Michener, who traveled to Havana in search of a sugar plantation
to describe in ``Caribbean,'' and co-wrote ``Six Days in Havana''
as a spin-off of the larger novel, also sends the doctor to Havana
on a mission from President Reagan to discuss normalizing relations
between the United States and Cuba.
   The issue is considered incendiary in South Florida's Cuban
exile community, but Michener's feelings are clear:
   ``Miami, perched at the tip of a great continent, striving to
retain its Anglo-Saxon character, and Havana, located on the edge
of a glorious island and determined to protect its Spanish
heritage. ... They should have enjoyed a symbiotic relationship of
mutual reward.''
   He blames the Castro revolution for making intercourse between
the two natural neighbors impossible, ``to the grave detriment of
each.''
   Michener has published 36 books since winning the 1947 Pulitzer
Prize for ``Tales of the South Pacific.'' And despite a quintuple
coronary bypass operation in 1986 and a hip replacement the next
year, he plans to keep working, as a ``Professor Emeritus
Emeritus'' at the University of Texas.
   ``I'm feeling good. I'm a little unsteady on my pins, but I take
a long walk every night,'' said Michener, who swears he hasn't
decided what the subject of his next book will be.
   ``It will probably be a novel, all fiction. It's a pretty big
decision to jump into another book, another state, another society,
another set of problems and contradictions. It's really quite
complicated.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wednesday AMs, Nov. 22</NOTE>
