<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:McKee Adv23   11-17 0889</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: McKee, Adv 23,0935</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Nov. 23, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Maria McKee Almost Quit Before Debut Solo Album</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This may be a shock to anyone
who's heard her soaring voice, but singer Maria McKee nearly quit
the business just before recording her solo debut album.
   ``I went through a lot of soul-searching before doing this
album,'' said the 25-year-old McKee. ``I had moments when I
thought, `Is this worth it?' I had moments of sheer desolation
about it.''
   The depression stemmed from her experiences fronting Lone
Justice, a highly touted country-rock band from Los Angeles that
fell far short of expectations.
   Plucked from the garages in time to put out a record in 1985,
Lone Justice found friends in high places: Jimmy Iovine, who
produced John Lennon, sat behind the controls for them; Tom Petty
gave them a song; U2 invited them on tour. But neither of Lone
Justice's two records sold very well, and the supposed can't-miss
stars missed.
   The experience scarred McKee, but didn't fatally wound her. Her
solo debut, an amalgam of rock, country and gospel filled with
messages from the lovelorn, isn't setting any sales records,
either, but it's been received with the kind of quiet respect for
which McKee is longing.
   ``Ever since I was a little kid I wanted to have a rock 'n' roll
band, to put a band together and be successful at it,'' she said.
``I had to let that go and realize that it wasn't going to happen.
I was beginning to wonder if I really wanted to make music.''
   Like many rockers before her, Lone Justice was disillusioned by
the realization that the pop music merry-go-round was controlling
them, instead of the other way around.
   There was no way Lone Justice could live up to the advance
billing, she said.
   ``The hype was so completely absurd, without really the
substance to back it up and that's very dangerous,'' she said.
``Even if you are as great as everyone expects you to be it can
never really work out because people like to discover for
themselves something to like about your music.''
   She blamed the band's failure on the usual litany of rock 'n'
roll excuses: bad chemistry between band members, business naivete
and a sense they were writing songs to fulfill the expectations of
others instead of themselves.
   McKee took some time off, the band dispersed to various parts of
the country, but they didn't immediately learn their lessons. Lone
Justice actually regrouped and started work on a third album before
McKee decided to pack it in.
   The solo record is largely a collaboration with keyboardist
Bruce Brody and producer Mitchell Froom, with several session
players added. The sound is more sophisticated and airy than the
Lone Justice records, highlighting McKee's extraordinary voice.
   ``I wanted to have the freedom to write whatever I wanted to, to
record with whoever I wanted to,'' she said. ``It could be an
acoustic band, it could be a jug band, it could be a string band.
Maybe I took liberties that I'm too young to take or too
inexperienced to take, but I thought I should be honest with
myself.''
   Although the album sounds like it's coming from a woman whose
heart has been broken a few times, McKee insists that isn't the
case.
   Love is used as a metaphor for some of her career uncertainties
during the song ``I've Forgotten What It Was in You (That Put the
Need in Me).''
   ``I'm not really experienced in the art of love and all of
that,'' she said. ``I'm sort of an idiot savant when it comes to
love. I've been on the road since I was 18 and I haven't really had
any boyfriends.''
   On compact disc, the downer spell of her album is broken by the
last song, ``Drinkin' in My Sunday Dress.'' The twisted tale of a
hard drinking yet church-going woman features some of McKee's most
uninhibited vocals, and a wild guitar that Marc Ribot plays with
his car keys.
   McKee said the song was left off the album because it didn't
really fit the theme, but it's a highlight of her live shows. She
opened a series of dates for Neil Young this summer accompanied by
Brody and her acoustic guitar, singing no Lone Justice songs.
   Although Geffen Records was initially concerned that her album
didn't have a natural single, McKee said she's not that worried
about having hits. A career role model for her now is Elvis
Costello, she said.
   ``I really admire the way he's gone about it,'' she said. ``He
makes album after album and some are better than others, but he's
always onto something. He's always on the edge and always
experimenting with n and new musicians and stretching his writing.
it.''
   After a few tours with Lone Justice s really didn't believe,
she's recaptured the sp music business in the first place.
   McKee'salfway through her 20s.
   ``I'm 25 years old and even though I've been doing this for 10
years, there was soof that time that was spent trying to figure out
what I wanted to do,'' she said. ``Now that I know, I'm on the
right track again.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday AMs, Nov. 23</NOTE>
