<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00-1st-LdWritethru   11-17 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00-1st-Ld Writethru,b0812,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf to correct spelling of Nightingale and title of
``How the Camel Got His Hump.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since everything from stamp collecting to
dieting to entertainment can be had on video, why not the news?
   MPI Home Video has released ``The San Francisco Earthquake,'' a
one-hour look at the devastating earthquake of Oct. 17, which
measured 7.1 on the Richter scale, killed 66 people and did an
estimated $7 billion in damage.
   According to promotional material, the $14.95 tape promises to
``examine through dramatic footage the 15 catastrophic seconds that
San Francisco and the entire Bay Area experienced as well as the
deadly aftermath of the quake.''
   The video also gives earthquake safety tips and provides a list
of agencies where contributions can be sent. The video is produced
by ABCNEWS.
   Elsewhere, SVS has produced a series of narrated children's
stories on video. Although animation on the tapes hardly matches
the quality and artistry of Disney, the storytelling is upbeat and
imaginative.
   Narrators include Glenn Close doing ``The Emperor and the
Nightingale'' and ``The Legend of Sleepy Hollow''; Danny Glover,
``How the Leopard Got His Spots''; Jodie Foster, ``The Fisherman
and His Wife''; Jack Nicholson, ``How the Rhinoceros Got His Skin''
and ``How the Camel Got His Hump''; Robin Williams, ``Pecos Bill'';
Meryl Streep, ``The Tailor of Gloucester,'' ``The Tale of Mr.
Jeremy Fisher'' and ``the Tale of Peter Rabbit''; and Holly Hunter,
``Three Billy Goats Gruff'' and ``Three Little Pigs.''
   The videocassettes have a suggested retail price of $14.95.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Leviathan'' (MGM-UA Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated R)
   
   Nothing like borrowing from every sci-fi, high adventure,
creature feature and still coming up a loser. George P. Cosmatos'
``Leviathan,'' starring Peter Weller and Richard Crenna, does
exactly that.
   It's easy to spot the basic recipe for ``Alien'' and ``The
Abyss'' in this tale about the mutant result of a failed experiment.
   Most of the action takes place underwater, where a mining team
(shades of ``The Abyss'') is trapped with a genetic mess. The
underwater photography is not very special, but the special effects
are _ especially Stan Winston's creature.
   Weller, who turned ``Robocop'' into a cult hit of the 1980s,
provides well-need humor to an otherwise slow, very slow, story.
   This video won't keep you on the edge of the sofa, but it's as
good as any adventure fright night on commercial TV.
   ``Leviathan'' also features Ernie Hudson, Amada Pays and Daniel
Stern.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
