<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0883</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's merchandise trade deficit in
September tumbled to $7.9 billion, its smallest imbalance in nearly
five years, the government said.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday the September deficit fell
21.4 percent from August, when the trade gap posted a $10.1 billion
difference, the largest of the year.
   The drop resulted from a 3.9 percent decline in imports to $39
billion and a 1.9 percent gain in exports to $31.1 billion. The
deficit is the difference between the two.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee has passed a market reform
bill that would allow the Securities and Exchange Commission to
halt trading during stock market emergencies _ with the president's
approval.
   The proposed Market Reform Act of 1989, passed Thursday, would
give the SEC authority to take temporary emergency action in
response to a major market disturbance. But the president would be
required to state that he does not disapprove of any such action
before it could take effect.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially struggling Texas Air Corp. said its
Continental Airlines subsidiary has agreed to buy 40 foreign-made
Airbus jets in a deal valued at about $4.5 billion.
   Houston-based Texas Air, the nation's largest airline company,
said Thursday the new A330 and A340 planes would allow Continental
to develop new markets and replace other planes in its fleet. The
company said it was the largest single order ever for both aircraft
types.
   Texas Air said up to 10 of the new jets may be assigned to
Miami-based Eastern Airlines, its other airline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have fired Arizona
millionaire Charles H. Keating Jr. as manager of a luxury resort
owned by his failed thrift institution, Lincoln Savings and Loan
Assocation.
   Keating and 23 family members and associates were dismissed
Thursday from positions at The Phoenician Resort near Scottsdale
and from posts at the 344-room Crescent Hotel in Phoenix.
   Regulators, accompanied by FBI agents, Phoenix police officers
and private security guards, seized the properties at 1:30 a.m.
local time, according to Resolution Trust Corp., a new agency
created this summer to handle failed S&amp;Ls.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Corp. and Warner Communications Inc.
reached a settlement that allows hot Hollywood producers Peter
Guber and Jon Peters to leave Warner and head up Sony's Columbia
Pictures, the parties to the dispute said.
   The settlement Thursday includes several joint business
arrangements and ends all litigation stemming from Guber's and
Peters' acceptance of Sony's offer, according to an announcement
issued from New York by Warner Bros., Sony USA and The Guber-Peters
Entertainment Co.
   Guber and Peters were producers of the highly acclaimed and
box-office hits ``Batman'' and ``Rain Man.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Services Administration is
investigating International Business Machines Corp.'s sale to the
government of used computer equipment marked as new, GSA officials
said.
   IBM says it told the GSA about the problems two years ago.
   The investigation by the agency's inspector general is also
trying to determine if IBM violated the Buy American Act by
incorrectly certifying that more than half the components of some
products it sold the government were made in America.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. said it is discontinuing all
business related to racially segregated South Africa, including
trading or researching South African securities.
   Merill Lynch said Thursday it will no longer engage in any
financial or commercial transactions with the South African
government, any of its agencies or any corporation or individuals
organized or residing in the country.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate efforts to overhaul the nation's
racketeering law stalled while members of both parties rallied to
defend the sponsor, Arizona Democrat Dennis DeConcini, from charges
the bill was designed to dilute curbs against white-collar crime.
   DeConcini's bill would cut back on provisions that enable those
who file such suits to collect triple damages.
   The Judiciary Committee had been expected to draw up its final
version of the bill and send it to the floor on Thursday. But
efforts to do so broke down when the committee ran out of time.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange said the amount of
computerized program trading declined sharply in October, when the
controversial strategy was blamed for a rash of wild market swings.
   Program trading strategies accounted for 9.7 percent of an
average total daily volume of 182.4 million shares, or 17.7 million
shares a day, on the NYSE, the nation's largest stock exchange, the
NYSE said Thursday. That marked a decline from 13.8 percent in
September.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market churned in place Thursday, getting little
benefit from news of a smaller-than-expected U.S. trade deficit.
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 3.08 to 2,635.66.
   The dollar rallied on news of the big improvement in the trade
balance.
   Bond prices fell modestly.
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose; coffee prices fell
sharply; heating oil surged, leading the energy complex higher;
precious metals were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were
mixed.
</TEXT>
