<HEAD>Ford Building 3 New Electronics Plants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said it is spending $300
million for three new electronics plants, two of them overseas,
which will begin making car and truck components during the next
three years.
   The first new plant to be in operation will be in Worcester
Township, Pa., about 30 miles northwest of Philadelphia. It will
replace a nearby outdated factory in Lansdale.
   That plant next year will begin making electronic engine control
devices, anti-lock brake parts and sensors, the company said. About
2,600 people are employed at Lansdale and the new plant will have
more than 2,000 workers when full production is reached next year.
   The company also is building plants in Cadiz, Spain, and Lisbon,
Portugal.
   The Spanish plant will make engine controls in mid-1991 and
employ about 350 people. The Portuguese plant will employ about
1,700 when it reaches full production of audio components in 1992.
</TEXT>
