<SECOND>PM-AT&amp;T,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Increases Some Phone Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AT&amp;T says it will increase some domestic
long-distance rates, prices for calls to various foreign locations
will be changed and certain international rates will be simplified.
   Basic night and weekend prices for long-distance calls will go
up about 1.3 percent. That would amount to 2 cents per minute on a
call from New York to Los Angeles, the company said Thursday.
   The rate hike, totaling $34 million, should average out to about
3 cents per month per customer, it said.
   The higher rates cover interstate calls after 11 p.m. during the
week and all weekend until 5 p.m. on Sundays.
   In addition the company said it is simplifying rates for calls
to India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Bangladesh and Nepal, reducing some
prices and changing from three rate pariods to two.
   There will be an increase, however, on prices for calls to
Romania, Suriname and Macao.
