<FIRST>r f BC-CineplexOdeon     11-17 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cineplex Odeon,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drabinsky Misses Deadline For Financing To Take Movie Chain Private</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: All dollar figures are Canadian.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cineplex Odeon Chairman Garth Drabinsky says he
will continue to work on a proposed bid to buy the major theater
chain, which he founded, after missing a deadline to obtain
financing for the deal.
   Drabinsky and his partner, Cineplex Vice Chairman Myron
Gottlieb, were to have secured financing by Wednesday for their
proposed bid of $16.40 (Canadian) per share for Cineplex valued at
more than $700 million.
   The pair said in a statement Thursday that ``adverse market
conditions and ... a difficult financial climate'' were partly
responsible for their inability to find a backer.
   But they also said they were still negotiating with a special
committee of the Cineplex board that was set up to examine offers
for the company, which operates one of the largest movie theater
chains in the United States.
   ``We are discussing possible extensions and revisions'' to the
proposed bid, committee spokesman Sandra Kolber confirmed.
   Possibilities under consideration include an offer at a lower
share price, and a restructuring under which certain company assets
would be sold to chip away at $750 million in long-term debt,
Kolber said from Montreal.
   Cineplex stock, which fell 50 cents to $12.63 Wednesday on the
Toronto Stock Exchange, was off another dollar Thursday, closing at
$11.63.
   In their statement, Drabinsky and Gottlieb said they remain
``highly confident'' that financing would be arranged for an
alternate buyout proposal.
   The success of such a deal could depend on whether MCA Inc. of
Los Angeles and Claridge Inc. of Montreal, Cineplex's two top
shareholders, are willing to accept less than $16.40 per share for
their stock, said Marianne Godwin, an analyst with Merrill Lynch
Canada.
   Drabinsky is likely having trouble financing a deal because of
the company's poor financial record, she said.
   On Tuesday, Cineplex reported a net loss of $8.4 million for the
third quarter that ended Sept.30, compared with a profit of $17.2
million for the same period a year earlier.
   Cineplex Odeon Corp. is North America's second-largest theatre
chain, with 500 locations and 1,870 screens.
   Drabinsky, a 41-year-old lawyer, founded the company in Toronto
a decade ago. He proposed buying the business Oct.25, and got MCA
and Claridge to agree to sell their stock if a Nov.15 financing
deadline was met.
   Drabinsky and Gottlieb were also to be reimbursed by Cineplex
for up to $10 million in expenses related to their bid if they met
the deadline.
</TEXT>
