<FIRST>r f PM-Trade-Dollar Bjt   11-17 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade-Dollar, Bjt,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Presses South Korea on Currency Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea is manipulating its currency to
gain advantages in foreign trade, the U.S. says, and the Bush
administration will press for progress by April in negotiations
aimed at stopping the practice, a senior Treasury official says.
   Informal talks since the summer of 1986 have had some result in
persuading the South Koreans to allow their currency, the won, to
appreciate against the dollar, David C. Mulford, Treasury
undersecretary for international affairs, said Thursday.
   But, the Korean system remains ``inherently manipulative,'' and
the United States hopes in January to begin a round of formal talks
with Seoul aimed at changing it, Mulford told the Senate Banking
subcommittee on international finance and monetary policy.
   Sen. Paul S. Sarbanes, D-Md., chairman of the panel, warned that
Congress was growing impatient with South Korea and would press to
tie the currency question to other U.S.-Korean trade matters if
progress wasn't evident soon.
   The largest U.S. trade deficits are with Japan and West Germany,
but in recent years the deficit has soared with newly
industrialized countries in Asia such as South Korea and Taiwan.
   In October 1988, the United States charged both South Korea and
Taiwan with manipulating their currencies to maintain their trade
surpluses. Efforts by the two countries to keep their currencies
weak make their goods cheaper on U.S. markets and make American
products more expensive for their consumers.
   However, Mulford noted with approval that Taiwan changed its
system in April and said there is no evidence that its central bank
continues to intervene in currency markets. The New Taiwan dollar
has strengthened by 5 percent since April, in contrast with the
won, which has weakened slightly, he said.
   Meanwhile, at a separate hearing, a private economist told a
House Banking subcommittee that South Korea's shrinking trade
surplus indicates there is no basis for the currency manipulation
charges. The surplus has shrunk 28 percent in the first nine months
of this year compared with the same period last year.
   John Williamson, senior fellow at the Institute for
International Economics, said the administration was attempting to
deflect attention from its own failure to live up to international
monetary agreements by shrinking its budget deficit.
   However, Sarbanes said, ``I think the currency manipulation has
to be straigtened out. ... The fact that (South Korea's) surpluses
may have dwindled somewhat does not eliminate that problem.''
   In a related matter, Federal Reserve Board Vice Chairman Manuel
H. Johnson, in response to a question from Sarbanes, acknowledged a
rift between the central bank and the Treasury Department over
exchange rate policy.
   Unlike Treasury officials, Johnson said he and other Fed members
do not believe in massive currency sales to drive the dollar lower
when market forces are driving the value higher. Fed members favor
such sales only to stabilize a disorderly market, he said.
   Sarbanes faulted the Fed for allegedly undermining a Sept. 23
agreement among the United States and its major economic allies
that sought to drive the dollar lower.
   However, both Johnson and Mulford played down the significance
of the dispute and said policy coordination was working smoothly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
