<FIRST>r f PM-LincolnS&amp;L-Keating     11-17 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L-Keating,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Seize Keating Resort</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lincoln S&amp;L, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators handling the nation's
largest savings and loan failure have seized a luxury resort in the
Arizona desert from Phoenix millionaire Charles H. Keating Jr., the
S&amp;L's owner.
   The regulators, accompanied by FBI agents, local police and
private security guards on the 1:30 a.m. raid Thursday, took
control of two Keating properties: the Phoenician, a 605-room golf
resort near Scottsdale, and the 344-room Crescent Hotel in Phoenix.
   Keating, his wife, Mary Elaine Keating, two daughters, two
sons-in-law and 18 other associates were fired from management
positions at the properties, owned by a subsidiary of Lincoln
Savings and Loan Association, Irvine, Calif.
   Later Thursday, a source said the Senate Ethics Committee would
hire an outside counsel to investigate five senators who received a
total of $1.3 million in campaign contributions from Keating and
intervened with regulators on his behalf.
   There was no indication from the source, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, whether the committee had decided on an individual to
investigate Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Dennis DeConcini,
D-Ariz.; John Glenn, D-Ohio; John McCain, R-Ariz. and Donald
Riegle, D-Mich.
   In related developments:
   _Cranston became the third senator to formally respond to the
Senate Ethics Committee inquiry into the allegations that the five
senators intervened with regulators on behalf of Keating.
   _A top aide to S&amp;L regulator M. Danny Wall complained that
Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman Richard C. Breeden, in
criticizing the thrift agency, gave sworn testimony to the House
banking panel that was ``simply not true.''
   A Keating representative called the seizure of the Phoenician
``the most despicable, outrageous, blatant act of terror we have
ever seen by our U.S. government.''
   ``The Gestapo-like tactics used on employees and management of
the resort are just unconscionable,'' said Bradley Boland, senior
vice president of American Continental Corp., Lincoln's parent
company.
   ``They walked in ... they locked offices, they locked desks.
Then they went out into the community to the homes of the core
management group and posted severance notices on their front doors.
These guys are gutless, ruthless, faceless bureaucrats trying to
carry out their ongoing vendetta against Charlie Keating,'' Boland
said.
   Keating's continuation as manager of the Phoenician had
particularly irked members of the House Banking Committee, which is
investigating the thrift's collapse, expected to cost taxpayers $2
billion.
   A recent newspaper advertisement for the resort said Robin Leach
featured the Phoenician on his television special, ``The Rich and
Famous, 1989 World's Best.'' Room rates range from $200 a night to
$3,750 for the most expensive suite, according to the House panel.
   Alan J. Whitney, a spokesman for the Resolution Trust Corp.,
created in August to handle failed S&amp;Ls, said regulators had been
trying to take over the resort since April, when they seized
Lincoln.
   The government filed a $1.1 billion fraud and racketeering suit
against Keating and his associates, but officials were delayed in
taking over the resort because its minority owner, the Kuwaiti
Investment Office, had the authority to block changes in management.
   Obtaining approval from the London-based Kuwaiti office was
awkward and cumbersome, Whitney said.
   Although Keating was not paid as manager of the Phoenician, he
continues to receive a $400,000-a-year salary as chairman of
American Continental, which has filed for protection under
bankruptcy laws.
   Keating is scheduled to testify before the House banking panel
on Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, Cranston said in his written response to the ethics
committee that he violated no laws, ethical standards or Senate
rules in two April 1987 meetings with regulators examining
Lincoln's finances.
   ``I never attempted to derail any investigation of wrongdoing at
Lincoln, nor did I ever suggest ... that an investigation be
delayed,'' Cranston wrote.
   Riegle and DeConcini provided material to the committee earlier.
Glenn and McCain have not filed formal responses, but have denied
wrongdoing.
   The SEC is investigating the accuracy of financial statements
filed by American Continental, and Breeden told the House banking
committee earlier this week that Wall's agency undermined the probe
in 1988 by accepting Lincoln's financial statements as accurate.
   Thrift office senior deputy Karl T. Hoyle said in a letter to
the banking panel that regulators ultimately rejected much of
Lincoln's financial statements and, in any event, did nothing that
would have prevented the SEC from pursuing its investigation.
</TEXT>
