<FIRST>r f PM-SEC-Schapiro     11-17 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Schapiro,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Approves Schapiro Nomination for SEC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel has voted to send the
nomination of Mary C. Schapiro to the full Senate for confirmation
as a member of the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Ms. Schapiro has served on the SEC since December 1988 when she
was named as a recess appointment by then-President Reagan.
   President Bush nominated her for a full five-year term last week.
   Appointments to the five-member board, which oversees the stock
markets, are subject to Senate approval.
   Although few members of the Senate Banking, Housing and Urban
Affairs Committee were on hand for Ms. Schapiro's confirmation
hearing, she was praised for her 11-month stint on the commission.
   She told the committee that her priorities were getting more
money for the agency to raise staffers' salaries and maintaining
the agency's enforcement drive.
   While she agreed that SEC staffers should be paid more, there
also is a need for more of them, said Ms. Schapiro.
   Because of the SEC's small staff, about 2,200, she said
investment advisers are only examined about once every 12 years by
the agency.
   Ms. Schapiro is a one-time attorney at the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission and former general counsel of the Futures
Industry Association.
   Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., the committee chairman,
asked if there may be more major insider trading cases yet to be
found.
   ``I would love to think that what we've done is brought an end
to insider trading. But I think that's probably not the case,''
said Ms. Schapiro.
   ``... We will continue to pursue insider trading, as I think we
have to.''
</TEXT>
