<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0736EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAL     11-17 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Woos Lenders While United Pilots Map Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp. executives are reaching out again to
the banks that refused to finance an employee-management buyout
plan last month, sources say.
   Separately, leaders of the pilots union at UAL's United Airlines
opened a two-day strategy session Thursday on contract negotiations
and the possibility of a new buyout offer.
   UAL is being pressured by the investor group Coniston Partners,
which is one of its largest shareholders, to increase the company's
stock value.
   A bank official who met with UAL executives Thursday said the
company ``made it perfectly clear there is nothing out there that's
firm'' regarding a sale or restructuring of UAL.
   The bank official characterized the meeting as ``a kind of
goodwill gesture'' aimed at rebuilding ties with the lenders.
   ``I guess it's no secret they're meeting with all the major
banks'' that initially had agreed to help raise financing for the
failed $6.75 billion offer, said the bank executive, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   He said 30 or 40 banks had been participating in the failed bid,
and UAL was visiting many of them seeking ``a perspective on what
happened in the last deal and on what might be going on now.''
   UAL said its meetings with U.S. and Japanese lenders were
routine.
   Officials at Citibank and Chase Manhattan, the New York-based
banks that were the lead lenders for the failed bid, declined to
comment on UAL.
   Representatives at the Chicago offices of Sumitomo Bank Ltd. and
Mitsubishi Bank Ltd., two large Japanese banks that were
participating in the original deal, also declined to comment.
   The company's stock plunged in October after the
pilot-management group's $300-a-share buyout bid collapsed when the
buyers failed to get financing.
   UAL's stock fell $4.25 to $184.75 a share Thursday on the New
York Stock Exchange. The stock had traded as high as $294 amid the
takeover speculation ub September and October.
   The buyout group's failure to secure financing helped trigger a
breathtaking 190-point drop in the Dow Jones industrial average on
Oct. 13.
   Coniston, a New York-based investment group, is pressuring UAL
to increase shareholder value either through a sale of the company
or a restructuring that would involve a cash payout to stockholders.
   Coniston owns 9.7 percent of UAL's stock and is seeking consent
from other shareholders to dump most of the company's directors,
take control of the board, and direct an ``extraordinary
transaction'' to benefit shareholders.
   UAL spokesman Joe Hopkins confirmed the bank meetings were
taking place but would not comment on their content.
   Meanwhile, leaders of the United chapter of the Air Line Pilots
Association opened a two-day special meeting Thursday in Chicago.
   The pilots have been trying to buy United, the nation's
second-largest airline, since 1987 and have been working without a
contract since April 1988.
   The pilots were discussing contract talks and prospects for a
new buyout bid, sources said.
   United's pilots have threatened to stop flying United's new
Boeing 747-400 aircraft if they fail to get a contract.
   United owns two of the long-distance planes and uses them on
routes from Los Angeles to the Australian cities of Sydney and
Melbourne.
</TEXT>
