<FIRST>r f PM-Chrysler-Maserati     11-17 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler-Maserati,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>No More Than 7,300 TCs by Maserati for Chrysler</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. has put a 7,300-car limit on its
order with Maserati for the TC two-seat sports coupe, an order the
Italian automaker plans to fill by next May, company officials say.
   The Chrysler TC by Maserati went on sale in January after
several delays because of quality concerns. In a letter last month
to Maserati's parent company, De Tomaso Industries of Italy,
Chrysler said it wanted no more than 7,300 of the cars.
   ``We have been notified by Chrysler that we are to terminate
production of the TC coupe after we build 7,300 cars and we
estimate that will fall in May of 1990,'' said Howard Chase, vice
president and general counsel for De Tomaso Industries Inc., of Red
Bank, N.J.
   Nationwide, through Nov. 10, the 315 Chrysler dealers who handle
the TC by Maserati had sold 1,922 of the cars and have more than
1,770 cars on hand, Chrysler spokesman Tom Jakobowski said.
   The car carries a base price of $33,000 with a no-extra-cost
choice of two powertrains.
   ``That would end the TC project. It would not end Chrysler's
involvement with Maserati,'' Chase said from his New York office.
   Chrysler owns 15.6 percent of Maserati SpA, and De Tomaso
Industries owns the rest. Jakobowski said the company has passed
opportunities to increase its stake in Maserati and has no plans to
reduce it.
   Chase said Maserati is involved in discussions with several
automakers about establishing a manufacturing agreement similar to
that with Chrysler. He declined to identify the other companies or
whether any were U.S. based.
</TEXT>
