<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-TimeSuit     11-17 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Time Suit,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Magazine Fined Over Allegedly Inaccurate Quote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time magazine was ordered by a court Friday to pay
$2,100 in damages to a Japanese doctor who said the magazine
misquoted her six years ago.
   Judge Eiko Ito of Tokyo District Court ruled that the magazine
had damaged the reputation of the doctor, Etsuko Negishi.
   In its Aug. 1, 1983, issue, the magazine said, ``Two out of
three Japanese women have had an abortion, which is so common, `it
is like having a tooth out,' says Dr. Etsuko Negishi, a woman
gynecologist.''
   ``The article in Time did not quote her accurately,'' said Judge
Ito in the ruling. ``By putting abortion on the same level as
pulling out a tooth, it gave a wrong impression to the readers and
damaged the plaintiff's social reputation.''
   Dr. Negishi said she never made such a comment to Time.
   ``I have never met a Time reporter nor have I ever made such a
comment before,'' she was quoted by Kyodo News Service as saying.
``The content (of the quote) contradicts the facts.''
   Time magazine officials in Tokyo were not immediately available
for comment, but according to court documents, the magazine
acknowledged that its reporters had not contacted her. It defended
its action by saying the doctor was quoted by Japanese newspapers,
and the magazine took the quote from them.
   The 49-year-old doctor complained that she was criticized by
colleagues as a result of the article and that it had hindered her
activities as a gynecologist.
   In her suit, Dr. Negishi had demanded that Time pay $420,000 in
damages and print full-page corrections in the magazine and in all
five major Japanese daily newspapers.
</TEXT>
