<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv20   11-17 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 20,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Nov. 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Resorts Bondholders Make a Deal With Griffin, But Some Question Its
Worth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resorts International Inc. bondholders have
played a game of ``Let's Make a Deal'' with owner Merv Griffin,
trading some of the money they're owed for Resorts stock while
betting he can revive the sickly casino company.
   One of the advisers to the bondholders calls the agreement,
announced last week, a model for how the parties to a near-bankrupt
company can work together.
   ``This had the potential for five years of litigation,'' said
Arthur B. Newman, a Chemical Bank investment banker and bondholder
adviser. ``And no one wins in five years of litigation.'' Except,
of course, the lawyers.
   Newman represents investors who own the $600 million in Resorts
bonds issued before Griffin bought the company from developer
Donald J. Trump last year. The second group of bondholders are
those who bought the $325 million worth of junk bonds that gave
Griffin the money for the takeover.
   Under the agreement, Griffin will give bondholders 78 percent of
the stock in the company, which he owns outright, in exchange for
their going along with a Resorts bankruptcy filing on friendly
terms.
   Griffin, the entertainment magnate and former talk show host,
also agreed to inject $30 million in fresh cash to rehabilitate the
company's aging Atlantic City casino and other properties.
   Resorts, which stopped paying interest on its bonds in August,
will operate under protection of a bankruptcy court for a brief
period, according to the plan, before emerging as a presumably
healthier company early next year with much lower debt.
   The plan will also provide bondholders with new bonds or notes
in the company. It must be approved by owners of two-thirds of the
bonds.
   Newman said the two bondholder groups, along with Griffin's
people, hammered out the agreement in just one week.
   ``Everybody worked very, very hard,'' he said last week.
``Everybody hurts a little,'' he said, referring to compromises
that were made.
   Newman said the Resorts case is the first to his knowledge in
which a major, near-bankrupt company and its creditors agreed to a
reorganization plan before the actual bankruptcy filing. It is
called a prepackaged bankruptcy.
   Newman advised the main creditors group in the Texaco Inc.
bankruptcy case, which was bitterly fought and expensive. Citing
the smooth Resorts deal, he said, ``I think people are just getting
smarter.''
   Some analysts said the Resorts deal. ``It appears to be a fair
compromise,'' said Steven Eisenberg, an industry analyst for Bear,
Stearns &amp; Co. Inc.
   But others said the bondholders may see little of the money they
invested unless the company stages a dramatic turnaround.
   ``Gamblers at Merv Griffin's Resorts have more odds of seeing
their money repaid than the junk-bond holders,'' said Paul Getman,
an economist for Wefa Group, an economic consulting firm in Bala
Cynwyd, Pa.
   Getman had little sympathy for either Griffin or the
bondholders. He characterized Resorts as another over-leveraged
takeover that was based on unrealistic projections of a company's
ability to sell assets and pull in money.
   ``These bonds are what, a year old? Is this what we're coming
to, that you can't trust a promise to repay principle and interest
that is a year old?'' he said of the Resorts high-yield bonds. ``It
is just another chapter in what I think is going to be a long, sad
spectacle in junk-bond ownership.''
   However, the bond market cheered the deal. Prices of Resorts
bonds surged the day the agreement was confirmed.
   Griffin bought Resorts a year ago after a heated takeover battle
with Trump, who owns several other Atlantic City casinos. Another
aspect of the reorganization plan is that bondholders expect to
file a ``fraudulent conveyance'' lawsuit against Trump.
   Such a suit would claim that something of value was transferred
to Trump in the buyout without him giving a fair return to the
company. One such asset is the huge, incomplete Taj Mahal casino in
Atlantic City, which Trump bought for $273 million as part of his
deal with Griffin after Resorts spent about $500 million on it.
   Griffin avoided becoming a target of such a suit by agreeing to
the reorganization plan, according to those involved in the deal.
   In a statement, Trump said Griffin should accept full
responsibility for Resorts' problems, ``instead of pursuing wholly
baseless and ultimately wasteful claims against me.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Nov. 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
