<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-EdselLives Adv18-19   11-17 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Edsel Lives, Adv 18-19,0759</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 18-19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Car Symbolizing Auto Failure Is Gone, But Not Forgotten</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Edsel, the car that has come to symbolize
failure in modern automaking, may be gone but it's not forgotten.
   There was a time when owners of Edsels, named after Henry Ford's
son, were laughed at and questioned about their mental condition
when they drove the car.
   But three decades after Ford Motor Co. stopped making the car on
Nov. 19, 1959, folks still get together and talk about those
funny-looking cars with the horse collar in the grille.
   According to the Old Cars Price Guide, a 1958 two-door Edsel
Citation hardtop in mint condition could fetch up to $13,000, or
almost four times the original price of $3,500.
   That's not keeping up with the rate of inflation, but it's not
bad for a car that has a reputation as a marketing disaster.
   Paul Yount said he and his wife Ethel buy Edsels out of
affection. They have owned 53 of them at their farm in Polo, Ill.
``When you go crazy, you go crazy,'' he said.
   Yount said it was the Edsel's high price, not its pucker-faced
appearance, that led to its demise. A recession struck in 1957 and
dealers didn't lower their sticker price while they lowered the
other sticker prices, he said.
   The name didn't help, either. Historians have written that the
name, taken from the original Henry Ford's son Edsel Bryant Ford,
initially was thrown out. It was adopted later after thousands of
other names were rejected.
   Edsel buffs even blame the Cold War for hurting the Edsel's
changes.
   ``The public was in a blue funk because at the very time we
introduced the car, the Russians were successful in launching an
intercontinental missile,'' said Gale Warnock, who handled public
relations during the Edsel's 1957 launch.
   He recalled an early Edsel joke that appeared in the New Yorker
magazine showing one person talking to another saying something
like: ``Great, the Russians have an intercontinental missile and we
have an Edsel.''
   ``That really fries me,'' Warnock said of Edsel jokes.
   However, he acknowledged, ``The word Edsel has become a synonym
for loser. Every comedian uses it when they want to describe
something horrible.''
   The only Edsel at Ford these days is Edsel B. Ford II, 40, head
of the company's marketing staffs. He has been on the Ford board of
directors since last year.
   The Sept. 4, 1957, public introduction of the Edsel capped a
launch program that began in March 1956. During those 18 months,
Ford teased the public with magazine advertisements that showed a
blur of an Edsel roaring down a rural highway.
   ``Lately some mysterious automobiles have been seen on the
roads,'' read an advertisement in the July 22, 1957, issue of Life.
``The EDSEL is on its way.''
   When showrooms opened up, crowds were big. A telegram to Edsel
executives from a C. Pickrell of Beacon Edsel in Inglewood, Calif.,
described showroom traffic:
   ``Reception to car fantastic, have written seven orders
delivered five cars. Had approximately 2,000 people through our
showroom. Went through 45 gallons of coffee 26 dozen doughnuts.
   ``Darndest coffee and doughnut town I've ever been in.''
   From there, things quickly went downhill.
   Ford projected sales of 290,000 by 1960, but production, which
is based on sales, fell far short of that. The company made 63,100
Edsels for the 1958 model year, 44,891 for 1959 and just 2,846 for
the 1960 model year before stopping the Edsel assembly line.
   The Edsel had a number of unique features, some of which died
with the car and some that live on only in expensive models today.
   Edsel featured a ``Teletouch'' transmission which had
push-button shifting on the steering wheel hub. That's no more,
anywhere.
   But it also offered as accessories a compass, a station-seeking
radio and thermometers to show inside and outside temperatures,
sophisticated versions of which are on today's cars.
   Those kinds of features helped the car get some rave reviews
from auto journals of the day.
   The Edsel ``could very well be an indication of things to
come,'' read a review in Motor Life, a magazine that ceased to
exist on its own in December 1961 when it was absorbed by Sports
Car Graphic.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Nov. 18-19</NOTE>
