<FIRST>r f AM-Dunkin'Donuts-Allied     11-17 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dunkin' Donuts-Allied,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Firm To Acquire Dunkin' Donuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dunkin' Donuts Inc., which fought off a hostile
takeover attempt earlier this year, said Friday it has agreed to be
acquired by the British food and beverage group Allied-Lyons PLC
for $325 million in cash.
   ``We think this is the best possible deal,'' said Robert
Rosenberg, Dunkin' Donuts chairman. ``We fit right in.''
   Dunkin' Donuts had decided in September to accept friendly bids
after DD Acquisition Corp., a Canadian partnership, mounted a
hostile $43-a-share bid, which later was raised to $45 a share.
   Under terms of the deal with Allied-Lyons, the London-based
concern will pay $47.25 a share for all outstanding common Dunkin'
Donuts shares.
   ``They were the highest bidder,'' Rosenberg said. ``It worked
out well for our stockholders, for our management, for our
franchises.''
   Rosenberg declined to comment on the number of offers his
company received.
   Dunkin' Donuts, based in Randolph, has 1,600 U.S. outlets and
250 abroad.
   Rosenberg said joining Allied-Lyons would strengthen his
company's position as the world's largest coffee and doughnut
chain, and he said the British company supports the goals of
Dunkin' Donuts to expand.
   Allied-Lyons, which already owns a number of North American food
companies including the Baskin-Robbins ice cream franchise and the
tea and coffee group Tetley Inc., said Dunkin' Donuts ``is a
natural strategic fit with our existing strengths.''
   Richard Martin, Allied-Lyons chief executive, said the
acquisition shows the company's determination to expand its food
division and ``develop the successful Dunkin' Donuts core franchise
business with its strong cash flow.''
   Roger Lipton, an analyst with Ladenburg, Thalmann &amp; Co. Inc. in
New York, described Allied-Lyons ``as the right kind of buyer.''
   ``This is strategic, rather than financial,'' he said.
   But he also said DD Acquisition still would be a good buyer for
Dunkin' Donuts.
   The Canadian partnership was comprised of Cara Operations Ltd.,
a restaurant franchise company, and Kingsbridge Capital group, the
merchant banking arm of Toronto investor George Mann's Unicorp
Canada Corp.
   Lipton said despite the buyout agreement, the Canadian group
could raise its offer and force the Dunkin' Donuts board to
consider a higher price.
   Eric Evans, a spokesman for DD Acquisition, said his group had
no comment on Friday's announcement, and he would not say if the
partnership might raise its bid.
   Rosenberg said he could not speculate on the possibility of a
higher offer.
   Dunkin Donuts' in August reported a 34 percent drop in
third-quarter earnings, much of it attributed to the battle against
the hostile takeover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
