<DOCNO> AP891117-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HousingStarts Bjt   11-17 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Starts, Bjt,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Starts Rebound From Seven-Year Low</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing starts bounced back 12 percent in
October from September's seven-year low, the government reported
Friday, and analsyts said they expect the construction rate to
remain stable through the first quarter of 1990.
   ``The housing market seems to have bottomed out,'' said David
Seiders, chief economist for the National Association of Home
Builders. But he and other analysts said they do not foresee any
surge in building _ ``just hanging in there.''
   The Commerce Department reported that new homes and apartments
were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.42 million
units last month.
   The 12 percent rebound from September was the sharpest gain
since a 13 percent advance in December 1986. Starts had fallen 4.6
percent in September and 6.4 percent in August.
   Although September's pace was revised up from the 1.26 million
reported earlier, it still was the most sluggish since new homes
and apartments were built at an annual rate of 1.17 million units
in October 1982 during the depths of the 1981-82 recession.
   Many analysts attributed the September construction drop to a
spike in mortgage rates and said the October advance followed a
subsequent decline.
   The housing industry has been among the hardest hit as the
Federal Reserve drove up interest rates to slow economic growth and
lower inflation.
   But the Fed has slowly eased rates over the summer and, except
for the blip in September, mortgage rates have fallen from March's
11.22 percent peak to 9.82 percent by the end of October, according
to surveys by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   The higher rates stifled sales and boosted inventories of
single-family homes to an 8.1-month supply by last March, said
Richard Peach, an economist for the Mortgage Bankers Association.
As rates have fallen, he said, inventories have dropped to a
6-month supply, which ``by historical standards ... are in good
shape.''
   But even though many analysts expect mortgage rates to drop
another half of a percentage point in coming months, Peach said he
does not expect a major surge in building.
   Construction of single-family homes in October rose 6.9 percent
to an annual rate of 1.03 million units. Single-family starts had
fallen 3 percent in September and 3.5 percent in August.
   Apartment construction rose 28 percent in October to an annual
rate of 393,000 units. It had fallen 9.4 percent in September after
dropping 14 percent in August.
   Total housing starts during the first 10 months of the year were
down 6 percent from the same period of 1988.
   The South, which posted a 14.7 drop for the steepest regional
decline in September, turned in the sharpest increase in October,
up 17.1 percent to 562,000 units. It was followed by the Midwest
with a 16.5 percent gain to 289,000 units.
   Construction rose 6 percent in the Northeast to 176,000 units
and 5.1 percent in the West to 393,000 units.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891117-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Germany-Tourism     11-17 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Tourism,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Creates Ministry of Tourism</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany on Friday established a minister
of tourism, apparently to draw more visitors.
   Premier Hans Modrow, in presenting his new 28-member Cabinet,
selected Liberal Democrat Bruno Benthien to head the Ministry for
Tourism, a post that didn't exist previously.
   The move is seen as a strong indication East Germany plans to
expand tourism to earn sorely needed hard currency, now that its
borders have been thrown open for its own citizens to travel West
freely.
   While East Germany always has permitted visitors to travel and
drive through its territory, it has also imposed strong
restrictions that discouraged many tourists.
   Included in the restrictions is the mandatory exchange of the
equivalent of 25 West German marks ($14) per day per person while
staying in the country.
   Officially, East Germany has insisted in the past of exchanging
on a one-to-one basis its marks for West German marks. Western
prices for the East German marks fluctuates, but in West Germany is
normally about one West German mark to 10 East German marks.
   The mandatory exchange rate has long been a sore point with West
Germans traveling to visit relatives in East Germany.
   Cornelia Schmalz-Jacobsen, secretary-general of West Germany's
business-oriented Free Democratic Party, said East Germany's
requirements for visitors were ``absurd.''
   ``Through increased tourism the German Democratic Republic could
earn much more than through the current mandatory exchange,'' Mrs.
Schmalz-Jacobsen said.
   Another factor affecting tourism is East Germany's strictly
enforced 62 mph speed limits and the police practice of imposing
on-the-spot fines if it is exceeded even slightly. The fines for
Western visitors must be paid in dollars or West German marks, and
range from $11 up, depending on the seriousness of the infraction.
   In addition, hotels are few in large cities and practically
non-existent in the rest of the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
