<DOCNO> AP891117-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Ferranti     11-17 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ferranti,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ferranti Says It Lost $338 Million in Fraud, Half in Cash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British defense manufacturer Ferranti on Friday
said it lost more than $157 million in cash because of fraud in its
acquisition of the U.S. company International Signal &amp; Control.
   In total, Ferranti said its loss was the equivalent of $338
million as a result of what it called ``a serious fraud'' involving
bogus contracts which it unwittingly inherited when it bought the
American company in November 1987.
   Ferranti's deputy managing director Charles Scott told a news
conference about half the loss represented cash spirited out of the
American firm, the vast majority before the Ferranti takeover.
   In a rewritten version of its annual report, Ferranti
International Signal PLC said ISC's assets and profits ``were
substantially inflated by a serious fraud which had been running
for some years prior to the merger.''
   Ferranti Chairman Sir Derek Alun-Jones said at the news
conference that the fraud involved the creation of false contracts
and the circulation of money to and from non-existent customers
through various vehicles including some Panamanian and
Swiss-registered companies. ``I think most of the companies have
been liquidated,'' he said.
   Ferranti paid $660 million for the Lancaster, Pa.-based defense
contractor. But it said it now believes the American company had no
net worth at the time of the merger, even though ISC's audited
balance purported to show a net worth of $320 million.
   Alun-Jones said the company expects to initiate legal
proceedings soon to try to recover some of the money, but he said
there was a chance it would never recover anything.
   Scotland Yard's Serious Fraud Office and the U.S. Federal Bureau
of Investigation have said they are investigating. Alun-Jones
refused to say who the company believed was responsible, or where
the money had gone.
   Ferranti has renegotiated a $471 million loan package with its
bankers to keep afloat and has been looking for either a rescue
merger or a substantial injection of capital from a new partner.
   Alun-Jones said he was holding talks with between 10 and 15
people about a possible merger or takeover of the company. He
refused to identify them, citing confidentiality agreements.
   In the meantime, he said, the company will continue to dispose
of businesses which aren't central to its strategy.
   He said the company was nearing completion of the sale of the
maintenance and service division of Ferranti Computer Systems Ltd.
and the disposal of Marquardt Co. in the United States, a maker of
propulsion technology and ordnance products. The combined asset
sales are expected to bring Ferranti around $157 million.
   In its revised report, Ferranti provided numerous figures
updated to reflect its write-off of assets related to the $338
million value previously assigned to the phantom contracts at ISC.
   The write-off was foreshadowed in Ferranti's report to
shareholders at the end of September, when it said it had uncovered
the full extent of suspected contract irregularities at the
American subsidiary. At that time, the company estimated it might
have to take a write-off of $270.5 million.
   Ferranti was alerted to the ISC problems in August, and sent a
team of accountants to examine the true worth of ISC after it
emerged that contracts the company claimed to have secured with
Pakistan, China and a Middle Eastern country didn't exist.
   Ferranti previously had no reason to doubt the validity of ISC's
audited accounts and only discovered the fraud in August after some
trading and management problems had emerged in ISC earlier in the
year, Alun-Jones said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
