<DOCNO> AP891117-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 2146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-France-Pathe     11-17 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-France-Pathe,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearing on Pathe Cinema Purchase Cancelled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French court canceled its hearing Friday on the
purchase of Pathe Cinema by Italian film mogul Giancarlo Parretti
after the government withdrew its objections to the sale.
   The Paris Tribunal of Commerce dropped the case after
determining that the Finance Ministry and Parretti were nearing
agreement to end their dispute over the venerable cimena chain.
   Court officials released no details of any moves toward a
settlement and repeated calls by The Associated Press to the
ministry and Pathe were not returned.
   French financial newspapers reported Friday that the ministry
would no longer contest the sale of Pathe to Max Theret
Investissement (MTI), the Parretti-headed group whose origins have
been debated for months.
   The government has contended that MTI acted as a front for the
Geneva-based Sasea holding company, while Parretti, who owns the
ailing U.S. Cannon film group, said his funds came mostly from a
string of successful business ventures in Italy.
   The distinction became crucial after MTI purchased majority
shareholdings in Pathe last year because Switzerland, the home of
Sasea, is not a member of the 12-nation European Community.
   French law requires that non-EC investors seek government
approval to purchase more than 20 percent of a French concern. But
MTI bought a 52 percent stake in Pathe directly from the Banque
Rivaud and increased its holdings with further purchases from
minority shareholders.
   Several scheduled court appearances were postponed over the past
four months as Finance Ministry investigators tried to build a case
against Parretti and divine the origin of the funds behind MTI.
   Parretti meanwhile created a new Amsterdam-based holding company
called Pathe Europe and promised to put Pathe Cinema under its
control. Its shareholders include two Parretti-controlled
Luxembourg holding companies.
   Negotiations followed between MTI and ministry officials, and
the government reportedly promised to abandon its case if an EC
character could be established for Pathe Cinema.
   The proposals also involved having the bulk of Pathe stock
revert to previous owners, leaving the Parretti group with a
holding of under 20 percent.
   Last month the European Commission in Brussels rebuked France
for blocking the Pathe deal and scheduled a hearing before the the
European Court of Justice to see what evidence of illegal
activities French officials could bring against Parretti.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
