<DOCNO> AP891117-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GAFTrial Bjt   11-17 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GAF Trial, Bjt,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jefferies Raises Question of GAF Chairman's Role, Criticizes Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Language in 5th graf may offend some readers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As one of the nation's top stockbrokers, Boyd L.
Jefferies made millions keeping his numbers in the best possible
order. He may have a little more trouble with words.
   Jefferies finished his stint as a prosecution witness this week
by saying for the first time in three GAF Corp. stock manipulation
trials that he assumed the alleged scheme was directed by GAF
Chairman Samuel J. Heyman.
   Defense lawyers pounced on the surprise statement as an example
of numerous discrepancies in testimony by the former Los Angeles
broker, who cut a deal with federal prosecutors in exchange for
lenient treatment.
   And in an article in the December issue of Esquire magazine,
Jefferies bluntly states that Heyman ordered the alleged
manipulation and derides the quality of the prosecution.
   ``It's such a chickenshit case,'' Jefferies is quoted as saying.
   Based on information from Jefferies, the government charged GAF,
two subsidiaries and vice chairman James T. Sherwin with stock
manipulation and other crimes. They allegedly tried to boost Union
Carbide Corp.'s share price in 1986 shortly before selling a large
block of Carbide shares.
   Jefferies has waffled, sweated, stammered and failed to
recollect during lengthystretches of testimony, especially under
cross-examination from GAF lawyer Arthur Liman. The first two
trials ended in mistrials.
   ``It's very difficult for any man to go through that many
examinations for that long,'' Jefferies' lawyer, James Linn, said
Friday. ``He is frustrated and very tired of it. I think it showed
a little.''
   But, Linn said, ``there's no real discrepancy on his fundamental
story'' that Sherwin called Jefferies in late October 1986 and
asked him to raise Carbide stock to close at $22 a share.
   Barring another mistrial, Jefferies is done testifying. He also
appeared at the trial that convicted investor Paul Bilzerian and
provided information for charges against speculator Salim B. Lewis,
who pleaded guilty to stock manipulation on the eve of his trial.
   In exchange, Jefferies pleaded guilty to two felonies. After the
government praised his assistance, he was spared jail, sentenced to
probation and fined $250,000. The multimillionaire is running a
golf clinic for youngsters in Aspen, Colo.
   Jefferies also has a home in Palm Springs, Calif., where he
returned Friday. He didn't immediately return telephone calls
seeking comment.
   In all three GAF trials, defense lawyers have attacked
Jefferies' credibility, calling him an admitted felon testifying to
save his skin.
   ``The crux of this trial is whether Boyd Jefferies is or is not
a truth teller,'' Sherwin's lawyer, Stephen Kaufman, said in a
closed session in U.S. District Judge May Johnson Lowe's chambers
this week.
   In the Esquire article, Jefferies said that after he was
implicated by now-jailed speculator Ivan Boesky he remembered
thinking, ``If they're going to bring me down for something like
this, I'm going to bring down a lot of other people with me.''
   Jefferies also was quoted as saying about Heyman and the alleged
GAF manipulation: ``The whole thing was all Sam's idea. Sherwin
doesn't even go to the bathroom without Sam telling him to.''
   Liman read some of the quotations in court and Jefferies said he
couldn't recall having made them.
   Jefferies testified in the second trial that during
conversations with Heyman in Tuscon, Ariz., he had no indication
Sherwin was acting on Heyman's instructions. He said the same thing
this Tuesday.
   But on Wednesday Jefferies suddenly said Heyman called him to
see if he could talk to Sherwin ``and discuss something that Mr.
Heyman knew was illegal and he did not want to have any
association.''
   ``Mr. Heyman is smart,'' he testified. ``He knows the conniving
and the way to do an illegal transaction and not provide any
trail.''
   On Thursday, he wavered, saying he merely assumed Heyman knew
and had instructed Sherwin what to do. ``I felt that Mr. Sherwin
and I had been set up by Mr. Heyman,'' he said.
   Heyman has not been charged, although he was named in the second
trial as an unindicted co-conspirator. It was unclear what effect
Jefferies' latest testimony would have on the case, though some
lawyers believe it could help Sherwin's chances of acquittal but
hurt GAF.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
