<HEAD>Kloster to Buy Royal Cruise Lines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kloster Cruise Ltd., owner of Royal Viking and
Norwegian Cruise lines, said Friday it had signed a definitive
agreement to buy Royal Cruise Line, the San Francisco-based owner
of two luxury ships.
   The purchase price was not disclosed.
   The agreement calls for Kloster to acquire Royal Cruise Line,
which owns the 1,052-passenger Crown Odyssey and the 472-passenger
Golden Odyssey, while leaving Royal Cruise's sales, marketing and
operational headquarters in San Francisco as a separate division.
   P.S. Panagopoulos, chairman and owner of Royla Cruise, will
remain with the company.
   Kloster, based in suburban Coral Gables, already operates 10
ships through its Norwegian Cruise Line and Royal Viking Line
divisions. Most of them offer Caribbean cruises out of the Port of
Miami, but some sail worldwide.
   Kloster Chairman Trygve Hegnar noted that Royal Cruise ``has a
strong identity in the luxury end of the market'' and said the
acquisition ``will greatly broaden and enhance our offer of cruise
products, covering the whole range from the mass market to the very
top of the luxury market.''
   Hegnar also said Royal Cruise's Greek heritage and
well-established European cruise program gives Kloster the chance
to increase its presence in Europe, ``which is an integral part of
our expansion strategy for the 1990s.''
