<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1658EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Skinner-Airlines     11-17 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinner-Airlines,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner Warns Against High-Debt Airline Takeovers, Re-Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner on
Friday reiterated his department's opposition to high levels of
debt in airline takeovers, which have swept the industry this year.
   ``Many recapitalizations are good. They put new blood into the
company; they set standards for performance,'' Skinner told an
airline industry gathering in New York. He added, however, that he
is concerned that excessive debt resulting from takeovers could
negatively affect an airline's safety.
   While conceding that some foreign investment is essential,
Skinner said, ``We have to make sure that national security is not
compromised'' by foreign control of U.S. airlines.
   Under U.S. law, foreign airlines aren't allowed to own more than
25 percent of the voting stock of domestic carriers.
   Last month, Skinner used his authority to force KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines, the foreign partner in the $3.65 billion buyout of
Northwest Airlines parent NWA Inc., to cut its $400 million
investment by $225 million.
   Despite his concern about takeovers, Skinner said Friday he
doesn't need the new authority to deal with buyouts that a bill in
Congress would give him.
   The House recently passed a bill to require government rejection
of any airline takeover that might affect safety, hinder
competition, cut a carrier's size, affect jobs or result in foreign
control of an airline.
   Under the legislation, now before the Senate, the transportation
secretary would determine whether transactions meet the standards
before they are completed. He also would have the power to approve
any airline merger if he believes it is in the public interest.
   Skinner said he would recommend that President Bush veto the
bill if it is sent to him. The House vote exceeded the two-thirds
majority necessary to override a veto.
   The transportation chief also criticized new proposals in
Congress to re-regulate the airline industry.
   ``The concept of re-regulation is not a concept I agree with,''
Skinner told the airline executives and analysts.
   He said a study of airline competition by his department, due to
be completed in January, will show that such drastic action is not
warranted _ although there are small ``pockets'' of
anti-competitiveness.
   Skinner urged the airlines to forge the same sort of cooperation
between labor and management that exists in the auto industry.
   ``The days of adversarial striking, to the degree it has
occurred in the past, are over,'' he said.
   He didn't specifically mention the strike against Eastern
Airlines, which has continued since early March although the
carrier has hired replacement workers. Skinner and Bush have
refused to intervene in the strike, as the unions have asked them
to do.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891117-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1732EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-DualTrading-CFTC Bjt   11-17 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dual Trading-CFTC, Bjt,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Regulators Plan Dual Trading Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal agency that regulates the nation's
futures exchanges said Friday it will ask those exchanges to
restrict the controversial practice of dual trading.
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission also released its
long-awaited study of dual trading, which involves traders who
execute trades for themselves and their customers on the same day.
   The study found dual traders are not ``a critical ingredient in
providing liquidity and low-cost trade execution.''
   Critics of dual trading, which is not illegal, claim it poses
conflict-of-interest problems for traders who might try to make a
profit trading for themselves ahead of their customers.
   This practice, known as front-running, is banned.
   Front-running is among the many fraud schemes alleged in the
indictments of more than 40 traders at the nation's two-largest
futures exchanges in Chicago this past summer.
   Based on the study, as well as the Chicago indictments, the CFTC
said its staff was preparing ``proposed rules that would require
exchanges to restrict dual trading on a provision, phased-in
basis.''
   CFTC Chief Economist Steven Manaster said, however, that
developing those rules ``will be a lengthy process.''
   Legislation that would severely limit dual trading is pending
before Congress.
   ``Dual trading exists in all markets,'' the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange said in a prepared statement, adding that the exchange
``after its own study, has proposed to deal with any real or
perceived problems with dual trading through the enhancement of the
audit trail. Both the House and Senate have also adiopted this
approach.''
   An audit trail is an anti-fraud device to reconstruct a trade to
determine when it occurred and who was involved.
   ``We will review the CFTC's report on dual trading and make
comments to any proposed rules at the appropriate time,'' the CME
statement concluded.
   Futures contracts are agreements to deliver a quantity of goods
at a specified price at a certain time in the future. Futures
contracts are used by producers of such commodities as soybeans or
gold to lock in a favorable price down the road.
   And speculators, in turn, buy and sell those contracts to profit
from constantly changing price differences.
   Supporters of dual trading claim it helps keep trading costs
down and keeps the markets liquid when there is little trading
especially in small, low-volume markets.
   ``It had been argued that dual traders might be superior
providers of liquidity or that dual traders might be superior in
terms providing customer service and on that basis were kind of
super traders _ they were absolutely essential to whatever was
going on in these markets,'' said Manaster.
   But he noted the 47-page study, conducted by the CFTC's Division
of Economic Analysis, found that the ``vast majority'' of dual
traders tend to specialize in trading either for themselves or for
their customers. Dual trading is really a sideline for most floor
traders, constituting only about 10 percent or less of their
business.
   The study also found that:
   _There is no statistical support for claims that dual trading
increases in low-volume months;
   _Dual traders ``do not, on average'' get better quality trades
for their cusrtomers than brokers who trade only for customers.
   _Dual traders do not help make the market any more liquid than
``exclusive traders,'' or those who don't engage in dual trading.
   ``On the basis of the study, I think we have a reasonable idea
of what may happen and in particular, dual traders are not a
unique, super trader and it seems reasonable that their
contribution to the market organization could be substituted for by
exclusive traders or brokers,'' said Manaster.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891117-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 2251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Hewlett-Packard     11-17 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Hewlett-Packard,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard's Profit Nearly Flat in Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. reported Friday
that its profit was nearly flat in its fiscal fourth quarter,
depressed by its acquisition of Apollo Computer Inc. and costs
associated with the California earthquake.
   The computer, electronics and instruments company said it earned
$246 million, or $1.04 a share, in the three months ended Oct. 31,
up only 1 percent from $243 million, or $1.03 a share, a year
earlier.
   The Apollo purchase and earthquake costs reduced net earnings
for the quarter by about 14 cents a share, Hewlett-Packard said.
   The flat earnings occurred despite a 25 percent increase in
fourth-quarter revenue to $3.37 billion from $2.70 billion.
   The company paid $476 million for Apollo, a large maker of
computer workstations.
   Among the effects of the purchase was a one-time $6 million
charge stmming from employee payouts in Hewlett-Packard's
profit-sharing plan. The payout was extended to Apollo employees.
   Hewlett-Packard also posted a $9 million charge to cover costs
connected with the earthquake that rattled Northern California on
Oct. 17, killing 66 people and causing $7 billion in damage.
   The costs included repair and cleanup from the quake, said Nancy
Colvert, a spokeswoman for Hewlett-Packard. The company doesn't
expect any further charges connected with the quake.
   Orders for the fourth quarter totaled $3.14 billion, up 20
percent from $2.61 billion in the same period last year.
   For the entire fiscal year, net profit edged up 2 percent to
$829 million, or $3.52 a share, from $816 million, or $3.36 a
share, the previous year.
</TEXT>
