<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off; Gold Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed Friday in a quiet
session with traders lacking any incentive to buy or sell heavily.
   Gold bullion prices rose.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery settled at $394.60 a troy ounce, $3.20 higher than
Thursday. The Republic National Bank of New York quoted an ounce of
gold at $394.25 as of 4 p.m. EST, up $2.95 from Thursday's late bid.
   ``There was not much activity today'' in the dollar, currency
dealer John McCarthy said.
   McCarthy, who is with the Amsterdam Rotterdam Bank's office in
New York, said currency dealers paid more attention to buying West
German marks than to trading dollars.
   Demand for marks has increased as currency investors speculate
that West German economic growth will accelerate due to closer ties
with East Germany.
   Traders said news that U.S. housing starts rebounded 12 percent
in October from September's seven-year low failed to evoke much of
a response in the currency markets.
   The dollar ended lower against most major currencies in U.S.
trading after a mixed performance overseas.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing 143.98 Japanese yen from
143.85 yen at Thursday's close. Later, in London, it rose to 144.15
yen. By the time trading was done in New York, the dollar was
quoted at 144.25 yen, unchanged from Thursday's late level.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.5705 from $1.5805 late
Thursday. The pound weakened further in later New York trading,
falling to $1.5670 from $1.5755 on Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
late rates included: 1.8410 West German marks, down from 1.8427;
1.6307 Swiss francs, down from 1.6326; 6.2630 French francs, down
from 6.2725; 1,355.00 Italian lire, down from 1,357.25; and 1.16945
Canadian dollars, up from 1.16875.
   Selected late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with late
Thursday's quotes included: 1.8410 West German marks, up from
1.8375; 1.6315 Swiss francs, up from 1.6290; 6.2590 French francs,
up from 6.2550; 2.0770 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0750; 1,353.50
Italian lire, down from 1,354.00; and 1.1697 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1700.
   Precious metals prices moved higher.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $392.25 a troy ounce, down
from $393 late Thursday.
   In Zurich, the metal fell to a closing bid of $391.50, down from
late Thursday's bid of $392.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.59 to close at $392.21.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $5.61 a
troy ounce, up from $5.60 late Thursday. On New York's Comex,
silver bullion for current delivery settled at $5.672 a troy ounce,
up from Thursday's settlement of $5.582.
</TEXT>
