<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-17 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Push Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Precious metals futures prices rose broadly Friday, supported by
continued investor buying of gold, silver and platinum, and by
supply fears in the palladium market linked to reports of problems
at Soviet nickel refinery.
   Gold closed near its high for the week, prompting predictions by
analysts that it will test the psychologically important
$400-an-ounce level next week.
   On other commodity markets, copper sank to four-month lows;
energy futures rose; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and
grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Gold futures settled $3.10 to $3.90 higher on New York's
Commodity Exchange with the contract for delivery in December at
$395.80 a troy ounce; silver futures finished 8.7 cents to 9.6
cents higher on the Commodity Exchange with December at $5.685 a
troy ounce.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, platinum futures settled
$5.20 to $6 higher with January at $526.60 a troy ounce; palladium
ended $3.25 to $4 higher with December at $145.60 a troy ounce.
   The latest gains fit with a bullish trend in precious metals
prices that began last month and which analysts have attributed
largely to buying by investors fleeing the turbulent stock market.
   The rally, which began on the London market before the New York
markets opened, defied expectations for a drop in prices following
Thursday's weak finish.
   ``What impressed me is that the market wasn't taken lower
abroad,'' said analyst Craig Sloane of Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp;
Co. ``I felt everything followed from that.''
   The palladium market led a late surge in the metals markets
following news that a gas pipeline feeding a major Soviet nickel
refinery had exploded.
   The Soviet Union is the world's largest producer of palladium, a
white metal similar to platinum that is a by-product of nickel
refining.
   Copper futures fell sharply on the Commodities Exchange,
continuing a downward trend linked to an improving supply outlook.
Traders expect the London Metal Exchange's weekly stocks report on
Monday to show an increase in the exchange's warehouse stocks of
copper.
   Copper futures finished 2.5 cents to 4.6 cents lower with
December at $1.089 a pound, the lowest daily settlement price since
July 21.
   Energy futures rose on the New York Merc, led by strong gains in
the gasoline and heating oil markets.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 7 cents
higher with December at $19.91 a barrel; heating oil was .46 cent
to .60 cent higher with December at 59.27 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .05 cent to .67 cent higher with December at 51.95
cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures were narrowly mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange ahead of a monthly Agriculture Department report that
showed 3 percent fewer cattle on feedlots Nov. 1 than on the same
date a year ago.
   That number was near market expectations but the report also
showed an unexpectedly large number of feedlot placements last
month, which was expected to prompt fairly heavy selling of live
cattle futures when trading resumes Monday.
   Live cattle settled .07 cent lower to .20 cent higher with
December at 74.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower
to .10 cent higher with November at 83.15 cents a pound; hog
futures were .30 cent to .95 cent higher with December at 49.97
cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .65 cent higher
with February at 64.17 cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures prices finished mixed on the Chicago
Board of Trade after a dull trading session.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 2{ cents higher with December at
$4.10 a bushel; corn was \ cent lower to \ cent higher with
December at $2.40 a bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent higher
with December at $1.47{ a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 1{
cents lower with November at $5.83} a bushel.
