<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     11-17 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Market Advances on Anticipation of OPEC Meeting, Colder Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures moved higher Friday in
anticipation of the upcoming OPEC meeting and increased demand
during the winter months.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 5 cents to $19.91 a 42-gallon barrel
on the New York Mercantile Exchange, adding to a 19 cent gain on
Thursday.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the December
contract for home heating oil advanced 0.48 cent to 59.27 cents a
gallon following a 1.66 cents rise the previous session.
   And wholesale gasoline for December delivery picked up 0.64 cent
to close at 51.95 cents a gallon after rising 0.70 cent on Thursday.
   ``We had a one-two punch coming in here,'' said analyst Madison
Galbraith of Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Galbraith said the market expected the return of colder weather
to many parts of the nation to increase the demand for home heating
oil, which is refined from crude.
   But traders also were looking ahead to meetings of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries beginning next week
in Vienna, Galbraith said.
   The market anticipated that the 13-member oil cartel might take
steps to tighten production and raise prices, and investors bought
up oil so they would not be caught short in the event of a new OPEC
agreement.
   Galbraith said buying remained strong throughout Friday's
session.
</TEXT>
