<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1828EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Lockheed     11-17 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lockheed,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockheed to Take $300 Million Loss on Anti-Sub Plane, May Show Loss
for Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Design changes on a new anti-submarine
patrol plane will force Lockheed Corp. to report a pre-tax loss of
about $300 million in the fourth quarter and possibly a loss for
the year, Lockheed said Friday.
   The big aerospace company has been building fixed-wing maritime
surveillance planes since World War II for the Navy, which plans to
spend between $4 billion and $5 billion to buy 125 of the new P-7A
planes.
   Lockheed said the cost of developing the P-7A had risen because
its design will be less like that of its predecessor, Lockheed's
P-3C Orion, than expected.
   Despite big changes in the wings, body and engine _ the new
plane's wingspan is 7 feet longer than the old one, for example,
and top takeoff weight is 156,600 pounds, up from 139,700 pounds _
the company had hoped it would be able to keep many parts of the
structure unchanged.
   ``We originally had thought that something over 50 percent of
the structure might be common to the P-3,'' said Lockheed spokesman
Jim Ragsdale.
   Stress analysis proved different. ``We don't know what the
actual percentage is going to be, but it's going to be far lower
than that,'' Ragsdale said.
   Lockheed stock fell $2.12{ a share to $39.50 in trading on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Lockheed has been building P-3s since 1962 and is to deliver the
last P-3 to the Navy in mid-1991. It had hoped to have the P-7A in
production by late 1992. Ragsdale said it was unclear how much the
design changes would delay production.
   The writeoff of about $300 million covers all the extra
development costs that are expected over the next several years,
and Lockheed expects to show a profit once production of the P-7As
gets under way, said Daniel M. Tellep, the company's chairman.
   Tellep said in a statement that the exact amount of the writeoff
wouldn't be known until after more studies and review by the Navy.
   He didn't say how long that would take. But in a memo from the
aerospace company's Burbank facilities to P-7A workers, Lockheed
said it would immediately launch a three-month to five-month
reassessment of the program.
   ``The P7-A is now viewed as an almost new design,'' the memo
said.
   ``Some activities will be temporarily suspended until revised
plans can be set in place and approved by the customer,'' Lockheed
told the workers. ``We are confident the program will be continued
and will meet its objectives.''
   For its third quarter ending Sept. 31, Lockheed lost $32 million
on sales of $2.1 billion, compared to a profit of $123 million on
sales of $2.3 billion for the same quarter a year earlier. For the
first nine months of the year, Lockheed earned $108 million on
sales of $6.6 billion, compared to $333 million on sales of $7.2
billion in the same period in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
