<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 1930EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AltmanClosing     11-17 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Altman Closing,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hooker Closing Six Altman Stores</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L.J. Hooker Corp., unable to find a buyer for
its B. Altman department stores, said Friday it would close six of
the chain's seven branches.
   Hooker said the move, which will include the company's flagship
Manhattan store, was approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court
overseeing the company's reorganization.
   Hooker is owned by the Australian developer Hooker Corp., which
has been unable to handle its massive debt load and been forced to
liquidate itself.
   Last month, L.J. Hooker said it had received a $409 million cash
offer from an investor group for the company's three regional
shopping malls, shopping centers, a large Atlanta office building
and undeveloped land in several states. It also included L.J.
Hooker International Inc., a commercial real estate brokerage.
   The offer did not include the Altman stores, and Hooker had said
it would close the chain if it did not find a buyer for them by
Friday.
   ``We just couldn't wait any longer, given our fiduciary
responsibility to the company's creditors and other business
entities,'' said Sanford C. Sigoloff, Hooker's chief executive.
   Hooker said the Altman store in a Hooker mall outside Cincinnati
would remain open. The company also owns the Bonwit Teller
specialty store chain, and has said it would keep those stores open.
   Hooker had been trying to sell the Altman branches while several
other big U.S. department stores also were on the block.
   Canada's Campeau Corp., another developer that has run into
financial trouble because of its retail acquisitions, plans to sell
its Bloomingdale's chain. Meanwhile, BAT Industries PLC plans to
sell its Marshall Field and Saks Fifth Avenue chains as part of its
defense against an unwanted takeover bid in Britain.
   Retail industry analysts have said Hooker and Campeau took on
too much debt and underestimated the volatility of the U.S.
retailing industry when they made their acquisitions.
   Campeau Chairman Robert Campeau was forced to surrender control
of his company to fellow developers Olympia &amp; York recently in
return for financial aid to keep his company afloat. Campeau paid
$3.4 billion for Allied Stores Corp. and $6.6 billion for Federated
Department Stores Inc., going heavily into debt to finance the two
deals.
   The retailing industry has had a generally disappointing
performance in recent years, and Hooker and Campeau stores have
been unable to generate the cash flow the companies needed to pay
their debts.
   When both companies made their acquisitions, analysts said the
firms were more interested in the real estate they acquired rather
than the retailing businesses.
   The investors bidding for most of Hooker's assets are led by the
Shidler Group and the Simpson Organization Inc. The group was
assembled by the London-based investment banking company Hoare
Govett, a subsidiary of Security Pacific Corp.
   Besides the Manhattan store, located in a landmark building
across from the Empire State Building, the Altman branches being
closed are in White Plains and Manhasset, two New York City
suburbs; Paramus and Short Hills, N.J.; and St. Davids, Pa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891117-0272 </DOCNO>
