<FIRST>r f BC-LINBroadcasting     11-17 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-LIN Broadcasting,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sets Jan. 12 for Shareholder Vote on BellSouth Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LIN Broadcasting Corp. said Thursday it has
scheduled a Jan. 12 special meeting for its shareholders to vote on
its plan to combine its cellular phone operations with those of
BellSouth Corp., a regional telephone concern.
   New York-based LIN, which also owns television stations and a
specialty publishing business, said shareholders of record as of
the close of business Dec. 1 will be eligible to vote.
   LIN has been the target of an unwelcome takeover bid from McCaw
Cellular Communications Inc., the nation's largest cellular
operator, which already owns nearly 10 percent of LIN's stock.
   McCaw has offered $125 a share for 22 million of LIN's 54
million shares, which would give it a controlling 50.3 percent
interest in LIN. LIN has recommended that its shareholders reject
the McCaw offer.
   Under LIN's agreement with BellSouth, LIN shareholders would get
a special dividend of $42 a share, keep a stake in the new cellular
company and get stock in a new company being spun off consisting of
LIN's TV stations.
</TEXT>
