</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regulators said they will dissolve the Federal
Asset Disposition Association after an unsuccessful attempt to sell
the agency established to manage and sell loans and real estate
from failed savings institutions.
   Almost since its creation in 1985, FADA has been the target of
harsh criticism from members of Congress who charged that the
federally owned, but privately controlled, financial institution
had grown into a bloated, inefficient bureaucracy mired in
political favoritism and inside dealing.
   The announcement that it will be dissolved was made Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal agency that regulates the nation's
futures exchanges said it will ask those exchanges to restrict the
controversial practice of dual trading.
   Also on Friday, the Commodity Futures Trading Commission
released its long-awaited study of dual trading, which involves
traders who execute trades for themselves and their customers on
the same day.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new East German premier said his country
is open to private enterprise and foreign investment to meet the
needs of frustrated consumers, but warned of hard economic times
ahead.
   In his first speech to the East German parliament as head of the
government, Hans Modrow recommended Friday greater cooperation with
economically powerful West Germany while rejecting reunification.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gained ground Friday as the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials rose 17.00 points to 2,652.66,
   The dollar finished mixed in a quiet session.
   Bond prices slumped.
   Precious metals futures prices rose broadly; gold closed near
its high for the week; copper sank to four-month lows; oil futures
rose; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and grains and
soybeans were mixed.
