<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Oil     11-17 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Oil,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>BP Announces $884 Million Expansion Plan in Scotland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Petroleum Co. PLC on Thursday announced a
$884 million plan to expand North Sea oil and gas processing at its
onshore complex at Grangemouth in Scotland and to increase ethylene
production there.
   BP said $489 million of the new investment would be spent on
enlarging its Grangemouth processing plant that separates oil and
gas from the company's Forties Field in the North Sea.
   It said the other $395 million would be spent on a new plant to
increase the production of ethylene. Ethylene is made from gas and
is used among other things to make chemicals.
   BP's activities at Grangemouth near the Scottish capital of
Edinburgh include the processing and export of North Sea oil and
gas products, oil refining and the manufacture of chemicals and
plastics.
   In June, BP announced plans to spend $255 million to replace its
Forties oil pipeline with a bigger one able to handle up to 900,000
barrels a day.
   On Nov. 2, Mobil Oil Co. Ltd. announced plans to spend $474
million on building a North Sea gas pipeline and onshore processing
plant at St. Fergus in northeast Scotland. The Mobil Corp.
subsidiary said the 210-mile pipeline will carry gas to the plant
from Mobil's Beryl oil and gas field in the North Sea.
</TEXT>
