<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-JunkBonds-Mergers     11-17 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Junk Bonds-Mergers,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Junk Bond Sales For Mergers Dropped By More Than Half, Magazine Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The percentage of mergers funded by junk
bonds dropped by more than half in the first nine months of the
year, Mergers &amp; Acquisitions magazine said Thursday.
   Junk bonds, which many buyers have viewed with caution in recent
months, were used to finance only 8.5 percent of the $133.3 billion
worth of mergers in the first three quarters of the year, said
Martin Sikora, editor of Mergers &amp; Acquisitions, which says it has
followed 39,000 deals since 1979.
   In the first nine months of last year, junk bonds were sold to
raise 19.5 percent of the $132.9 billion worth of deals, the
Philadelphia-based magazine said.
   More than $11.3 billion worth of junk bonds were sold as part of
mergers in the first nine months of 1989, while nearly $25.9
billion were sold to finance acquisitions in the same period last
year.
   Owners of junk, or low-grade, bonds accept a higher risk of
default in exchange for the high yields offered by the securities.
</TEXT>
